export const AIES_LABS = [{"id":"lab1","n":1,"cat":"E","title":"Ollama — The Local Model Engine","tagline":"Install Ollama and run a real open-weight AI model entirely on your own computer, offline, with your data never leaving the machine.","whatItIs":"Ollama is a small, free program that runs open-weight AI language models directly on your own computer instead of on a company's servers. Think of it as the \"engine\" that downloads a model's files, loads them into memory, and lets you chat with the model — either by typing in a terminal or through other apps that connect to it. It handles the hard parts (hardware setup, memory management, model packaging) automatically, so you just pick a model by name and go. When it is running, Ollama also quietly offers a local \"API\" at the web address http://localhost:11434, which is how other tools on your computer talk to it.","whyUseIt":"Running a model locally means your text never leaves your computer, so nothing is sent to a third party, retained, or used for training — which matters enormously in education where student records (FERPA) and health data (HIPAA) make local the safer default for anything identifiable. It is also effectively free: open-weight models like Gemma, Llama, and Qwen cost roughly $0 per use once downloaded, versus per-token or subscription fees for cloud services. Use it when you want privacy, offline access, unlimited experimentation, or a backend for other local AI tools. Be honest about the trade-off: local models are smaller and weaker than frontier cloud systems on the hardest reasoning, coding, and factual tasks, so you must verify their answers — and running a model locally does not by itself make your workflow legally compliant. Local complements the cloud; it does not replace it.","bestFor":"A non-technical beginner who wants to try a private, offline AI model on their own laptop for the first time, and anyone who needs a free local backend that other AI tools can connect to.","platforms":["Windows","macOS","Linux"],"prerequisites":["A computer running Windows 10/11, macOS 14 (Sonoma) or newer, or Linux.","At least 8 GB of RAM (memory). 8 GB comfortably runs small 3B-8B models like Gemma 4 e4B or Llama 3.x 8B; 16-24 GB runs larger 12B-32B models. On a Mac this is 'unified memory'; on a Windows/Linux PC with an NVIDIA graphics card it is 'VRAM'.","About 10-15 GB of free disk space for the program plus your first model (each model is a few gigabytes).","A stable internet connection for the one-time download of Ollama and your first model. After that, models run fully offline.","No account, sign-up, credit card, or coding experience is required.","Permission to install software on the computer (an administrator account)."],"steps":[{"title":"Download the Ollama installer","detail":"Ollama is a free program you download once. This step just gets the installer file onto your computer.","do":["Open your web browser — Chrome, Edge, Safari, or Firefox.","Click the address bar at the very top, type  ollama.com/download , and press Enter.","The page detects your computer automatically. Click the big download button for your system (Windows gives you a file called OllamaSetup.exe; Mac gives you Ollama.dmg).","Wait for it to finish — watch the little download bar at the bottom of the browser, or check your Downloads folder."],"commands":[],"check":"a finished installer file (a few hundred megabytes) is sitting in your Downloads folder."},{"title":"Install Ollama","detail":"Now you run that installer. Follow the line for your computer.","do":["Windows: double-click OllamaSetup.exe in your Downloads folder. If a blue “Windows protected your PC” box appears, click “More info” then “Run anyway” — this is normal for any newly downloaded app, not a sign it's unsafe. Click through and let it finish.","Mac: double-click Ollama.dmg, drag the Ollama icon onto the Applications folder, then open Ollama from Applications and click “Open” if asked to confirm.","Linux: skip the browser download — open a terminal and paste the command below instead.","After it installs, Ollama starts running quietly in the background on its own."],"commands":["curl -fsSL https://ollama.com/install.sh | sh"],"check":"a small llama icon appears — bottom-right near the clock on Windows, or top-right in the menu bar on Mac."},{"title":"Open your terminal","detail":"A “terminal” is just a plain window where you type commands instead of clicking. You don't need to be technical — you'll only copy and paste.","do":["Windows: click the Start button, type  powershell , and click “Windows PowerShell” (or “Terminal”) in the results.","Mac: press Command (⌘) and the Spacebar together, type  terminal , and press Enter.","Linux: open the app called “Terminal”.","Leave this window open — you'll use it for the next few steps."],"commands":[],"check":"a dark window opens with a blinking cursor, waiting for you to type."},{"title":"Check that Ollama installed correctly","detail":"A quick five-second test before you download a model.","do":["Click once inside the terminal window so it's active.","Type the command below exactly, then press Enter."],"commands":["ollama --version"],"check":"you see a line like  ollama version is 0.x.x . If instead it says “command not found” or “not recognized,” close the terminal, open a fresh one (Step 3), and try again — terminals only notice newly-installed programs when freshly opened."},{"title":"Download and chat with your first model","detail":"This downloads a real AI model (Google's Gemma) and drops you straight into a chat with it. The download happens only once.","do":["Type the command below and press Enter.","The first time, a progress bar fills as the model downloads (a few gigabytes — a good moment for a coffee). This only happens once.","When you see a  >>>  prompt, the model is loaded and ready.","Type a question like  Explain photosynthesis in two sentences.  and press Enter."],"commands":["ollama run gemma4"],"check":"the model types a real answer back to you — generated entirely on your own computer, with no internet needed."},{"title":"Give the model a bigger memory (optional)","detail":"“Context length” is how much text the model can hold in mind at once — bigger lets it read longer documents but uses more memory. You can change it live, without restarting.","do":["While still at the  >>>  prompt, type the first command to raise the memory to about 8,000 words.","Type the second command to see the model's details — its size, how it's compressed, and the current context length."],"commands":["/set parameter num_ctx 8192","/show info"],"check":"“/show info” prints a block of details that includes the larger context length you just set."},{"title":"Leave the chat and see your models","detail":"How to exit a chat and keep track of what you've downloaded.","do":["To leave the chat, type  /bye  and press Enter (or hold Ctrl and press C).","Back at the normal prompt, run the two commands below: the first lists every model you've downloaded; the second shows which ones are loaded in memory right now."],"commands":["/bye","ollama list","ollama ps"],"check":"“ollama list” shows  gemma4  in a small table."},{"title":"Confirm the local engine is running","detail":"Ollama quietly runs a tiny local web service so other apps (chat interfaces, coding assistants) can talk to it. “localhost” means “this computer only” — it never touches the internet.","do":["Open your web browser again.","Type  http://localhost:11434  in the address bar and press Enter."],"commands":[],"check":"a nearly-blank page shows the words  Ollama is running . That means other local AI tools can now connect to it. If the page won't load, check that the llama icon is still showing in your tray or menu bar."},{"title":"Try a model sized to your computer (optional)","detail":"You're not stuck with one model. Pick one that fits your memory, and download it now to use later.","do":["On 8 GB of RAM, stay with small models:  gemma4 ,  llama3.1 , or  phi4-mini .","With 16–24 GB, try a larger 12B model or a Qwen model — stronger, but slower.","The “pull” command below downloads a model without starting a chat. Swap the name for any model from  ollama.com/library ."],"commands":["ollama pull llama3.1"],"check":"the new model appears when you run  ollama list ."}],"resources":[{"label":"Ollama official website and download page","url":"https://ollama.com/download"},{"label":"Ollama model library (browse every model and its sizes)","url":"https://ollama.com/library"},{"label":"Ollama official documentation and quickstart","url":"https://docs.ollama.com"},{"label":"Ollama source code and README on GitHub","url":"https://github.com/ollama/ollama"},{"label":"Video search phrase: 'Ollama install and run first model beginner tutorial 2026'"},{"label":"Video search phrase: 'Ollama localhost 11434 API explained for beginners'"}],"cloudTieIn":"If you already use Microsoft Copilot, Anthropic Claude, OpenAI ChatGPT, or Google Gemini, think of Ollama as a private, offline complement rather than a replacement. Those cloud tools are more powerful on the hardest reasoning, coding, and up-to-date factual tasks, so keep reaching for them when you need maximum capability or the latest knowledge — but never paste identifiable student, patient, or confidential data into them without checking your organization's policy. Ollama is where you handle sensitive or private text, work offline, or experiment endlessly without per-message costs. Importantly, the local API at http://localhost:11434 mirrors the same request-and-response pattern the cloud providers use, so once you learn to point a tool at Ollama, you understand how the same tool would point at a cloud model instead — the workflow transfers directly.","troubleshooting":[{"symptom":"In the terminal you see 'ollama: command not found' or ''ollama' is not recognized'.","fix":"The terminal was already open before you installed Ollama, so it does not know the program exists yet. Close the terminal window completely and open a brand-new one, then try the command again. On Windows, also confirm the install finished and the llama icon is in the system tray."},{"symptom":"The page at http://localhost:11434 will not load or the browser says 'connection refused'.","fix":"The background service is not running. Look for the llama icon in your system tray (Windows, bottom-right) or menu bar (Mac, top-right). If it is missing, open the Ollama app from your Start menu or Applications folder to start it, then reload the page. On Linux, run 'ollama serve' in a terminal."},{"symptom":"The model crashes, quits, or shows an 'out of memory' error when it loads.","fix":"The model is too big for your RAM/VRAM. Exit with /bye and use a smaller model — on 8 GB choose gemma4, phi4-mini, or llama3.1 (8B). Also lower the context length with '/set parameter num_ctx 2048' and close other heavy apps (browsers with many tabs, video editors) to free memory."},{"symptom":"The very first reply is extremely slow or seems frozen.","fix":"This is normal on the first message: the model is being loaded from disk into memory, which takes several seconds to a minute depending on size and hardware. Wait — following messages in the same session are much faster because the model stays loaded. If every message is painfully slow, switch to a smaller model."},{"symptom":"The download bar for a model stalls, fails, or shows a network error.","fix":"This is a normal internet hiccup. Just run the same 'ollama run' or 'ollama pull' command again — Ollama resumes the download where it left off rather than starting over. Check that you are online and not behind a firewall or VPN that blocks the download."},{"symptom":"You get an error that says the port 11434 is already in use.","fix":"Ollama is likely already running in the background, which is fine — you do not need to start a second copy. Just proceed to use 'ollama run'. If a different program truly holds the port, quit Ollama from the tray/menu-bar icon and reopen it, or restart the computer to clear the stuck port."}],"tips":["Pause after any command instead of retyping it: press the Up arrow key in the terminal to bring back your last command, so you do not have to type 'ollama run gemma4' from scratch each time.","Match the model to your memory. As a rule of thumb, 8 GB comfortably runs 3B-8B models, 16-24 GB runs 12B-32B, and only 40 GB+ machines run ~70B models. Q4 quantization roughly halves the memory a model needs, which is why laptops can run these at all.","'Open weight' is not the same as 'open training data'. Before using a model for anything you will publish or rely on, glance at its model card and license on ollama.com/library — licenses like Apache-2.0 (Qwen, gpt-oss) are the most permissive.","Always verify a local model's answers, especially facts, math, code, and anything high-stakes. Smaller local models make confident mistakes; treat them as a fast draft, not a final authority.","Keep the '/save' and '/clear' slash commands in mind: inside a chat, '/clear' wipes the conversation memory to start fresh, and '/save myname' stores the session so you can '/load myname' later.","Running locally protects your data, but it does not automatically make you FERPA- or HIPAA-compliant. Compliance also depends on your device's security, storage, and your institution's policies — local is the safer default, not an automatic guarantee."],"difficulty":"Beginner — no coding or IT experience needed","time":"About 15 minutes"},{"id":"lab2","n":2,"cat":"E","title":"LM Studio — The Desktop Playground","tagline":"Install LM Studio, download your first open-weight AI model from Hugging Face, chat with it privately on your own computer, tune the GPU slider, and turn it into a local API server — all with zero coding.","whatItIs":"LM Studio is a free desktop app (a program you install and open by clicking an icon, like Zoom or Chrome) that lets you download and chat with AI language models that run entirely on your own computer. It gives you a friendly chat window that looks a lot like ChatGPT, plus a built-in store to search and download thousands of free \"open-weight\" models from Hugging Face (a huge public library of AI models). Because the model runs on your machine, nothing you type is ever sent to the internet. It also has a one-click \"server\" mode that lets other apps talk to your local model, and live meters showing how hard your computer is working.","whyUseIt":"It is the single easiest on-ramp for a non-technical person to run a real AI model locally — no terminal, no config files, just point and click. Privacy is the headline benefit: your prompts, documents, and any student or patient information never leave your computer, which matters for FERPA-protected student records and HIPAA-protected health data where sending identifiable data to a cloud service is risky. Cost is the second benefit: open-weight models like Gemma, Qwen, and Llama run for roughly $0 per use, versus per-token or monthly cloud fees. Use it when you want to experiment freely, work offline, or handle sensitive data. Be honest about the trade-off, though: local models are smaller and weaker on the hardest reasoning, math, and coding tasks than frontier cloud tools, so always verify important answers — and running a model locally does not by itself make your workflow legally compliant.","bestFor":"A complete beginner, educator, or privacy-conscious user who wants a rich, ChatGPT-like visual chat experience running fully offline on their own laptop or desktop, with no terminal and no coding.","platforms":["Windows (x64 and ARM64)","macOS (Apple Silicon — M1/M2/M3/M4)","Linux (x64)"],"prerequisites":["A computer running Windows 10/11, macOS on Apple Silicon (M-series chip), or x64 Linux. Older Intel Macs are not supported by current LM Studio.","At least 8 GB of RAM (memory). 16 GB or more is much more comfortable and lets you run larger, smarter models.","Roughly 10-20 GB of free disk space to start — AI model files are large (a single small model is often 2-6 GB) and you may download several.","A stable internet connection for the one-time download of the app (~400 MB) and your first model. After that, chatting works fully offline.","About 20-30 minutes, most of which is waiting for the model file to download.","No account, no credit card, no terminal, and no coding required. LM Studio is free."],"steps":[{"title":"Find out how much memory your computer has (so you pick a model that fits)","detail":"Checking how much memory (RAM) your computer has tells you which size of AI model will run smoothly. This is just a quick look — you won't change anything.","do":["On Windows, press the Ctrl, Shift, and Esc keys together to open Task Manager.","On Windows, click the 'Performance' tab on the left, then click 'Memory'.","On Windows, read the total shown at the top right (for example '16.0 GB').","On a Mac, click the Apple logo in the very top-left corner of the screen and choose 'About This Mac'.","On a Mac, read the number on the 'Memory' line.","Write this number down — with 4-bit (Q4) models, 8 GB comfortably runs 3B–8B models (like Gemma 4 e4B, Llama 3.x 8B, or Phi-4-mini), 16–24 GB runs 12B–32B models, and 40 GB+ can reach ~70B models."],"commands":[],"check":"you have your computer's total memory written down and know roughly which model sizes it can handle."},{"title":"Download the LM Studio installer from the official site","detail":"LM Studio is a free desktop app you install once. This step just downloads the installer file onto your computer.","do":["Open your web browser — Chrome, Edge, or Safari.","Click the address bar at the top, type  lmstudio.ai , and press Enter.","On the LM Studio homepage, click the big 'Download' button.","If the site offers a choice, pick Windows, macOS (Apple Silicon), or Linux to match your computer.","Wait for the roughly 400 MB file to finish — watch the download bar at the bottom of the browser or your Downloads folder."],"commands":[],"check":"a finished installer file named something like 'LM-Studio-x.y.z.exe' (Windows) or 'LM-Studio-x.y.z.dmg' (Mac) is in your Downloads folder."},{"title":"Install the app and open it","detail":"Now you run the installer to put LM Studio on your computer and open it for the first time.","do":["Open your Downloads folder and double-click the file you just downloaded.","On Windows, click 'Next' / 'Install' in the installer window and accept the defaults.","On Windows, if a blue 'Windows protected your PC' box appears, click 'More info' then 'Run anyway' (this is safe because you downloaded from the official site).","On a Mac, drag the LM Studio icon onto the 'Applications' folder shown in the window.","On a Mac, open Launchpad or your Applications folder and click LM Studio to launch it; if macOS warns the app is from the internet, click 'Open'."],"commands":[],"check":"the LM Studio window opens with a dark interface and a left-hand sidebar of icons."},{"title":"Open the Discover tab and search Hugging Face for your first model","detail":"The Discover tab is LM Studio's built-in store that searches Hugging Face's huge public library of free AI models. Here you'll search for your first one.","do":["In the left sidebar, click the 'Discover' tab (a compass/magnifying-glass icon), or press Ctrl+2 on Windows/Linux or Cmd+2 on a Mac.","Click the search box at the top.","Type a model family name — for your first model, type  gemma  (or  llama  or  qwen ).","Look near the top for 'Staff Picks' — models the LM Studio team has tested, which are safe beginner choices."],"commands":["gemma"],"check":"a scrollable list of matching models appears with download buttons on the right."},{"title":"Choose the right quantization (Q4) and download the model","detail":"Each model comes in several compressed versions called 'quantizations.' You'll pick the 4-bit (Q4) version — the best balance of size, speed, and quality — and download it.","do":["Click a model in the list to expand its download options.","Look at the version labels like Q3_K_S, Q4_K_M, Q6_K, Q8 — lower numbers are smaller and faster, higher numbers are larger and slightly more accurate.","Pick the 4-bit option, usually labeled Q4_K_M.","Watch for LM Studio's note like 'full GPU offload possible', or a warning if a file is too big for your machine, and heed it.","Click the blue 'Download' button next to your chosen Q4 version and wait — a 3B–8B Q4 model is typically 2–6 GB and can take several minutes."],"commands":[],"check":"the download reaches 100% and the model appears under 'My Models'."},{"title":"Load the model and send your first message","detail":"Now you'll load the model you downloaded into memory and send it a test question. Its reply is generated entirely on your computer.","do":["Click the 'Chat' tab in the left sidebar (a speech-bubble icon), or press Ctrl+1 / Cmd+1.","At the top of the chat window, click the model selector that says 'Select a model to load'.","Choose the model you just downloaded and wait a few seconds to a minute while it loads.","Click in the message box at the bottom, type  Explain what a firewall does in two sentences.  and press Enter."],"commands":["Explain what a firewall does in two sentences."],"check":"the model types a reply back to you, word by word — generated entirely on your computer, with nothing sent to the internet."},{"title":"Tune the GPU offload slider if replies are slow or fail to load","detail":"If the model is slow or won't load, this slider changes how much work goes to your fast graphics card (GPU) versus the slower CPU.","do":["Open the settings for the loaded model — click the small gear/settings icon near the model name at the top of the Chat tab, or the settings panel on the right.","Find the 'GPU Offload' slider (sometimes shown as 'GPU Layers').","If you have a capable GPU and want faster replies, drag the slider toward the maximum.","If the model crashed or ran out of memory, drag the slider DOWN so fewer layers use the GPU.","Click the reload button to reload the model, then try your prompt again."],"commands":[],"check":"replies come faster, or a model that previously failed now loads."},{"title":"Turn LM Studio into a local API server (optional, for connecting other apps)","detail":"Optionally, LM Studio can act as a private, offline version of the OpenAI API so other programs on your computer can use your local model. This step turns that on.","do":["Click the 'Developer' or 'Local Server' tab in the left sidebar (a terminal '>_' icon).","Make sure your model is selected at the top.","Click the 'Start Server' toggle — the server now listens at http://localhost:1234 ('localhost' means this computer, and 1234 is the port it uses).","To confirm it's alive, open a browser and visit  http://localhost:1234/v1/models , which should return a small list of loaded models in plain text."],"commands":["http://localhost:1234/v1/models"],"check":"the server panel shows a green 'Running' status and the URL responds with a list of models."},{"title":"Try side-by-side and load a second model to compare","detail":"To feel the difference between models, you'll download a second one and ask it the same question. Comparing answers is the fastest way to learn which model you prefer.","do":["Go back to Discover (Ctrl+2 / Cmd+2) and download a second, different model — for example a Qwen 3.5 model (strong at following instructions) alongside your Gemma.","In the Chat tab, start a new chat.","Load the second model from the top selector.","Ask it the exact same question you asked the first model.","Watch the live performance meters (tokens-per-second speed and memory use) to see what your hardware can handle."],"commands":[],"check":"you can switch between models and compare their answers and speed."}],"resources":[{"label":"LM Studio official site and download page","url":"https://lmstudio.ai"},{"label":"LM Studio documentation (install, download models, GPU offload, local server)","url":"https://lmstudio.ai/docs"},{"label":"Hugging Face — the public library LM Studio searches for models (browse model cards and licenses)","url":"https://huggingface.co/models"},{"label":"Ollama — the command-line alternative to LM Studio, useful to know for comparison (local API at localhost:11434)","url":"https://ollama.com"},{"label":"Video search phrase: 'LM Studio beginner tutorial 2026 download first model'"},{"label":"Video search phrase: 'LM Studio quantization explained Q4 vs Q8 GPU offload'"}],"cloudTieIn":"Think of LM Studio as a private, offline sibling to the cloud AI tools you may already use — Microsoft Copilot, Anthropic's Claude, OpenAI's ChatGPT, and Google Gemini. Those services run enormous frontier models on someone else's servers, so they are the smartest and best for your hardest tasks, but every prompt you send leaves your computer. LM Studio flips that: a smaller open-weight model runs on your own machine, so sensitive material (student records under FERPA, health data under HIPAA, unreleased work) never travels to a third party — at the cost of some capability. A useful pattern is to draft, brainstorm, and process private data locally in LM Studio, then turn to a cloud tool for the toughest reasoning or a final polish, pasting in only non-sensitive text. Notably, LM Studio's local server speaks the same OpenAI-compatible API format (at http://localhost:1234) that ChatGPT's API uses, so many tools built for OpenAI can be pointed at your local model by just changing the address — the same idea maps directly to the cloud. Local complements the cloud; it does not replace it.","troubleshooting":[{"symptom":"The model won't load and shows an 'out of memory' or 'failed to load model' error.","fix":"The model is too big for your available memory. Load a smaller model (fewer 'B' parameters, e.g. a 3B or 8B instead of a 13B), or choose a lower quantization such as Q4 or Q3 which uses far less memory. Also lower the 'GPU Offload' slider so fewer layers load onto the GPU, then reload. Close other heavy programs (browsers with many tabs, video editors) to free memory."},{"symptom":"Replies come out extremely slowly, one word every few seconds.","fix":"The model is running mostly on your CPU. Open the model's settings and raise the 'GPU Offload' / 'GPU Layers' slider toward maximum so your graphics card does the work, then reload. If you have no capable GPU, switch to a smaller model (3B-8B) or a lower quantization (Q4) — these run acceptably on CPU alone."},{"symptom":"The very first reply after loading a model takes a long time, then later replies are faster.","fix":"This is normal. The first prompt includes loading the model into memory and 'warming up.' Wait it out; subsequent replies in the same chat are much quicker. Keeping the model loaded between questions avoids repeating the warm-up."},{"symptom":"When starting the local server, it says the port is already in use or the server won't start.","fix":"Another program (possibly a second copy of LM Studio) is already using port 1234. In the Local Server tab, change the port number to something else like 1235 and start again, then use that new number in your address (http://localhost:1235). Fully quitting and reopening LM Studio also clears a stuck server."},{"symptom":"An app can't reach the local server — 'connection refused' at localhost:1234.","fix":"The server isn't running or the model isn't loaded. Go to the Local Server / Developer tab, confirm a model is selected at the top, and make sure the 'Start Server' toggle shows a green 'Running' status. Verify the exact port matches (default 1234), and check the address is http://localhost:1234, not https. Test it by opening http://localhost:1234/v1/models in a browser."},{"symptom":"A model download stalls, fails partway, or the Discover tab shows no results.","fix":"This is usually an internet hiccup reaching Hugging Face. Check your connection, then click the download again to resume or restart it. If searches return nothing, confirm you are online and try a simpler keyword like 'gemma' or 'llama'. A corporate or school firewall can block Hugging Face — try a different network if downloads consistently fail."}],"tips":["Start small, then size up. Get a 3B-8B Q4 model working first so you have a win, then experiment with bigger models once you know your machine's limits from the live memory meter.","Match quantization to your hardware: Q4_K_M is the sweet spot for most people. Only reach for Q8 if you have memory to spare and need a slight accuracy bump; drop to Q3 only if you're tight on memory.","Read the model card and license before relying on a model. 'Open weight' (like Qwen, Gemma, Llama, gpt-oss) means you can run it freely, but it does NOT mean the training data is open — licenses and allowed uses vary, so check on the model's Hugging Face page.","Always verify important answers. Local models are smaller than Copilot/Claude/ChatGPT/Gemini and can confidently state wrong facts. Treat their output as a fast first draft, not the final word — especially for anything factual, legal, medical, or graded.","Running locally protects privacy, but it does not automatically make you compliant. FERPA and HIPAA still require proper handling, access controls, and policies even when data never leaves your machine — local is the safer default, not a legal guarantee."],"difficulty":"Beginner — no coding or IT experience needed","time":"About 20–30 minutes"},{"id":"lab3","n":3,"cat":"E","title":"Open-WebUI — A Premium Local Interface","tagline":"Install Open-WebUI on your own computer to get a polished, ChatGPT-style chat interface — complete with saved chat history, custom prompt presets, and vision uploads — that talks only to AI models running locally on your machine.","whatItIs":"Open-WebUI is a free, open-source web application that looks and feels like ChatGPT or Claude, but instead of sending your messages to a company's cloud, it points at an AI model running on your own computer. It runs as a small local website you open in your normal web browser at an address like http://localhost:3000. \"Local\" here means the AI engine (Ollama) and the interface both live on your machine, so your typing, uploaded files, and chat history stay on your hardware. Open-WebUI is only the pretty front door; a separate program called Ollama is the actual engine that loads and runs the model behind it.","whyUseIt":"A raw local model in a terminal window is powerful but ugly and hard to use; Open-WebUI wraps it in a modern interface with saved conversations, a searchable chat history, reusable prompt presets, drag-and-drop image (vision) input, and multi-user accounts with admin permission controls — the same conveniences you expect from a paid cloud tool, but running for essentially $0 per message once installed. Use it when you want a team or a classroom to share a familiar chat experience without any data leaving the building: for a college program this matters because student records (FERPA) and any health data (HIPAA) are far safer when identifiable information never travels to a third party's servers. It is also the right choice when you want to hand a non-technical person a friendly window instead of a command line. Be honest about the trade-off, though: a model small enough to run on a laptop is genuinely weaker than frontier cloud models on the hardest reasoning, coding, and factual tasks, so you must verify important answers, and running software locally is not the same as being automatically FERPA- or HIPAA-compliant — the interface helps, but policy and configuration still matter.","bestFor":"A college program or small team that wants a shared, ChatGPT-style chat interface for local models — with saved histories, prompt presets, and per-user accounts — while keeping student data and files entirely on their own machines.","platforms":["Windows","macOS","Linux","Browser (the interface opens in Chrome, Edge, Safari, or Firefox)"],"prerequisites":["Ollama must be installed and working FIRST — Open-WebUI is only the interface; Ollama is the engine that actually runs the model. If you have not done the Ollama lab yet, do that part (Steps 1-3 below walk you through it).","At least one model already downloaded through Ollama (for example gemma or llama3.1:8b). Step 3 does this.","About 8 GB of RAM (memory) runs a small 3B-8B model comfortably; 16-24 GB lets you run 12B-32B models. On a Mac this is 'unified memory'; on a Windows/Linux PC with an NVIDIA graphics card it is 'VRAM'.","Roughly 10-15 GB of free disk space: a few GB for the model file, plus a couple GB for Docker or the Python packages.","For the easiest install path (Method A): Docker Desktop installed and running. For the no-Docker path (Method B): Python 3.11 installed. You need only ONE of these, not both.","A modern web browser (Chrome or Edge recommended for this program) — you already have one."],"steps":[{"title":"Open a terminal (the text-command window) — this is where you type commands","detail":"A terminal is a plain window where you type commands instead of clicking buttons. You'll use it a few times, so you'll open it now and keep it open.","do":["On Windows, click the Start menu, type 'PowerShell', and click 'Windows PowerShell' when it appears.","On a Mac, press Command+Space to open Spotlight, type 'Terminal', and press Enter.","On Linux, press Ctrl+Alt+T.","Leave this window open — you'll paste commands into it, and 'running' a command means typing it and pressing Enter."],"commands":[],"check":"a window with a blinking cursor is open, waiting for you to type."},{"title":"Install Ollama (the engine that runs the AI model)","detail":"Open-WebUI is just the pretty interface — Ollama is the engine that actually runs the AI model underneath it. This step installs Ollama.","do":["In your web browser, go to  https://ollama.com/download  and click the button for your system (Windows, macOS, or Linux).","On Windows, double-click the .exe installer and click through the prompts like any normal program.","On a Mac, open the downloaded .zip and drag the Ollama app into your Applications folder, then launch it once.","In your terminal, run  ollama --version  to confirm it installed.","Remember the address  http://localhost:11434  — Ollama quietly runs a local service there, and Open-WebUI will connect to it."],"commands":["ollama --version"],"check":"the terminal prints a version number such as 'ollama version 0.x.x'."},{"title":"Download one AI model with Ollama so there is something to chat with","detail":"A model is the actual AI 'brain' — a large file Ollama loads to answer you. You'll download one sized to fit your computer's memory.","do":["Decide which model fits your memory — on 8 GB use a small 8B model like Llama 3.1; on 16 GB+ you can use a 12B model like Gemma.","In your terminal, run  ollama pull llama3.1:8b  (or  ollama pull gemma ).","Wait several minutes while the multi-gigabyte download's progress bar fills in the terminal.","If it drops you into a chat, type  /bye  and press Enter to leave."],"commands":["ollama pull llama3.1:8b","ollama pull gemma"],"check":"it finishes with 'success' and returns you to a prompt — that model is now stored on your machine."},{"title":"Choose your install method, then install Docker Desktop OR Python (you need only one)","detail":"There are two ways to install Open-WebUI, and you only need one. Method A uses Docker (recommended, most reliable); Method B uses Python if you already have version 3.11.","do":["Choose Method A (Docker, recommended) or Method B (Python).","For Method A, go to  https://www.docker.com/products/docker-desktop/ , download Docker Desktop for your system, and install it.","For Method A, LAUNCH Docker Desktop and wait until its whale icon shows 'running' (it must be actively running for the next step).","For Method B, run  python --version  in your terminal and confirm it says 3.11.x (3.12 also works, but 3.11 is safest)."],"commands":["python --version"],"check":"either Docker Desktop is open and shows 'running', OR 'python --version' prints 3.11.x."},{"title":"METHOD A — Start Open-WebUI with one Docker command","detail":"If you chose Docker, this single command downloads Open-WebUI and starts it in a tidy self-contained box. (If you chose Method B instead, skip this step and do Step 6.)","do":["Make sure Docker Desktop is open and showing 'running'.","Paste the command below into your terminal and press Enter.","Wait several minutes on the first run while it downloads a large image.","Once it finishes, skip Step 6 and go to Step 7."],"commands":["docker run -d -p 3000:8080 --add-host=host.docker.internal:host-gateway -v open-webui:/app/backend/data --name open-webui --restart always ghcr.io/open-webui/open-webui:main"],"check":"the command finishes and prints a long string of letters and numbers (the container ID) with no red error text."},{"title":"METHOD B — Start Open-WebUI with Python instead (skip if you did Step 5)","detail":"Only do this if you chose the no-Docker path. These two commands install Open-WebUI and start it as a local website.","do":["In your terminal, run  pip install open-webui  and wait a few minutes while it downloads many Python packages.","Then run  open-webui serve  to start it.","Leave the terminal window open — closing it stops the app.","Note that with Method B your address is  http://localhost:8080  (8080, not 3000)."],"commands":["pip install open-webui","open-webui serve"],"check":"the terminal prints startup lines ending with a message that the server is running on port 8080, and the window stays busy."},{"title":"Open the interface in your browser and create the FIRST account (it becomes the admin)","detail":"Now you'll open Open-WebUI in your browser and create your account. The very first account automatically becomes the administrator — this is normal and only happens once.","do":["Open your web browser and click the address bar at the top.","For Method A (Docker), type  http://localhost:3000 ; for Method B (Python), type  http://localhost:8080 , then press Enter.","On the sign-up screen, enter a name, an email (any email works, even a made-up one — it's stored only on your machine), and a password you'll remember.","Click 'Create Admin Account'."],"commands":[],"check":"a clean chat screen that looks a lot like ChatGPT appears, with a model picker near the top."},{"title":"Pick your model and send your first message to confirm everything is connected","detail":"This step confirms Open-WebUI can see Ollama by picking your model and sending a test message.","do":["At the top of the chat screen, click the model dropdown.","Select the model you downloaded in Step 3 (for example 'llama3.1:8b' or 'gemma').","If the dropdown is empty, Open-WebUI can't see Ollama yet — go to Troubleshooting ('Connection refused').","Type  Say hello in one sentence.  and press Enter, then wait 10–60 seconds for the first answer as the model loads."],"commands":[],"check":"words stream back into the chat, one piece at a time — you're now running a private, local AI chat."},{"title":"Create a custom system-prompt preset (a reusable 'personality' or role)","detail":"A system prompt is a hidden instruction that shapes how the model behaves for every message. You'll save one as a reusable preset.","do":["Click your profile icon (bottom-left).","Open 'Admin Panel' or 'Workspace', then 'Models'.","Choose to create a new model preset based on your downloaded model.","Give it a name (for example 'Friendly Tutor').","Paste your instruction into the System Prompt box (for example 'You are a patient tutor for first-year students.') and save."],"commands":[],"check":"'Friendly Tutor' appears in the model dropdown and the model consistently answers in that style when you select it."},{"title":"Manage chat histories and confirm your data is staying local","detail":"Every conversation is saved automatically on your own machine, not in anyone's cloud. This step shows how to manage past chats and proves nothing leaves your computer.","do":["Click any past chat in the left-hand sidebar to reopen it.","Use the search box to find old conversations.","Use the menu on each chat to rename, pin, archive, or delete it.","To prove nothing leaves your computer, disconnect from the internet and confirm the chat still works because the model runs locally.","Remember the caveats: local models are weaker than frontier cloud models, so verify anything important, and 'runs locally' does not by itself make you FERPA- or HIPAA-compliant — follow your institution's policies for real student data."],"commands":[],"check":"you can reopen, search, and organize past chats, and they still work with the internet disconnected."}],"resources":[{"label":"Open-WebUI official documentation and quick-start guide","url":"https://docs.openwebui.com/"},{"label":"Open-WebUI source code and install commands on GitHub","url":"https://github.com/open-webui/open-webui"},{"label":"Ollama — download the local model engine (required first)","url":"https://ollama.com/download"},{"label":"Ollama model library — browse Gemma, Qwen, Llama, and other open-weight models","url":"https://ollama.com/library"},{"label":"Docker Desktop download (for the recommended Method A install)","url":"https://www.docker.com/products/docker-desktop/"},{"label":"Video search phrase: 'Open WebUI Ollama Docker setup beginner tutorial 2026'"},{"label":"Video search phrase: 'Open WebUI create custom model system prompt preset walkthrough'"}],"cloudTieIn":"Open-WebUI is deliberately built to look and feel like the cloud tools you may already use — Microsoft Copilot, Anthropic Claude, OpenAI ChatGPT, and Google Gemini — so the muscle memory transfers: a chat box, a model picker, a history sidebar, and prompt presets. The difference is where the work happens. Those cloud services send your text to a company's servers and run enormous frontier models you could never fit on a laptop; Open-WebUI keeps everything on your machine but is limited to smaller local models. The smart pattern is to use both: reach for a local model in Open-WebUI when the data is sensitive (student records, health information, anything you would not paste into a public website) or when you want zero per-message cost, and still reach for Copilot, Claude, ChatGPT, or Gemini for the hardest reasoning, the largest context, or cutting-edge coding where a frontier model clearly wins. Open-WebUI can even connect to those cloud providers' APIs alongside Ollama, letting one familiar interface switch between a private local model and a powerful cloud model — a concrete example of 'local complements, it does not replace, cloud.'","troubleshooting":[{"symptom":"The model dropdown in Open-WebUI is empty, or you see 'Connection refused' / cannot reach Ollama.","fix":"Ollama is not reachable. First confirm Ollama is running by opening http://localhost:11434 in your browser — it should say 'Ollama is running'. If it does not, relaunch the Ollama app (Windows/Mac) or run 'ollama serve' in a terminal. For the Docker install (Method A), if it still cannot connect, stop and remove the container and re-run it with host networking so the box can see your machine: 'docker rm -f open-webui' then 'docker run -d --network=host -e OLLAMA_BASE_URL=http://127.0.0.1:11434 -v open-webui:/app/backend/data --name open-webui --restart always ghcr.io/open-webui/open-webui:main' (with --network=host the address becomes http://localhost:8080)."},{"symptom":"The browser page won't load at localhost:3000 (or localhost:8080) — 'site can't be reached'.","fix":"The app may not be running or you used the wrong port. Method A (Docker) serves on 3000; Method B (Python) serves on 8080 — use the one matching your install. For Docker, check it is alive with 'docker ps' (you should see 'open-webui' listed); if not, run 'docker start open-webui' or check Docker Desktop is actually running. For Python, make sure the terminal running 'open-webui serve' is still open — closing it stops the server."},{"symptom":"'port is already allocated' or 'address already in use' when starting.","fix":"Another program is using that port. For Docker, change the left number, e.g. use '-p 3001:8080' and then open http://localhost:3001 instead. For the Python method, start it on a different port by setting the PORT value first: on Mac/Linux run 'PORT=8081 open-webui serve' (then use http://localhost:8081); on Windows PowerShell run '$env:PORT=8081; open-webui serve'."},{"symptom":"The model fails to load, the app crashes, or the machine freezes (out of memory).","fix":"The model is too big for your RAM/VRAM. Pull a smaller one and select it — for example 'ollama pull phi4-mini' or a 3B-size model instead of an 8B, and close other heavy apps (browsers with many tabs, video editors). Rule of thumb: 8 GB of memory handles 3B-8B models at Q4; step down a size if it struggles."},{"symptom":"The very first response is extremely slow (30-60+ seconds), then later ones are fine.","fix":"This is normal — the first message loads the whole model into memory. Subsequent replies are much faster because it stays loaded. If EVERY response is slow, the model is likely too large for your hardware or is running on CPU instead of the graphics card; switch to a smaller model, and on a PC make sure your NVIDIA GPU drivers are installed so Ollama can use the GPU."},{"symptom":"Uploading an image does nothing or the model says it cannot see pictures.","fix":"Only multimodal (vision) models can read images. Text-only models like a plain Llama 3.1 8B cannot. Download and select a vision-capable model such as Gemma (which supports images) or another multimodal model listed at ollama.com/library, then attach the image again."}],"tips":["Do the Ollama lab before this one. Open-WebUI is just the face; if Ollama isn't installed and a model isn't pulled, the interface will be empty and confusing.","Method A (Docker) is the most reliable and self-contained choice for a shared classroom machine; Method B (Python) is lighter if you already have Python 3.11 and don't want Docker.","The first account you create is the permanent admin — use a real, trusted person's login for it, and add student/team members afterward as regular users so they can't change system settings.","Save your class's standard instructions as a named model preset (a system-prompt preset) so every student gets the same assistant behavior with one click, instead of retyping instructions each time.","Prove the privacy story to skeptics: turn off Wi-Fi and keep chatting — because both the model and interface run locally, it keeps working, which makes the FERPA/HIPAA advantage concrete. Just remember 'local' is a strong privacy foundation, not automatic legal compliance."],"difficulty":"Intermediate — comfortable installing apps and copy-pasting commands","time":"About 30–45 minutes"},{"id":"lab4","n":4,"cat":"E","title":"Msty — The Power-User Studio","tagline":"Install Msty, point it at your existing Ollama models so you use zero extra disk space, then send one prompt to three local models at once to compare them side by side.","whatItIs":"Msty is a free, polished desktop app that lets you chat with AI models that run entirely on your own computer (and, if you want, cloud models too) through a friendly window instead of a command line. Its standout trick is multi-model chat: you type one question and Msty answers it with two or three different models at the same time, showing the replies in side-by-side columns. It also has \"Personas\" (reusable saved instructions that shape how a model behaves), branching (splitting a conversation into a separate what-if path without losing your original), and Knowledge Stacks (attaching your own documents for the model to read). Think of it as LM Studio's more powerful cousin, aimed at people who want to test, compare, and organize rather than just chat.","whyUseIt":"Msty is the fastest way to see how different local models answer the exact same prompt, which is invaluable for spotting which model is more accurate, more biased, faster, or better suited to your task before you commit to one. Because the models run on your machine, your prompts and any documents you attach never leave the computer, so there is no per-token cost and no third party retaining your data. For a college program this matters for privacy: identifiable student records (FERPA) or health data (HIPAA) are far safer processed locally than pasted into a cloud chatbot. Use Msty when you are evaluating models, benchmarking outputs, or handling sensitive text; reach for cloud tools when you need the absolute strongest reasoning on hard problems. Remember the guiding rule: local complements, it does not replace, cloud, and local is not automatically compliant just because it is offline.","bestFor":"A non-technical learner or educator who wants to compare several local AI models on the same prompt, side by side, without touching the command line — and keep sensitive text on their own machine.","platforms":["Windows","macOS","Linux"],"prerequisites":["A Windows, macOS, or Linux computer with at least 8 GB of RAM (16 GB or more makes larger models and multi-model comparison much smoother).","About 3-5 GB of free disk space for the Msty app itself, plus space for any models (a small 8B model at Q4 is roughly 4-5 GB each).","Ollama already installed with at least one model pulled — this lab reuses that model cache so you do NOT download models twice. If you have not done the Ollama lab yet, do that first, or let Msty download its own models instead.","A stable internet connection for the one-time app and model downloads (everything runs offline afterward).","No coding experience needed — this lab tells you exactly where to click and what to type."],"steps":[{"title":"Confirm Ollama is installed and has a model (so we can reuse it)","detail":"This lab's disk-saving trick reuses the models Ollama already downloaded. First you'll open a terminal and check that Ollama has at least one model.","do":["On Windows, press the Windows key, type 'PowerShell', and click 'Windows PowerShell'.","On macOS, press Command+Space, type 'Terminal', and press Enter.","In the terminal window that opens (a window with a blinking cursor), type  ollama list  and press Enter.","If you see 'command not found' or 'not recognized', Ollama isn't installed — do the Ollama lab first, or skip to Step 6 and let Msty download its own models."],"commands":["ollama list"],"check":"a small table lists at least one model name (for example 'llama3.1:8b' or 'gemma3:4b')."},{"title":"Download the Msty app from the official site","detail":"Msty is a free, polished desktop app. This step downloads the installer from its official site.","do":["Open your web browser and click the address bar at the top.","Type  msty.app  and press Enter (it may redirect to msty.ai — that's the same company, which is fine).","Click the big 'Download' button and choose your operating system: Windows, Mac (Apple Silicon for M1/M2/M3/M4, or Intel if older), or Linux.","Choose the free 'Msty' / local desktop app, not a paid plan — running local models is free."],"commands":[],"check":"a file named something like 'Msty.exe' (Windows) or 'Msty.dmg' (Mac) lands in your Downloads folder."},{"title":"Install and open Msty","detail":"Now you'll install Msty and open it for the first time.","do":["On Windows, double-click the downloaded 'Msty.exe', click 'Yes' if Windows asks permission, then 'Install' and 'Finish'.","On a Mac, double-click the '.dmg', drag the Msty icon onto the 'Applications' folder, then open it from Launchpad or Applications.","On the welcome/onboarding screen, click through it — you'll connect your existing models in the next steps.","If Msty offers to 'Set up Local AI' or download a starter model, you can click through it."],"commands":[],"check":"the Msty main window opens with a chat box in the middle and a sidebar of icons on the left."},{"title":"Point Msty at your existing Ollama models to save disk space","detail":"This is the key disk-saving step: instead of re-downloading gigabytes of models, you tell Msty's built-in engine to read the folder Ollama already filled.","do":["In Msty, click the Settings icon in the left sidebar (the gear), then choose 'Local AI'.","Under the Local AI Service section, find 'Models Path' and click its edit/pencil button.","Paste your Ollama models folder path: on Windows  C:\\Users\\<your-username>\\.ollama\\models  (replace <your-username> with your actual Windows account name); on Mac  /Users/<your-username>/.ollama/models ; on Linux  /usr/share/ollama/.ollama/models .","Save it and let Msty's Local AI service restart automatically."],"commands":["C:\\Users\\<your-username>\\.ollama\\models"],"check":"your Ollama models (the same names you saw in Step 1) appear in Msty's model dropdown with no new download needed."},{"title":"Alternative: connect to Ollama as a running provider (localhost:11434)","detail":"Instead of sharing the folder in Step 4, you can keep Ollama running as a separate program and have Msty talk to it. Use EITHER Step 4 or this step — you don't need both.","do":["Make sure Ollama is running (on Windows and Mac it usually runs quietly in the background after install).","In Msty, go to Settings, then 'Model Providers' (or 'Remote Model Providers').","Add or enable an 'Ollama' provider with the endpoint  http://localhost:11434  ('localhost' means this same computer, and '11434' is the port Ollama listens on).","Click Connect/Save."],"commands":["http://localhost:11434"],"check":"your Ollama models appear in Msty's model list."},{"title":"Send your first prompt and confirm a local model answers","detail":"Now you'll pick one of your local models and send it a test question to confirm it answers entirely on your own computer.","do":["On the main chat screen, click the model selector near the top of the chat box.","Pick one of your local models (for example a Gemma 3 4B or Llama 3.1 8B, which run comfortably on 8 GB of RAM at Q4).","Type  Explain what a firewall does in two sentences.  and press Enter.","Wait 10–40 seconds for the first answer while the model loads into memory; later answers are faster."],"commands":[],"check":"readable text streams into the chat, generated entirely on your computer."},{"title":"Turn on multi-model chat to compare models side by side","detail":"This is Msty's signature feature: you ask one question and two or three models answer at once in side-by-side columns.","do":["In an open chat, look next to the model name for a '+' (add model) icon or a 'split'/'multi-model' control, and click it to add a second model.","Click again to add a third model.","Pick a different model for each column (for example Gemma 3, Llama 3.1, and Qwen 3 if you have them).","Type ONE prompt — try  List three risks of using AI to grade student essays.  — and press Enter."],"commands":[],"check":"all selected models answer the same question at the same time in parallel columns, so you can read them next to each other."},{"title":"Create a Persona and a branched conversation","detail":"A Persona is a saved instruction that makes a model behave a certain way every time. Branching copies a conversation so you can try a different path without losing the original.","do":["Find 'Personas' in the left sidebar or the model area and click 'New Persona'.","Give it a name like 'Plain-English Tutor'.","In its instruction box, write something like 'You are a patient tutor. Explain every answer in simple language a first-year student understands, and define any jargon.' and save it.","Select that Persona for a chat.","To branch, hover over one of your messages in an existing conversation and choose 'Branch' (or the branch/split icon)."],"commands":[],"check":"a new branched conversation you can switch between appears, and the Persona visibly changes the model's tone."},{"title":"Verify everything is truly local and organize your work","detail":"Finally, you'll prove the models run offline and tidy up your chats.","do":["Turn off your Wi-Fi or unplug the network cable.","Send a prompt to a local model — it should still answer normally (only cloud providers would fail).","Reconnect to the internet when done.","Use Msty's folders to group related chats, and save prompts you reuse into the prompt library.","Remember local models are weaker than frontier cloud models on the hardest reasoning tasks, and running locally does not by itself make you FERPA- or HIPAA-compliant."],"commands":[],"check":"a local model still answers with your network disconnected, and your chats are organized into folders."}],"resources":[{"label":"Msty official website and download","url":"https://msty.app"},{"label":"Msty documentation (getting started, onboarding, guides)","url":"https://docs.msty.app"},{"label":"Msty guide: connect to and reuse existing Ollama models","url":"https://docs.msty.app/how-to-guides/use-existing-ollama-models"},{"label":"Ollama official site (install the local model engine Msty can share)","url":"https://ollama.com"},{"label":"Video search phrase: 'Msty multi-model chat side by side comparison tutorial for beginners'"}],"cloudTieIn":"Msty is deliberately model-agnostic, so it can sit in front of both your local models and the same frontier cloud services you may already use — Anthropic Claude, OpenAI ChatGPT, and Google Gemini — by adding their API keys under Model Providers. That means you can run the SAME prompt against a local Llama or Gemma model AND against Claude or Gemini in adjacent columns and directly see the quality gap, which is the honest way to decide when a task needs the cloud. A practical workflow: draft, iterate, and handle any sensitive or identifiable text locally in Msty (where nothing leaves your machine), then escalate only the genuinely hard reasoning to Claude or ChatGPT. If you use Microsoft Copilot, think of Msty as your private lab bench for testing open-weight models before trusting a workflow — Copilot stays your polished cloud assistant, Msty proves what you can do without sending data out. Local complements, it does not replace, cloud.","troubleshooting":[{"symptom":"Your Ollama models do not show up in Msty after setting the Models Path.","fix":"Double-check the path is exact and uses your real username (on Windows the folder is hidden — .ollama starts with a dot). Fully quit and reopen Msty so the Local AI service restarts, then open the model dropdown again. If still missing, use Step 5 instead: connect to Ollama live at http://localhost:11434."},{"symptom":"Connection refused or 'cannot connect to Ollama' when using the localhost:11434 method.","fix":"Ollama is not running. On Windows/Mac reopen the Ollama app so its background service starts; on Linux run 'ollama serve' in a terminal. Then in a terminal run 'ollama list' to confirm it responds, and click Connect in Msty again. Make sure you typed http://localhost:11434 with no trailing slash or typo."},{"symptom":"The app freezes, the model fails to load, or you see an 'out of memory' error.","fix":"The model is too big for your RAM/VRAM. Pick a smaller model (a 3B-8B model at Q4 fits 8 GB), close other heavy apps like browsers with many tabs, and avoid running three large models in multi-model mode at once on a low-memory machine — start with two small ones."},{"symptom":"The first answer takes a very long time or seems stuck.","fix":"This is normal on the first message because the model must load into memory — wait 30-60 seconds. Subsequent answers are much faster. If it never responds, the model likely exceeded your memory; switch to a smaller model."},{"symptom":"Multi-model chat only answers with one model, or the '+' add-model button is missing.","fix":"Make sure you added a second model to THIS conversation using the add-model/split control next to the model name before sending; some layouts hide it behind a small icon or a right-click menu. If your machine is low on memory, Msty may limit concurrent models — reduce to two smaller models."},{"symptom":"Downloads inside Msty duplicate models you already have in Ollama, wasting disk space.","fix":"That means Msty is downloading into its own folder instead of reading Ollama's. Redo Step 4 to set the Models Path to your existing .ollama/models directory, and download future models through Ollama ('ollama pull <model>') so both apps share one cache."}],"tips":["Always compare at least two models on the same prompt before trusting an answer — disagreement between models is your fastest signal that a claim needs human verification.","Reuse one shared model cache: set Msty's Models Path to Ollama's .ollama/models folder and pull new models with 'ollama pull', so you never store the same multi-gigabyte file twice.","Build a small library of Personas for recurring jobs (a plain-English tutor, a strict fact-checker, a rubric grader) so you get consistent behavior without retyping instructions.","Use branching to explore 'what if' follow-ups — it keeps your original thread clean and is perfect for A/B testing how a wording change affects the answer.","For anything with student or health data, keep it on local models and unplug the network to prove it stays offline, but pair that with your institution's data-handling policy — offline is safer, not automatically compliant."],"difficulty":"Intermediate — comfortable installing apps and copy-pasting commands","time":"About 20–30 minutes"},{"id":"lab5","n":5,"cat":"E","title":"KoboldCpp — Creative Text Sandbox","tagline":"Download one file, load a local GGUF model, and use a private in-browser sandbox to write and experiment with AI text — with granular control over how the model \"thinks.\"","whatItIs":"KoboldCpp is a single downloadable program (one file, no installer) that turns your own computer into a private AI text engine with a built-in web page for chatting and creative writing. It is built on top of the same foundation software (llama.cpp) that powers many local-AI tools, but it packages everything — the AI engine and a friendly control panel — into one executable you just double-click. Because it runs entirely on your machine, nothing you type is ever sent to a company's server. It is especially loved for creative writing, story-telling, and \"raw\" model testing where you want to see and tune exactly how the AI behaves.","whyUseIt":"Use KoboldCpp when you want maximum control over a local model on ordinary consumer hardware — it exposes granular sampling settings (how random or focused the text is), context-window controls (how much the model can \"remember\"), and GPU offloading so you can squeeze a laptop or gaming PC to its limits. It is the right pick for creative and experimental work: drafting fiction, brainstorming, role-play, and comparing how different open-weight models (Llama, Gemma, Qwen) actually respond. The privacy and cost angle is central: your text never leaves the computer (good for FERPA-protected student data or HIPAA-protected health notes), and open-weight models cost roughly $0 per word versus per-token cloud billing. It is portable — one file, \"zero install\" — so you can carry it on a USB drive. It also serves an OpenAI-compatible API locally, so other apps can plug into it just like they would a paid cloud service. The honest caveat: local models are weaker than frontier cloud models on the hardest reasoning and factual tasks, so always verify important output.","bestFor":"A curious, non-technical beginner who wants a private, portable, single-file sandbox for creative writing and hands-on experimenting with how local AI models generate text.","platforms":["Windows","macOS (Apple Silicon)","Linux","Browser (the KoboldCpp UI opens in your web browser)"],"prerequisites":["A Windows PC, an Apple Silicon Mac (M1/M2/M3/M4), or a Linux machine. Windows 10/11 works out of the box.","At least 8 GB of RAM/memory to comfortably run a small model (3B-8B, such as Llama 3.x 8B or Gemma 4 e4B). 16 GB or more lets you run 12B-class models; a dedicated NVIDIA GPU with VRAM makes everything much faster but is optional.","About 6-8 GB of free disk space: KoboldCpp itself is small, but one AI model file (a '.gguf' file) is typically 2-6 GB.","A web browser you already have (Chrome, Edge, Firefox, or Safari) — the KoboldCpp control panel opens as a local web page.","A free Hugging Face account is NOT required to download most models, but having one avoids occasional download limits. No account, no sign-up, and no payment is needed for KoboldCpp itself.","This lab is fully standalone — you do NOT need Ollama or any other tool installed first."],"steps":[{"title":"Open your web browser and go to the official download page","detail":"KoboldCpp isn't in an app store — you download one file from its official GitHub 'Releases' page. This step opens that page.","do":["Click your browser's address bar (the long box at the top where web addresses go).","Type  https://github.com/LostRuins/koboldcpp/releases/latest  exactly and press Enter.","Confirm you landed on the official page — don't download KoboldCpp from random mirror sites."],"commands":["https://github.com/LostRuins/koboldcpp/releases/latest"],"check":"a GitHub page whose title starts with 'KoboldCpp v...' (for example 'KoboldCpp v1.116.1') is open."},{"title":"Download the ONE correct file for your computer","detail":"This page lists several files, but you need exactly one that matches your computer. It's large because the whole AI engine is packed inside it.","do":["Scroll down to the section called 'Assets' and click the word 'Assets' if the list is collapsed.","On Windows, click  koboldcpp.exe .","On an Apple Silicon Mac, click  koboldcpp-mac-arm64 .","On Linux, click  koboldcpp-linux-x64 .","If Windows warns 'this file isn't commonly downloaded,' choose 'Keep' — this is normal for niche open-source tools."],"commands":[],"check":"the single file (often 300–600 MB) finishes downloading in your Downloads folder."},{"title":"Download a model — the AI 'brain' file (a .gguf file)","detail":"KoboldCpp is only the engine; it needs a model file to think with. You'll download one GGUF model file sized to your memory, choosing a Q4 (4-bit) version for the best balance.","do":["In a new browser tab, go to  https://huggingface.co/models?search=Q4_K_M%20GGUF .","Pick ONE model that fits your memory — for 8 GB RAM a small 8B model like Llama 3.1 8B or Gemma; for 16 GB+ a 12B model.","On the model's page, open the 'Files and versions' tab.","Click a file ending in '.gguf' with 'Q4_K_M' in its name (for example 'Meta-Llama-3.1-8B-Instruct-Q4_K_M.gguf') and click the download arrow.","Note where it saved — you'll point KoboldCpp at it next."],"commands":["https://huggingface.co/models?search=Q4_K_M%20GGUF"],"check":"a single .gguf file (2–6 GB) is in your Downloads folder."},{"title":"Launch KoboldCpp — its setup window appears","detail":"Now you'll start KoboldCpp to bring up its setup window, where beginners configure everything without typing.","do":["On Windows, open your Downloads folder (click the folder icon on the taskbar, then 'Downloads' on the left) and double-click  koboldcpp.exe .","On a Mac, open Terminal (press Command+Space, type 'Terminal', press Enter), then run the two macOS commands below in your Downloads folder to make the file runnable and start it.","On Linux, open a terminal and run the two Linux commands below in your Downloads folder."],"commands":["# macOS (Apple Silicon) — run these in Terminal, in your Downloads folder:","chmod +x koboldcpp-mac-arm64","./koboldcpp-mac-arm64","# Linux — run these in a terminal, in your Downloads folder:","chmod +x koboldcpp-linux-x64","./koboldcpp-linux-x64"],"check":"the KoboldCpp launcher window is on screen with tabs like 'Quick Launch' and 'Hardware'."},{"title":"Point KoboldCpp at your model and pick a hardware Preset","detail":"In the launcher, you'll tell KoboldCpp which model file to load and pick a hardware preset for speed. These are usually the only two things you ever change.","do":["Find the 'Model' box (labeled 'GGUF Text Model' or similar) and click 'Browse'.","Navigate to your Downloads folder and select the .gguf file you downloaded in Step 3.","Find the 'Preset' dropdown near the top.","If you have an NVIDIA graphics card, choose 'CUDA' (also called 'cuBLAS'); for any other graphics card or if you aren't sure, choose 'Vulkan'; with no dedicated GPU, leave the default CPU preset."],"commands":[],"check":"the model's file path shows in the Model box and a Preset is selected."},{"title":"Set GPU layers and context size (or accept the smart defaults)","detail":"Two optional dials control speed and memory. Beginners can accept the defaults; these settings just let you tune performance if you want.","do":["Find 'GPU Layers' — if you have a GPU, set it high (try 999, which means 'put as much as fits on the GPU'); KoboldCpp auto-lowers it if your card is too small.","Find 'Context Size' — 4096 is a safe default; 8192 lets the model remember more (good for long stories) but uses more memory.","If you have no GPU, leave GPU Layers at 0 and Context Size at 4096."],"commands":["# Optional, for confident users who prefer the command line instead of the GUI (Windows example):","koboldcpp.exe --model \"Meta-Llama-3.1-8B-Instruct-Q4_K_M.gguf\" --usecublas --gpulayers 999 --contextsize 8192 --port 5001"],"check":"'GPU Layers' and 'Context Size' show values you're comfortable with."},{"title":"Click 'Launch' and wait for the model to load","detail":"Now you'll start the engine. Loading a multi-gigabyte model takes a little while the first time — the window is working, not frozen.","do":["Click the 'Launch' button at the bottom of the launcher window.","Watch the black text window show loading progress — this is normal and can take 10 seconds to a couple of minutes the first time.","Look for a line saying the server is listening, ending with something like  http://localhost:5001  ('localhost' means this very computer)."],"commands":[],"check":"the console shows 'Please connect to custom endpoint at http://localhost:5001' (or similar) and your web browser opens automatically to the KoboldCpp interface."},{"title":"Use the web sandbox — type a prompt and generate text","detail":"KoboldCpp opens a retro-styled web page in your browser where you type prompts and generate text — all staying 100% on your computer.","do":["If it didn't open by itself, open your browser and type  http://localhost:5001  in the address bar.","Type a prompt in the big text box — for example  Write the opening paragraph of a mystery novel set on a lighthouse.  — and click 'Submit' (or 'Generate').","To experiment, open the 'Settings' menu and adjust the 'Temperature' slider: lower (0.3) is focused and predictable, higher (1.1) is wildly creative.","To stop everything later, close the browser tab and the black console window."],"commands":["http://localhost:5001"],"check":"the AI writes text back to you in the browser, and everything you type stays on your computer."}],"resources":[{"label":"KoboldCpp official GitHub repository (downloads, releases, and full docs)","url":"https://github.com/LostRuins/koboldcpp"},{"label":"KoboldCpp latest release page (where you download the one-file executable)","url":"https://github.com/LostRuins/koboldcpp/releases/latest"},{"label":"KoboldCpp GitHub Wiki (FAQ, launch options, GPU and context tips)","url":"https://github.com/LostRuins/koboldcpp/wiki"},{"label":"Hugging Face — search here for GGUF model files (add 'GGUF' or 'Q4_K_M' to your search)","url":"https://huggingface.co/models"},{"label":"Video search phrase: 'KoboldCpp beginner setup load GGUF model tutorial 2025' (search on YouTube)"},{"label":"Video search phrase: 'KoboldCpp GPU layers and context size explained' (search on YouTube)"}],"cloudTieIn":"Think of KoboldCpp as a private, local sibling of the cloud chatbots you may already use — Microsoft Copilot, Anthropic Claude, OpenAI ChatGPT, and Google Gemini. Those cloud tools run enormous frontier models on someone else's servers, which is why they are strongest on hard reasoning, coding, and up-to-date knowledge — but your text travels off your device and is billed per use or per subscription. KoboldCpp runs a smaller open-weight model entirely on your own computer, so it is the safer default when you are working with sensitive data like student records (FERPA) or health information (HIPAA), and it costs roughly $0 per word after the free download. A practical workflow is to draft, brainstorm, and iterate privately in KoboldCpp, then turn to a cloud tool like Claude or ChatGPT when you hit a task that needs frontier-level power — local complements cloud, it does not replace it. And because KoboldCpp also exposes an OpenAI-compatible API at http://localhost:5001/v1, apps that normally call ChatGPT can be pointed at your local model instead, letting you swap the cloud brain for a private one without rewriting the app.","troubleshooting":[{"symptom":"Windows SmartScreen or your antivirus blocks koboldcpp.exe or warns 'this file isn't commonly downloaded.'","fix":"This is expected for a niche open-source single-file program, not a sign of a virus. Click 'Keep' on the download, then if a blue 'Windows protected your PC' box appears, click 'More info' and then 'Run anyway'. Only ever download the file from the official github.com/LostRuins/koboldcpp releases page."},{"symptom":"The model fails to load, or the console shows an 'out of memory' / 'failed to allocate' error.","fix":"Your model is too big for your memory. Pick a smaller model (for example an 8B instead of a 12B) or a more compressed quantization (Q4_K_M instead of Q6 or Q8). If you set GPU Layers high, lower it so less is forced onto the graphics card, or set it to 0 to run on the CPU only."},{"symptom":"The browser says the page can't be reached, or 'connection refused' at http://localhost:5001.","fix":"The KoboldCpp server must be running for that page to work. Make sure the black console window is still open and finished loading (it should say it is listening on port 5001). If you closed it, launch KoboldCpp again. Then reload http://localhost:5001 in your browser."},{"symptom":"An error says the port is already in use, or 5001 won't start.","fix":"Another program (often a second copy of KoboldCpp you left running) is using that port. Close the other console window, or in the launcher's Network settings change the Port to a different number like 5002, then open http://localhost:5002 in your browser instead."},{"symptom":"The first reply is very slow, or generation feels sluggish overall.","fix":"The first response is always slower while the model 'warms up' — this is normal. For lasting speed, use a GPU Preset (CUDA for NVIDIA, Vulkan for other cards) and raise GPU Layers so more of the model runs on the graphics card. On CPU-only machines, choose a smaller model and keep Context Size at 4096."},{"symptom":"On Mac or Linux the file won't run, or you see 'permission denied'.","fix":"You skipped making the file executable. In Terminal, in the folder where you downloaded it, run 'chmod +x koboldcpp-mac-arm64' (Mac) or 'chmod +x koboldcpp-linux-x64' (Linux), then start it with './koboldcpp-mac-arm64' or './koboldcpp-linux-x64'. On Mac, if it says the developer can't be verified, open System Settings > Privacy & Security and click 'Open Anyway'."}],"tips":["Start small: an 8B model at Q4_K_M is the sweet spot for first-timers on 8 GB of RAM — you can always graduate to a 12B model later once you know it works.","Temperature is your creativity dial. Lower it (around 0.3) for focused, coherent writing and factual tasks; raise it (around 1.0-1.2) for wild, imaginative story ideas. Change one setting at a time so you can see what each does.","KoboldCpp is truly portable — copy the single executable and your .gguf model onto a USB drive and you have a private AI you can run on another computer with no installation.","Enable 'Context Shift' (on by default) so long chats and stories keep flowing without slowing to a crawl as the conversation grows — it lets the model reuse memory efficiently instead of re-reading everything.","Remember that local models can confidently state wrong things. For anything that matters — facts, code, medical or legal wording — verify it, and reach for a frontier cloud tool like Claude or ChatGPT when accuracy is critical. Local ≠ automatically correct, and local ≠ automatically compliant."],"difficulty":"Intermediate — comfortable installing apps and copy-pasting commands","time":"About 20–30 minutes"},{"id":"lab6","n":6,"cat":"E","title":"Pinokio — One-Click AI App Launcher","tagline":"Install the Pinokio launcher once, then install and run complex local AI apps (image generators, voice tools, chat UIs) with a single click — no terminal, no Python, no dependency hell.","whatItIs":"Pinokio is a free desktop application that acts like a \"browser for AI apps.\" Instead of visiting websites, you browse a built-in catalog (called Discover) of open-source AI projects — image generators, voice cloners, video tools, chat interfaces — and install each one with a single click. Behind that one click, Pinokio quietly does all the hard technical work that normally scares beginners away: it downloads the correct version of Python, fetches the project's code from the internet, installs dozens of software \"dependencies,\" sets up an isolated environment so nothing breaks your computer, and starts a small local server. You watch it happen in a live text window (the console) but you never have to type a single command. Everything installs into one tidy folder on your machine and runs locally, so your data stays on your computer.","whyUseIt":"Normally, getting an open-source AI project running means fighting with the terminal, installing the exact right Python version, cloning code with Git, resolving conflicting package versions, and reading cryptic error messages — a process that defeats most non-engineers before they ever see the app work. Pinokio removes that entire wall: it turns a multi-hour, expert-only setup into a one-click, watch-the-progress-bar experience. Use it when you want to try heavier local AI tools (Stable Diffusion image generation, voice cloning, face tools, or a polished chat front-end) without becoming a developer first. The privacy and cost angle is the same reason local AI matters generally: the apps run on your own hardware, so your prompts, images, and files never leave your machine (important for anything sensitive like student or health records), and once installed the open-weight models cost roughly $0 per use instead of a per-message cloud bill. Be honest with yourself, though: these apps lean heavily on your graphics card, big ones can be slow or fail on modest laptops, and \"runs locally\" does not automatically mean \"compliant\" — you still verify the app and its license for your use case.","bestFor":"A non-technical beginner who wants to run a real, dependency-heavy local AI app (like an image generator or voice tool) without ever touching a terminal, Python, or Git.","platforms":["Windows","macOS (Apple Silicon)","macOS (Intel)","Linux"],"prerequisites":["A Windows PC, a Mac, or a Linux computer with administrator rights (the ability to install software you download).","Free disk space: at least 20-40 GB free. Pinokio itself is small, but each AI app it installs can be several gigabytes, and image/video apps can be much larger. An external or secondary drive helps if your main disk is small.","A graphics card (GPU) is strongly recommended for the heavier apps: NVIDIA with 6 GB+ VRAM on Windows/Linux, or Apple Silicon (M1/M2/M3/M4) on Mac. Text-only tools can run on CPU but slowly; image and video tools really want a GPU.","A stable internet connection for the first-time downloads (the apps and their AI models are large). After install, most apps run offline.","About 20-40 minutes of patience the first time — the very first app you install downloads a lot; later installs reuse shared pieces and go faster.","Optional but recommended: install Ollama first (from ollama.com) if you also want a simple local chat model at http://localhost:11434 to compare against Pinokio-launched apps."],"steps":[{"title":"Download the correct Pinokio installer for your computer","detail":"Pinokio is a free program you download once. This step just gets the correct installer file for your computer onto your machine.","do":["Open your web browser — Chrome, Edge, or Safari.","Click the address bar at the top, type  desktop.pinokio.co , and press Enter.","On Windows, click the 64-bit Windows installer (the file ends in .exe).","On a newer Mac (M1/M2/M3/M4 chip), click 'Apple Silicon'; on an older Intel Mac, click 'Intel'.","On Linux, follow the link to the release page and pick AppImage, DEB, or RPM.","If you are not sure which Mac you have, click the Apple logo in the top-left, choose 'About This Mac,' and look for 'Apple M...' (Apple Silicon) or 'Intel.'","Wait for the file to finish downloading — check your Downloads folder."],"commands":[],"check":"a file lands in your Downloads folder (for example Pinokio-7.2.6-Setup.exe or a .dmg file)."},{"title":"Run the installer and get past the safety warning","detail":"This installs Pinokio onto your computer. Because it's a smaller open-source app, your system may show a scary-looking warning the first time — that's normal and expected.","do":["Open your Downloads folder and double-click the file you just downloaded.","On Windows, if a blue 'Windows protected your PC' / SmartScreen box appears, click the small 'More info' text, then click 'Run anyway'.","On a Mac, double-click the .dmg, then drag the Pinokio icon into your Applications folder and open it.","On a Mac, if it says the app 'cannot be opened because it is from an unidentified developer', open the Apple menu, choose System Settings, click 'Privacy & Security', scroll down, and click 'Open Anyway', then confirm."],"commands":[],"check":"the Pinokio window opens."},{"title":"Let Pinokio set itself up on first launch","detail":"The first time it opens, Pinokio builds its own private workspace folder where every AI app you install will live safely. You just accept the defaults and wait.","do":["If a one-time setup screen appears or it asks where to store its files, accept the default location.","Do not close the window while it works.","Wait for it to finish preparing (this creates a single folder, usually named 'pinokio', in your home/user folder)."],"commands":[],"check":"Pinokio finishes setup and shows its main home screen with a menu or a 'Discover' button visible."},{"title":"Open Discover — the one-click app catalog","detail":"Discover is Pinokio's built-in app store of AI tools that have been checked by the maintainer. This is where you safely browse apps instead of pasting random links from the internet.","do":["On the Pinokio home screen, find and click the 'Discover' button.","Browse the grid of AI apps that appears (image generators, voice tools, chat interfaces, video tools).","Use the tags and toggles to filter by GPU labels (NVIDIA, AMD, Apple) and platform labels (Windows, macOS, Linux) so you only see apps that match your computer."],"commands":[],"check":"a scrollable page of app cards appears, each with an install button."},{"title":"Pick a beginner-friendly first app and read its card","detail":"For your first try, pick a small, well-known app so the install goes smoothly. Choosing something too heavy for your computer is the number-one cause of a failed first attempt.","do":["Choose a lighter, well-known app for your first install — a Stable Diffusion image tool or a simple chat/UI app are good picks.","Click the app's card to open its detail page.","Read the short description and any GPU/VRAM requirement (for example '6 GB VRAM').","If your computer does not meet that requirement, go back and pick a smaller app instead."],"commands":[],"check":"the app's detail page opens with a prominent 'Install' or 'Download' button."},{"title":"Click Install and watch the visual console log do the work","detail":"This is the one click that does all the hard technical work for you. A scrolling text log (the console) shows Pinokio downloading and setting everything up — you don't need to understand it, just let it run.","do":["Click the 'Install' (one-click install) button.","Watch the console window — a black-and-white scrolling text log — open and start working.","Let it run: it downloads Python, fetches the app's code, installs packages, and sets up an isolated environment. This can take 5 to 30+ minutes the first time.","Do NOT close the window or let your computer go to sleep while it works."],"commands":[],"check":"the log slows down and ends with a 'completed', 'done', or 'Install success' style message, and an 'Open' or 'Start' button becomes available."},{"title":"Start the app and open it in your browser","detail":"Now you launch the app you just installed. It runs on your own computer and opens in your browser at a local web address — nothing goes to the internet.","do":["Click the 'Start' (or 'Run' / 'Launch') button.","Look for the local web address it shows, in the form http://localhost:PORT (for example http://127.0.0.1:7860).","Click that link (or the app's built-in browser view) to open the app's real interface.","Try it out: type a prompt, click generate, and wait — the first result is slow because the model is loading into memory for the first time."],"commands":[],"check":"the app's real interface loads and produces output — an image, text, or audio."},{"title":"Stop the app cleanly and know where to relaunch it","detail":"When you're finished, stop the app properly so it frees up your memory and graphics card. Closing the browser tab alone does not stop it.","do":["Go back to the Pinokio window and click 'Stop' (or the equivalent) to shut down the app's local server.","To use the app again later, open Pinokio, find the app in your installed/library list, and click 'Start' again — you never reinstall.","To completely remove an app, use its 'Uninstall' option inside Pinokio or delete its folder."],"commands":[],"check":"the app shows as stopped, your fan quiets down, and the app is still listed and ready to relaunch instantly."}],"resources":[{"label":"Pinokio official site and Discover catalog","url":"https://pinokio.co"},{"label":"Pinokio download page (Windows, macOS Apple Silicon/Intel, Linux)","url":"https://desktop.pinokio.co"},{"label":"Pinokio GitHub repository, releases, and documentation","url":"https://github.com/pinokiocomputer/pinokio"},{"label":"Ollama — simplest way to also run a local chat model at localhost:11434 (great to compare against Pinokio apps)","url":"https://ollama.com"},{"label":"Hugging Face — where the open-weight models (Gemma, Qwen, Llama) and many app models are hosted","url":"https://huggingface.co"},{"label":"Video search phrase: 'Pinokio install and first AI app walkthrough for beginners'"},{"label":"Video search phrase: 'Pinokio one-click Stable Diffusion setup no coding'"}],"cloudTieIn":"Think of Pinokio as the local counterpart to the cloud AI tools you may already use — Microsoft Copilot, Anthropic Claude, OpenAI ChatGPT, and Google Gemini. Those cloud services are the most capable option for the hardest reasoning, coding, and writing tasks, and they need no setup, but every prompt travels to a company's servers and, for heavy use, costs money per message or per subscription. Pinokio flips that trade-off: the open-source apps it installs run entirely on your own machine, so your prompts, images, and files never leave your computer and the running cost is roughly $0 — which is exactly why local is the safer default for sensitive material like student records (FERPA) or health data (HIPAA). The realistic pattern is to complement, not replace: reach for a frontier cloud model when you need maximum quality or don't have a capable GPU, and use Pinokio-launched local apps for privacy-sensitive work, offline use, cost control, and hands-on experimentation. Many Pinokio apps can even talk to a local model server (such as Ollama at http://localhost:11434) so you can wire together an entirely local workflow that mirrors what you'd otherwise send to the cloud.","troubleshooting":[{"symptom":"Windows shows a blue 'Windows protected your PC' (SmartScreen) box and won't let you install.","fix":"This is expected for smaller open-source apps, not a virus warning. Click the small 'More info' link inside the box, then click the 'Run anyway' button that appears, and the installer proceeds. Only do this because you downloaded from the official desktop.pinokio.co page."},{"symptom":"On Mac, 'Pinokio cannot be opened because it is from an unidentified developer.'","fix":"Open the Apple menu, choose System Settings, click 'Privacy & Security,' scroll to the security section, and click 'Open Anyway' next to the Pinokio message, then confirm. This one-time approval unblocks the app because it isn't from a paid Apple developer account."},{"symptom":"The console log turns red / shows an error and the install stops partway.","fix":"First just click 'Install' again — most failures are interrupted downloads and simply resuming works. If it keeps failing, the app is likely too big for your hardware or your disk filled up: free disk space, pick a smaller app, and make sure your internet stayed connected. As a last resort, uninstall that app inside Pinokio and try a different, lighter one."},{"symptom":"An out-of-memory error appears, or your whole computer freezes when you run the app.","fix":"The AI model is too large for your RAM/VRAM. Choose an app or model marked for lower VRAM (look for a 4-bit / Q4 'quantized' version, which roughly halves memory use), close other heavy programs and browser tabs, and stop any other Pinokio app that's still running. On a laptop, plug into power so the GPU isn't throttled."},{"symptom":"You click the localhost link and the browser says 'connection refused' or the page won't load.","fix":"The app's local server isn't running yet. Go back into Pinokio and make sure you clicked 'Start' (installing is not the same as running), then wait for the log to say the server is ready before clicking the link. If it still fails, click 'Stop' then 'Start' again to restart the server."},{"symptom":"The app fails to start with a 'port already in use' / 'address in use' message.","fix":"Another program (often a second copy of the same app, or another Pinokio app) is already using that network port. Stop the other running app inside Pinokio, or simply quit and reopen Pinokio to clear stuck servers, then click 'Start' again."},{"symptom":"The very first result is extremely slow or seems frozen.","fix":"This is normal on the first run — the AI model has to load into memory once, which can take a minute or more, and the first image or reply is always the slowest. Wait it out; subsequent runs in the same session are much faster because the model stays loaded until you click Stop."}],"tips":["Install ONE app at a time and let it fully finish before starting another — running two heavy AI apps at once will fight over your graphics card and memory and can freeze the machine.","Always click 'Stop' inside Pinokio when you're done with an app; closing the browser tab leaves the local server (and your GPU) running in the background and draining resources.","Everything Pinokio installs lives in a single 'pinokio' folder in your home directory — back that folder up, or delete an app's subfolder to reclaim space, and know that uninstalling from inside Pinokio is the clean way to remove an app.","Prefer apps listed in the built-in Discover catalog over random install links from forums or videos — Discover apps are manually reviewed, which is your main safety filter as a beginner.","Watch the console log the first few times even though it looks intimidating: seeing Pinokio download Python, packages, and models teaches you exactly what 'setting up a local AI app' really involves — and makes cloud vs. local trade-offs click.","Pair Pinokio with Ollama (localhost:11434) or LM Studio (localhost:1234) — use Pinokio for full apps like image and voice tools, and those for a lightweight local chat model, so you build a complete private AI toolkit."],"difficulty":"Beginner — no coding or terminal needed; just downloading and clicking through installs","time":"About 30–60 minutes (most of it waiting for downloads)"},{"id":"lab7","n":7,"cat":"E","title":"WebGPU — Run Models in Your Browser, Zero Install","tagline":"Run a real AI model entirely inside your web browser tab — no downloads, no installs, no terminal, and no admin rights — using WebGPU.","whatItIs":"WebGPU is a built-in feature of modern web browsers (Chrome, Edge, Firefox, Safari) that lets a web page use your computer's graphics chip (GPU) to do heavy math — the same kind of math an AI model needs to think. A project called WebLLM, from the open-source MLC AI team, uses WebGPU to load a small AI model straight into a browser tab. You open a web page, the model downloads once into the browser's private cache, and from then on the AI runs on your own machine right inside that tab. Nothing you type is sent to any server, and once the model is cached the tab even works with the internet turned off.","whyUseIt":"This is the single lowest-friction way to try a local AI model: there is nothing to install, no account to create, no command line, and no administrator password — so it works on locked-down school or corporate laptops where you cannot install software or open a terminal. Because the model runs inside the browser tab on your own hardware, your prompts never leave the machine, which matters for privacy-sensitive text like student records (FERPA) or health notes (HIPAA), and it costs nothing per message versus a paid cloud subscription. Use it as your very first taste of local AI, for offline demos, or anywhere data must not go to a third party. Be honest about the trade-off: browser models are small (1B–3B parameters) and noticeably weaker than frontier cloud tools on hard reasoning, math, and coding, so always verify their answers — and running locally makes data handling safer but does not by itself make you FERPA- or HIPAA-compliant.","bestFor":"A complete beginner on a restricted school or work computer who cannot install software or open a terminal but wants to try a genuinely local AI model in the next five minutes.","platforms":["Windows","macOS","Linux","ChromeOS","Browser (Chrome, Edge, Firefox, Safari)"],"prerequisites":["A modern web browser updated within the last year: Chrome or Edge version 113 or newer, Firefox 141 or newer on Windows, or Safari 26 or newer on a Mac (macOS Tahoe). Any browser you have not updated in over a year should be updated first.","A computer with a graphics chip (GPU) — essentially every laptop and desktop from the last several years qualifies, including built-in Intel/AMD graphics; you do NOT need a fancy gaming card.","At least 8 GB of RAM is comfortable. The tiny models (about 1 billion parameters) work on modest machines; larger in-browser options want more memory.","About 1–3 GB of free disk space for the model to cache inside the browser (this is a one-time download, roughly the size of a movie).","A working internet connection for the FIRST run only, to download the model. After that the tab runs offline.","No admin rights, no account, no terminal, and no software install are required — that is the entire point of this lab."],"steps":[{"title":"Open your web browser and confirm it is recent enough","detail":"You already have a web browser — you're not installing anything. This step just makes sure it's a recent enough version to run AI.","do":["Open your web browser — Chrome (a red-green-yellow circle), Edge (a blue-green swirl), or Safari (a blue compass).","In Chrome or Edge, click the three-dots menu in the top-right corner.","Click 'Help', then 'About Google Chrome' (or 'About Microsoft Edge').","Let it show the version number and quietly update itself if needed.","If your browser is very old and will not update, just continue — the next step tells you for certain whether it will work."],"commands":[],"check":"you see a version number of 113 or higher for Chrome or Edge."},{"title":"Verify your browser actually supports WebGPU","detail":"This opens a free diagnostic page that checks whether your browser can use your graphics chip for AI. Nothing installs and there's no login.","do":["Click once in the address bar at the very top of the browser.","Type the address below exactly and press Enter.","Wait a few seconds for the page to run its check.","If you see a red 'WebGPU is not available' message, go to the troubleshooting section for the one-line fix before continuing."],"commands":["https://webgpureport.org/"],"check":"the page fills with technical details showing a green/working status and your graphics card's name (an 'adapter')."},{"title":"Go to the official WebLLM Chat page","detail":"This is the free, official chat page from the WebLLM team. It looks like ChatGPT, but everything will run on your own computer.","do":["Click the address bar again.","Type the address below exactly and press Enter.","Wait for the chat page to load."],"commands":["https://chat.webllm.ai/"],"check":"a clean chat screen appears with a model picker (a dropdown or list of model names) and a message box at the bottom — nothing has downloaded yet."},{"title":"Pick a small model so the first download is fast","detail":"Smaller models download faster and run more smoothly, so pick a small one for your first try. Look for names labeled 1B or 2B.","do":["Find the model selector — usually a dropdown near the top or a list when you start a new chat.","Choose a small model such as 'Llama 3.2 1B', 'Phi-3.5 mini', 'Gemma 2 2B', or a Qwen model.","If you see 'q4' or 'Q4' in the name, prefer it — that's a compression trick that halves the size with only a small quality cost."],"commands":[],"check":"the model name now shows as selected."},{"title":"Allow the download and let the model stream into the browser cache","detail":"Sending your first message triggers a one-time download of the model into your browser. After this, the AI runs on your machine.","do":["Click the message box at the bottom and type a short first message like 'Hello, are you running locally?'.","Press Enter.","Watch for a progress bar or a 'loading/initializing model' message — this is the one-time download of roughly 1–3 GB and can take one to several minutes.","If the browser shows a small permission prompt about hardware acceleration or graphics, click Allow."],"commands":[],"check":"the progress bar reaches 100%, then the AI types a reply back to you word by word — generated on your own machine."},{"title":"Confirm it is truly running locally by going offline","detail":"Here's the proof that everything is private: turn off your internet and the AI still works, because the model now lives on your computer.","do":["Make sure the model has fully loaded and answered you at least once.","Turn off your Wi-Fi from the system tray/menu bar, or unplug the network cable.","Type another message like 'Write me a two-line poem about coffee.' and press Enter.","Turn your Wi-Fi back on afterward when you are done."],"commands":[],"check":"the AI still answers even with no internet — proof that your text never left the computer."},{"title":"Run a few real prompts and watch the speed","detail":"Now put the model through its paces with real tasks. Notice that the first reply is slowest and later ones speed up.","do":["Paste in a paragraph and ask it to summarize.","Ask it to brainstorm some ideas.","Ask it to rewrite a sentence more formally.","Notice the first reply after loading is the slowest, and later replies come faster."],"commands":[],"check":"you are holding a back-and-forth conversation entirely offline, with each answer streaming in on your own hardware."},{"title":"Understand the limits before you trust an answer","detail":"This last step is about knowing the trade-offs. Small in-browser models are private and free, but they make mistakes, so you need to know when to trust them.","do":["Always double-check anything important — math, dates, code, and niche facts — against a reliable source, because small models make confident mistakes.","Remember that running locally protects your data, but does not by itself make your workflow FERPA- or HIPAA-compliant.","Weigh what you gained (privacy, zero cost, zero install, offline use) against what you traded away (raw capability)."],"commands":[],"check":"you understand both what you gained and what you traded away, so you know when a browser model is enough and when to reach for a bigger local model or a cloud tool."}],"resources":[{"label":"WebLLM Chat — official in-browser chat app (start here)","url":"https://chat.webllm.ai/"},{"label":"WebLLM project home and model list (MLC AI)","url":"https://webllm.mlc.ai/"},{"label":"WebLLM source code and supported-models docs on GitHub","url":"https://github.com/mlc-ai/web-llm"},{"label":"WebGPU Report — instant check of whether your browser supports WebGPU","url":"https://webgpureport.org/"},{"label":"web.dev tutorial: build an offline-capable chatbot with WebLLM","url":"https://web.dev/articles/ai-chatbot-webllm"},{"label":"Video search phrase: 'WebLLM WebGPU run LLM in browser no install tutorial'"},{"label":"Video search phrase: 'chat.webllm.ai offline browser AI demo how to'"}],"cloudTieIn":"Think of this browser model as a private, offline sketchpad that sits next to — not instead of — the frontier cloud tools you may already use like Microsoft Copilot, Anthropic Claude, OpenAI ChatGPT, and Google Gemini. Those cloud services are far more capable on hard reasoning, long documents, and up-to-date knowledge because they run enormous models on remote servers; reach for them when you need maximum quality and the data is not sensitive. Reach for the WebGPU browser model when the data must never leave the machine (student or health records), when you have no internet, or when you simply cannot install anything on a locked-down computer. The interaction is deliberately familiar — WebLLM even mimics the OpenAI-style chat experience — so the prompting skills you build here transfer directly to Copilot, Claude, ChatGPT, and Gemini, and vice versa. The honest rule of thumb: local complements the cloud, it does not replace it.","troubleshooting":[{"symptom":"webgpureport.org or WebLLM Chat says 'WebGPU is not available' or 'not supported'.","fix":"First update the browser (three-dots menu, Help, About). If it still fails on Chrome/Edge, type chrome://flags/#enable-unsafe-webgpu (or edge://flags/#enable-unsafe-webgpu) in the address bar, set that flag to Enabled, and restart the browser. On a locked school/work machine where flags are blocked, try a different modern browser (Chrome or Edge) — Safari needs macOS Tahoe 26 or newer."},{"symptom":"The tab freezes, crashes, or shows an out-of-memory error while loading the model.","fix":"You picked a model too large for your machine. Refresh the page and choose the smallest option (a 1B model, ideally a Q4/4-bit version), and close other heavy browser tabs and apps to free up memory. Q4 quantization roughly halves the memory needed."},{"symptom":"The download bar is stuck or never finishes.","fix":"This is a one-time 1–3 GB download and needs a stable internet connection — do not go offline until it hits 100%. If it stalls, refresh the page and let it resume (the browser keeps partial cache). A strict corporate firewall can block the model file host; try a different network or a personal hotspot for the initial download only."},{"symptom":"The first reply is extremely slow or seems frozen.","fix":"The first response after loading is always the slowest because the model is warming up in memory; wait 20–30 seconds. Later replies are faster. On built-in (integrated) graphics, expect a steady but not cloud-fast pace — this is normal for a local model, not a bug."},{"symptom":"The AI gives a confidently wrong or made-up answer.","fix":"Expected behavior for a small 1B–3B model. These are weaker than cloud tools on facts, math, and code — always verify important answers against a trustworthy source, or switch to a larger local model (via Ollama or LM Studio) or a cloud tool for hard tasks."},{"symptom":"After closing and reopening the browser, the model seems to reload from scratch.","fix":"The model is cached per-browser-profile; using a private/incognito window or a machine that wipes browser data on logout (common in school labs) clears the cache, forcing a re-download. Use a normal (non-incognito) window on a machine that keeps your profile so the cached model persists and stays offline-ready."}],"tips":["Start with the smallest model (1B, Q4) to guarantee a fast first success, then experiment with a larger one like Gemma 2 2B once you know your machine handles it.","After the model is cached, deliberately turn off Wi-Fi and send a message — proving to yourself it works offline is the single most convincing demo of local, private AI.","This browser route is the 'no-terminal, no-install' tier. When you outgrow it and want bigger models or an API on your own machine (Ollama at http://localhost:11434 or LM Studio at http://localhost:1234), those are the natural next labs — but they need software install rights this lab does not.","Use a normal browser window, not incognito/private mode, so the cached model survives between sessions instead of re-downloading every time.","For a class demo on locked machines, pre-load the model once on the classroom Wi-Fi before students arrive; after caching, each machine runs offline and instantly.","Keep expectations calibrated: treat browser-model output as a helpful first draft to verify, not a final authority — the same healthy skepticism you should apply to any AI, cloud or local."],"difficulty":"Beginner — no coding or IT experience needed; everything runs in your web browser","time":"About 15–20 minutes (most of it a one-time model download)"},{"id":"lab8","n":8,"cat":"D","title":"AnythingLLM — Your Private Knowledge Base (Local RAG)","tagline":"Turn a folder of your own PDFs into a private, offline chatbot that answers only from your documents — with nothing ever leaving your computer.","whatItIs":"AnythingLLM is a free desktop app that gives you a private, ChatGPT-style chat window that answers questions using your own files instead of the public internet. This technique is called RAG (Retrieval-Augmented Generation): the app reads your documents, breaks them into small pieces, stores them in a local search index called a vector database, and then feeds only the relevant pieces to a local AI model so it can answer grounded in your material. Paired with Ollama (a companion app that runs the actual AI model on your machine), the entire loop — your files, the search index, and the model — lives on your computer. Nothing is uploaded to any company.","whyUseIt":"Use this when you have a body of your own material — course readings, research papers, policy manuals, meeting notes, tax records, medical letters — and you want to ask questions of it in plain English without hunting through pages, and without handing that material to a cloud service. Because everything runs locally, it is the safer default for identifiable or regulated data: for a college program that means student records under FERPA and any health data under HIPAA never leave the device, there is no third-party retention, and open-weight models cost roughly nothing per question versus a cloud subscription. AnythingLLM also lets you keep separate \"workspace\" silos (for example one for Academic Research and a different one for Personal Records) so the AI never mixes facts across unrelated topics. Be honest about limits: local models are smaller and weaker than frontier cloud models on the hardest reasoning, they can still be wrong, and running locally does not by itself make you compliant — always verify important answers against the source documents.","bestFor":"Non-technical students and professionals who want to privately ask questions of their own confidential documents — course readings, research, policy manuals, or personal records — entirely offline.","platforms":["Windows","macOS (Apple Silicon and Intel)","Linux"],"prerequisites":["Ollama installed and running first — AnythingLLM is just the friendly front end; Ollama is the engine that actually runs the AI model. If you have not set up Ollama yet, do that lab before this one (download from ollama.com).","At least one chat model already pulled in Ollama, such as llama3.2 (about 2 GB) or gemma3 (about 3 GB). This is the model that writes the answers.","8 GB of RAM is enough for a 3B-8B model like llama3.2 or gemma3; 16 GB or more lets you run larger, smarter models. Models use 4-bit (Q4) quantization, which roughly halves the memory they need.","About 5 GB of free disk space: roughly 2-3 GB for the chat model, ~274 MB for the embedding model, and space for the AnythingLLM app and your documents.","A folder of documents to query (PDF, Word .docx, .txt, or Markdown all work). Start with a handful of files for your first test.","No account, no internet connection, and no credit card are required to use it after the one-time downloads."],"steps":[{"title":"Make sure the AI engine (Ollama) is running","detail":"AnythingLLM needs a companion app called Ollama running in the background to actually run the AI. This step launches Ollama and confirms it's awake.","do":["On Windows, click the Start menu, type Ollama, and press Enter; on a Mac, press Command+Spacebar, type Ollama, and press Enter.","Look for a small llama icon in your taskbar (bottom-right on Windows) or menu bar (top-right on Mac) — that means it's running.","Open a terminal: on Windows click Start, type PowerShell, and press Enter; on a Mac press Command+Spacebar, type Terminal, and press Enter.","Type the command below and press Enter."],"commands":["ollama list"],"check":"a short list of model names is printed back to you."},{"title":"Confirm you have a chat model, and pull one if the list was empty","detail":"You need at least one chat model — the AI 'brain' that writes answers. If your list from the last step was empty, this step downloads one.","do":["Look at the list from the previous step for a chat model name like llama3.2 or gemma3.","If the list is empty or you are not sure, run the first command below to download Llama 3.2 (a small ~2 GB model from Meta).","Watch the progress bar and wait for the word 'success'.","Optionally, run the second command to also download Google's gemma3 as an alternative."],"commands":["ollama pull llama3.2","ollama pull gemma3"],"check":"the download ends with the word 'success' and the model now shows in your list."},{"title":"Download and install the AnythingLLM desktop app","detail":"AnythingLLM is the app that gives you the ChatGPT-style window over your own files. This step downloads and installs it.","do":["Open your web browser and go to anythingllm.com.","Click the Download button and choose your version: 'Windows' for a PC, 'Apple Silicon' for a Mac made in 2020 or later, or 'Apple Intel' for an older Mac.","On Windows, open the downloaded .exe and click through the installer (click Yes if Windows asks for permission).","On a Mac, open the downloaded .dmg and drag the AnythingLLM icon into your Applications folder.","Launch it from the Start menu on Windows, or Applications/Launchpad on a Mac."],"commands":[],"check":"a welcome/onboarding screen appears with a 'Get Started' button."},{"title":"On the setup wizard, choose Ollama as your AI provider","detail":"The setup wizard needs to know where the AI comes from. You point it at Ollama, the engine you started in Step 1.","do":["When the wizard asks you to pick an 'LLM Provider', scroll the list and click Ollama.","Check that the address box already reads http://127.0.0.1:11434 and leave it exactly as-is.","In the model dropdown, pick the chat model you downloaded, for example llama3.2 or gemma3.","If the dropdown is empty, Ollama is not running — go back to Step 1.","Click Continue."],"commands":[],"check":"Ollama is selected with the address http://127.0.0.1:11434 and your chat model chosen, and you can click Continue."},{"title":"Choose the embedding model (how your files become searchable)","detail":"An embedding model turns your documents into searchable math so the app can find the right passages. For a beginner, the built-in option is easiest.","do":["When the wizard asks about the 'Embedder', select 'AnythingLLM Built-in' — it needs zero setup and works offline.","Or, to route everything through Ollama instead, choose Ollama as the embedder and pick nomic-embed-text.","If nomic-embed-text is not listed, open a terminal, run the command below, then return and select it.","Click Continue."],"commands":["ollama pull nomic-embed-text"],"check":"an embedder is selected and you can click Continue."},{"title":"Leave the vector database on its default (LanceDB)","detail":"The vector database is the local index that stores your searchable document pieces. The default works perfectly, so you just accept it.","do":["When the wizard asks about a 'Vector Database', do not change anything — leave it set to LanceDB.","Click Continue.","Finish any remaining welcome screens — you can skip the optional survey and you do not need to create an account."],"commands":[],"check":"the main dashboard appears with an empty sidebar on the left."},{"title":"Create a workspace and load your documents","detail":"A workspace is a folder for one topic's documents. Here you make one and feed it your PDFs so the app can read and index them.","do":["In the left sidebar, click '+ New Workspace'.","Give it a clear name describing one topic, like 'Course Readings' or 'Tax Records'.","Open the new workspace, then click the upload icon (a paperclip or up-arrow near the chat box).","Drag your folder of PDFs (or individual files) into the dashed drop zone.","Click each file (or select all) and click 'Move to Workspace' to move them to the right column.","Click the 'Save and Embed' button and wait while the progress indicator runs."],"commands":[],"check":"the spinning stops and your files show as embedded."},{"title":"Ask a question and confirm the answer is grounded in your files","detail":"Now you test it: ask a question only your documents can answer, and check the citation to be sure the answer really came from your files.","do":["Click into the chat box at the bottom of the workspace.","Type a question that can only be answered from your documents — for example, 'Summarize the key argument in the second reading'.","Press Enter and wait — the first answer may take 10–40 seconds while the model loads.","Click the 'Citations' or 'Show Citations' link on the answer to see the exact source passage.","Spot-check that passage against the real document to catch any wrong answer."],"commands":[],"check":"you get an answer that restates facts from your material, with a citation you can trace back to the real document."}],"resources":[{"label":"AnythingLLM official site and desktop download","url":"https://anythingllm.com"},{"label":"AnythingLLM documentation (setup, embedders, vector databases)","url":"https://docs.anythingllm.com"},{"label":"AnythingLLM embedder configuration overview","url":"https://docs.anythingllm.com/setup/embedder-configuration/overview"},{"label":"Ollama — download the local model engine AnythingLLM connects to","url":"https://ollama.com"},{"label":"Video search: 'AnythingLLM Ollama local RAG setup tutorial for beginners'"},{"label":"Video search: 'AnythingLLM chat with your PDFs privately offline walkthrough'"}],"cloudTieIn":"This local setup is the private-data counterpart to the frontier cloud tools you may already use — Microsoft Copilot, Anthropic Claude, OpenAI ChatGPT, and Google Gemini. Those cloud services are more capable on the hardest tasks and let you upload documents to chat with, but your files travel to a company's servers, which is a poor fit for FERPA-protected student records, HIPAA health data, or confidential business material. The workflow here is the same idea — upload documents, then ask questions grounded in them — but the retrieval, the search index, and the model all run on your machine, so nothing leaves it. A sensible split: use AnythingLLM plus Ollama for anything private, sensitive, or high-volume where per-message cloud costs would add up, and reach for a cloud model when you need maximum reasoning power on non-sensitive material. Local complements cloud; it does not replace it. If you later outgrow the desktop app, the same AnythingLLM concepts (workspaces, Ollama provider, LanceDB) map directly to its Docker server version for teams.","troubleshooting":[{"symptom":"The model dropdown in AnythingLLM is empty, or it says 'Could not connect' / 'connection refused' to Ollama.","fix":"Ollama is not running. Launch it (Start menu on Windows, or open the Ollama app on Mac) and confirm with 'ollama list' in a terminal. Make sure the address in AnythingLLM is exactly http://127.0.0.1:11434 with no extra spaces or a trailing slash, then reopen the dropdown."},{"symptom":"'Save and Embed' fails, hangs forever, or throws an embedding error.","fix":"Your embedder is misconfigured. If you chose Ollama's nomic-embed-text, make sure you actually pulled it: run 'ollama pull nomic-embed-text' in a terminal, then re-select it in Settings > Embedder. The easiest fix is to switch the embedder to 'AnythingLLM Built-in', which needs no download."},{"symptom":"The computer becomes very slow, the answer stops halfway, or you see an 'out of memory' error.","fix":"The chat model is too large for your RAM. Close other heavy apps, then switch to a smaller model: run 'ollama pull llama3.2' and select llama3.2 in AnythingLLM's LLM settings. Models are 4-bit (Q4) quantized already; on 8 GB stay with 3B-8B models and avoid anything labeled 13B or larger."},{"symptom":"The very first answer takes a long time (20-60 seconds) before any text appears.","fix":"This is normal — the model is being loaded from disk into memory on the first question. Subsequent questions in the same session are much faster because the model stays loaded. If every answer is slow, your model is too big for your machine; switch to a smaller one."},{"symptom":"The chatbot ignores your documents and answers from general knowledge, or says it has no information.","fix":"Confirm the files finished embedding (they should show as embedded in the workspace, not just uploaded), and that you are chatting inside the same workspace the files are in. Also check the workspace chat mode is set to 'Query' (answers only from your docs) rather than a broad chat mode, in the workspace settings."},{"symptom":"On Mac the app won't open and says it is 'damaged' or 'from an unidentified developer'; on Windows SmartScreen blocks the installer.","fix":"On Mac, right-click (or Control-click) the AnythingLLM icon and choose Open, then confirm — this approves it once. On Windows, click 'More info' on the SmartScreen prompt and then 'Run anyway'. Only do this because you downloaded it from the official anythingllm.com."}],"tips":["Keep unrelated topics in separate workspaces (one for research, one for personal records). Each workspace has its own document index, so the AI never bleeds facts from one into another.","Set the workspace chat mode to 'Query' when you want answers strictly from your files, and 'Chat' when you want the model to blend its own knowledge in. Query mode gives fewer made-up answers.","Always click the 'Citations' link under an answer and read the source passage before trusting anything important — local models can still be confident and wrong.","Fewer, cleaner documents beat one giant messy dump. Well-structured PDFs and text files chunk and retrieve far better than scanned image-only PDFs (which have no selectable text to embed).","You can swap the chat model anytime in Settings without re-embedding your documents — the embeddings belong to the embedder, not the chat model — so experiment with llama3.2 versus gemma3 to see which answers your material best."],"difficulty":"Intermediate — comfortable installing apps and copy-pasting a few terminal commands","time":"About 30–45 minutes"},{"id":"lab9","n":9,"cat":"D","title":"Deep RAG Pipeline — Embeddings, Chunking & Local Vectors","tagline":"Build a fully offline \"chat with your documents\" system on your own computer, where an AI answers questions using only your files — the data never leaves your machine.","whatItIs":"RAG (Retrieval-Augmented Generation) is a way of using an AI so that instead of answering from memory, it first looks things up in your own documents and then answers based on what it found. To do the \"looking up,\" your files are turned into lists of numbers called embeddings (vectors) that capture meaning, and those numbers are stored in a vector database so the system can find the passages most related to your question — even when you don't use the exact same words. In this lab you build the whole pipeline locally: an embedding model (nomic-embed-text) running through Ollama turns your text into vectors, and AnythingLLM automatically chunks your documents, creates the embeddings, and stores them in a built-in local vector database called LanceDB. The result is a private \"chat with your PDFs and notes\" app that runs entirely on your computer.","whyUseIt":"RAG dramatically reduces made-up answers (\"hallucinations\") because the model is instructed to answer from the passages retrieved from your documents rather than guessing, and good tools will cite which document a fact came from so you can check it. Doing it locally means sensitive files — student records under FERPA, health data under HIPAA, contracts, financials — are indexed and searched entirely on your own drive, with nothing sent to a cloud API and no third-party retention. It also costs roughly nothing per question because open-weight models run on hardware you already own, versus per-token or subscription cloud pricing. Use it whenever you need answers grounded in a specific, private, or large set of documents that a general chatbot has never seen. Be honest about limits, though: local models are weaker than frontier cloud models on the hardest reasoning, retrieval can miss the right passage, and \"runs locally\" does not by itself make you FERPA- or HIPAA-compliant — you still verify the answers and follow your organization's rules.","bestFor":"Non-technical beginners, business analysts, and privacy-conscious administrators who want a private, offline \"ask my documents\" assistant for sensitive or bulky files without writing code.","platforms":["Windows","macOS","Linux"],"prerequisites":["Ollama installed first — this lab pulls the embedding model through it. If you have not installed Ollama, do that lab before this one (download from ollama.com and run the installer).","AnythingLLM Desktop, a free app you will download in Step 3 from anythingllm.com. It is the beginner-friendly GUI that does the chunking, embedding, and vector storage for you.","About 8 GB of RAM is comfortable. The embedding model is tiny (~274 MB), and a small chat model like Llama 3.x 8B or Gemma at 4-bit (Q4) quantization fits in roughly 8 GB. 16 GB+ is smoother.","Around 5-8 GB of free disk space: ~274 MB for the embedding model, a few GB for a chat model, plus room for your documents and the local vector database.","A few sample documents to test with — a couple of PDFs, Word docs, or .txt files. Start with non-sensitive files while you learn.","No coding experience and no accounts required. Everything runs offline once the models are downloaded."],"steps":[{"title":"Open a terminal (the text-command window)","detail":"A terminal is just a window where you type commands instead of clicking. You'll paste one line at a time — no need to understand it.","do":["On Windows, click the Start menu, type powershell, and click 'Windows PowerShell'.","On a Mac, press Command+Spacebar, type terminal, and press Enter.","On Linux, open the app called 'Terminal' in your applications."],"commands":[],"check":"a window opens with a blinking cursor waiting for you to type."},{"title":"Confirm Ollama is installed and running","detail":"Ollama is the free engine that runs AI models on your computer. This checks that it's installed before you go further.","do":["Type the first command below and press Enter — it should print a version number like 'ollama version 0.x.x'.","If you see 'command not found' or 'not recognized', go to ollama.com, download and run the installer, then reopen the terminal and try again.","Type the second command and press Enter to list any models you already have — it's fine if the list is empty."],"commands":["ollama --version","ollama list"],"check":"a version number is printed on the screen."},{"title":"Download the embedding model (turns text into numbers)","detail":"An embedding model converts your text into lists of numbers that capture meaning — this is what makes 'search by meaning' work. Here you download it.","do":["Type the command below and press Enter.","Watch the progress bar as it downloads about 274 MB — this can take a minute or two.","Wait for the word 'success' to appear."],"commands":["ollama pull nomic-embed-text"],"check":"the progress bar completes and you see the word 'success'."},{"title":"Download a small chat model to answer questions","detail":"This is the conversational model that actually writes the answers. It's a bigger download, so give it a few minutes.","do":["Type the command below and press Enter to download Meta's Llama 3.1 8B model.","If you have less memory, instead run 'ollama pull phi4-mini'; if you have 16 GB or more, you could try 'ollama pull gemma3'.","Wait a few minutes for the larger download to finish.","Leave this terminal window open so Ollama keeps serving in the background."],"commands":["ollama pull llama3.1:8b"],"check":"another progress bar completes and ends in 'success'."},{"title":"Install AnythingLLM Desktop (the click-and-point RAG app)","detail":"AnythingLLM is the point-and-click app that ties the whole RAG pipeline together. This step installs it.","do":["Open your web browser and go to anythingllm.com.","Click the Download button for AnythingLLM Desktop for your operating system (Windows, Mac, or Linux).","Run the downloaded installer, accept the defaults, and click through.","When it opens the first time, click through any setup wizard — you can change settings later."],"commands":[],"check":"the AnythingLLM app opens to a home screen with a sidebar on the left."},{"title":"Point AnythingLLM at your local Ollama models","detail":"Here you connect the app to the models you downloaded in Steps 3–4, so it knows which AI brain and embedder to use.","do":["In AnythingLLM, open Settings (the gear or wrench icon, usually bottom-left).","Under 'LLM Preference', choose 'Ollama' as the provider — it should auto-detect the address http://localhost:11434 — then pick llama3.1:8b.","Under 'Embedding Preference', choose 'Ollama' again and select nomic-embed-text.","Under 'Vector Database', confirm it says 'LanceDB'.","Click Save on each section."],"commands":[],"check":"each section shows Ollama and your models selected with no red error messages."},{"title":"Understand chunking and overlap before you upload","detail":"This step is just to understand what's happening under the hood — you don't change anything. Your documents get cut into small overlapping 'chunks' before they're indexed.","do":["Know that documents are cut into 'chunks' of about 1,000 characters each because they're too big to index whole.","Know that consecutive chunks share about 100 characters of 'overlap' so no sentence gets sliced in half.","If you want to see these, open a workspace's settings and look for 'Text splitting & Chunking'.","Leave the defaults as they are — you don't need to change anything."],"commands":[],"check":"you can find the chunking settings and see sensible default numbers."},{"title":"Create a workspace and upload your sample documents","detail":"Now you feed the pipeline real files. When you save them, the embedding model turns each chunk into vectors and stores them locally.","do":["Click 'New Workspace' in the left sidebar and give it a name like 'My Docs'.","Open the workspace and click the upload area (often a paperclip or 'Upload' button).","Drag in a few sample files (PDF, .docx, or .txt).","Once they appear in the list, select them and click 'Save and Embed' (or 'Move to Workspace' then 'Save').","Wait while the 'embedding' progress indicator runs."],"commands":[],"check":"your documents show a status of embedded/vectorized and appear inside the workspace, ready to chat."},{"title":"Ask a question and confirm it answers from your files","detail":"The final test: ask something only your files can answer, then check the citation to confirm the whole RAG pipeline works.","do":["Click into the workspace chat box.","Ask something that can only be answered from your uploaded documents — a specific figure, name, or clause you know is inside them.","Wait for the answer — the very first one may take 10–30+ seconds while the model loads.","Click the 'citations' or 'sources' link to verify which document the answer came from."],"commands":[],"check":"you get a correct, document-grounded answer with a citation pointing to your file — proof the full RAG pipeline is working entirely offline."}],"resources":[{"label":"Ollama — download and docs (the local model engine)","url":"https://ollama.com"},{"label":"nomic-embed-text model page on Ollama (the embedding model)","url":"https://ollama.com/library/nomic-embed-text"},{"label":"AnythingLLM — download the desktop app (beginner RAG GUI, built-in LanceDB)","url":"https://anythingllm.com"},{"label":"AnythingLLM documentation (workspaces, embeddings, chunking, vector DB settings)","url":"https://docs.anythingllm.com"},{"label":"Video search phrase: 'Understanding embeddings how text becomes numbers explained'"},{"label":"Video search phrase: 'AnythingLLM Ollama local RAG chat with your documents tutorial'"}],"cloudTieIn":"This local RAG stack is the same idea behind features you may already use in the cloud: Microsoft Copilot answering from your SharePoint/OneDrive files, ChatGPT's 'chat with a PDF' and its file/knowledge features, Claude answering over uploaded documents or Projects, and Gemini grounding answers in your Google Drive — all of them retrieve relevant chunks from your documents and feed them to a model, exactly like what you built here. The difference is where the data lives: your local pipeline keeps sensitive files (student records, health data, contracts) entirely on your machine, while the cloud tools send that content to a provider. A practical pattern is to use local RAG as the private default for identifiable or regulated data, and reach for Copilot/Claude/ChatGPT/Gemini when you need their stronger reasoning on non-sensitive material, larger scale, or team collaboration. Local complements cloud — it does not replace it.","troubleshooting":[{"symptom":"The chat says something like 'connection refused' or AnythingLLM can't find any Ollama models.","fix":"Ollama isn't running or the address is wrong. Make sure the Ollama app/service is running (reopen it, or run 'ollama list' in a terminal — if that works, Ollama is up). In AnythingLLM's LLM and Embedding settings, confirm the base URL is exactly http://localhost:11434, then click Save and reload the app."},{"symptom":"Your chosen model 'won't load', crashes, or the app reports out of memory.","fix":"The model is too big for your RAM/VRAM. Use a smaller, 4-bit (Q4) model: pull 'phi4-mini' or a smaller Llama/Gemma variant, close other heavy apps (browsers with many tabs, video calls), and select the smaller model in AnythingLLM's LLM Preference. The tiny nomic-embed-text embedding model rarely causes memory issues; the chat model is the culprit."},{"symptom":"The very first answer takes a long time (10-30+ seconds) or seems frozen.","fix":"This is normal — the model is being loaded into memory the first time. Wait; it isn't stuck. Subsequent questions in the same session are much faster because the model stays loaded. If every answer is very slow, your machine is memory-constrained — switch to a smaller model."},{"symptom":"The AI answers from general knowledge instead of your documents, or says it has no information.","fix":"Your files may not be embedded into that workspace. Reopen the workspace's document manager, confirm each file shows an 'embedded/vectorized' status, and click 'Save and Embed' if not. Also make sure you're chatting inside the workspace that contains the documents, and ask a question whose answer is actually in the files."},{"symptom":"'ollama pull' fails, stalls, or errors partway through the download.","fix":"It's usually a network hiccup. Check your internet, then run the same 'ollama pull' command again — it resumes and re-verifies. Corporate networks or VPNs sometimes block it; try a different network. Confirm you have several GB of free disk space."},{"symptom":"A port-in-use error, or two tools fight over the same address.","fix":"Ollama uses http://localhost:11434 and (if you ever add LM Studio) that uses http://localhost:1234 — they don't conflict. If something else already occupies 11434, quit the other program using it, or restart your computer to clear the stuck process, then relaunch Ollama and AnythingLLM."}],"tips":["Start with a few small, non-sensitive documents to learn the workflow, then scale up to the real files once you trust the answers and citations.","Always open the 'citations/sources' on an answer and confirm the cited passage really says what the model claims — RAG reduces hallucinations but doesn't eliminate them, and local models still make mistakes on hard questions.","Keep chunk size around 1,000 characters with ~100-character overlap as your default; only tune it if answers feel like they're missing context that spans across a boundary.","Use one workspace per topic or project. Mixing unrelated documents in one workspace makes retrieval noisier and answers less accurate.","'Runs locally' keeps data on your machine, but it does not automatically make you FERPA- or HIPAA-compliant — follow your organization's data-handling rules and still verify outputs before relying on them."],"difficulty":"Intermediate — comfortable using a terminal and copy-pasting commands","time":"About 30–60 minutes (mostly waiting for model downloads)"},{"id":"lab10","n":10,"cat":"D","title":"Vector Database Deployment (Chroma / Milvus via Docker)","tagline":"Run an industrial-grade vector database (ChromaDB) as a background service on your own computer using Docker, so your local AI apps can store and search thousands of documents fast.","whatItIs":"A vector database is a special kind of database built to store the \"meaning\" of text as long lists of numbers (called embeddings or vectors) and to instantly find the most similar pieces of text to a question. This is the memory engine behind RAG (\"Retrieval-Augmented Generation\"), where a local AI model answers using YOUR documents instead of only its training. In this lab you install Docker Desktop (a free tool that runs small pre-packaged programs called \"containers\") and use it to launch ChromaDB, a popular open-source vector database, as an always-on service on your machine. \"Via Docker\" simply means you download one ready-made package and start it with a single command instead of installing the database by hand.","whyUseIt":"Most beginner RAG tools (like AnythingLLM) ship with a tiny built-in vector store that is fine for a few files but crawls once you load hundreds or thousands of dense academic PDFs. A dedicated engine like ChromaDB indexes and searches far faster, survives app restarts, and can be shared: several local apps and Python scripts can all read and write the SAME document index instead of each keeping its own copy. Running it locally keeps every document and embedding on your own machine, which matters for privacy and for regulated data like FERPA-protected student records or HIPAA-protected health data, where sending files to a cloud service is the risk you are trying to avoid. It is also essentially free to run, since it uses your own hardware rather than a per-request cloud bill. Local complements cloud: you keep sensitive indexing on your machine and reach for cloud tools only when you deliberately choose to.","bestFor":"Someone building a personal or classroom knowledge base over many PDFs who has outgrown a single app's built-in storage and wants a fast, private, shareable document index that stays entirely on their own computer.","platforms":["Windows 11 (and Windows 10, build 19044 or newer)","macOS (Apple Silicon and Intel)","Linux"],"prerequisites":["A computer with at least 8 GB of RAM (16 GB is more comfortable) and roughly 5-10 GB of free disk space for Docker plus the database and your documents.","Windows only: the free WSL 2 feature (Docker Desktop turns this on for you during install; it needs Windows 10 build 19044 or newer, or any Windows 11).","A free Docker account is optional but recommended, since Docker Desktop may prompt you to sign in the first time you open it.","Administrator access to your own computer so you can install software.","Optional but recommended for actually using the database: Ollama already installed and running (its local API lives at http://localhost:11434) so you have a local model to generate embeddings and answers.","Optional: AnythingLLM installed if you plan to point a friendly desktop app at your new database instead of writing code."],"steps":[{"title":"Open your terminal (the black text window) and confirm you can type in it","detail":"The terminal is a window where you type commands instead of clicking buttons. You don't need to understand it yet — you just need it open.","do":["On Windows: click the Start menu (the Windows icon at the bottom-left of your screen).","Type the word  powershell , then click \"Windows PowerShell\" or \"Terminal\" when it appears.","On a Mac: press Command+Spacebar to open Spotlight, type  terminal , and press Enter.","Leave the window open — you will come back to it throughout this lab."],"commands":[],"check":"a window with some text and a blinking cursor is waiting for you to type."},{"title":"Download and install Docker Desktop","detail":"Docker Desktop is a free program that runs small pre-packaged apps called containers. You download and install it once here.","do":["Open your web browser and go to the official Docker download page (the link is in Resources below).","Click the big download button for YOUR system — Windows, Mac Apple Silicon, or Mac Intel (on a newer Mac, if unsure, choose Apple Silicon).","When the file finishes downloading, double-click it to start the installer.","Follow the installer and accept the default options (on Windows, leave the \"Use WSL 2\" box checked).","When it asks, allow it to restart your computer.","After restarting, open Docker Desktop from your Start menu or Applications folder.","Accept the service agreement, and if it asks you to sign in, click \"Continue without signing in\" or make a free account.","Wait until the small whale icon stops animating in your taskbar (Windows, bottom-right) or menu bar (Mac, top-right)."],"commands":[],"check":"a window titled Docker Desktop is open and the whale icon has stopped animating, which means the engine is running."},{"title":"Prove Docker is actually running before you build anything","detail":"This quick check confirms Docker is installed and running before you go further. It simply prints the version number.","do":["Go back to your terminal window from Step 1.","Type the command below exactly, then press Enter.","Read the result: a line like \"Docker version 27.x.x, build ...\" (any numbers are fine) means Docker is alive.","If you see \"command not found\" or \"not recognized\", open Docker Desktop, wait for the whale to go solid, then try again."],"commands":["docker --version"],"check":"you see one line of text showing a Docker version number."},{"title":"Create a folder to hold your database files so nothing is lost when you restart","detail":"A container normally forgets everything when it stops. Making a real folder on your disk lets ChromaDB save your data permanently.","do":["Make sure you are in your terminal window.","If you are on Windows, type the first command below and press Enter.","If you are on a Mac or Linux, type the second command below and press Enter instead.","Notice the text at the start of your terminal line now ends with \"chroma-data\" — that means you are inside the new folder."],"commands":["mkdir chroma-data; cd chroma-data    # Windows PowerShell","mkdir -p ~/chroma-data && cd ~/chroma-data    # Mac / Linux"],"check":"the text at the start of your terminal line ends with \"chroma-data\", showing you are inside that folder."},{"title":"Start ChromaDB with a single command","detail":"This one command downloads ChromaDB and starts it as a running database. The first download can take a couple of minutes — that is normal.","do":["Type the command below exactly and press Enter.","Wait while Docker downloads the ChromaDB package the first time — do not close the window.","Watch for a burst of startup text ending with \"Application startup complete\" and \"Uvicorn running on http://0.0.0.0:8000\".","Notice the terminal then appears to \"hang\" with no new prompt — that is correct; it is showing the database's live log.","Leave this window open — the database is running inside it."],"commands":["docker run -v ./chroma-data:/data -p 8000:8000 chromadb/chroma"],"check":"the startup text ends with \"Application startup complete\" and \"Uvicorn running on http://0.0.0.0:8000\", and the terminal stays open showing the log."},{"title":"Verify the database is reachable from a browser","detail":"This confirms the database is alive and answering requests. You are visiting its built-in \"are-you-alive\" check in a web browser.","do":["Leave the terminal from Step 5 running.","Open your web browser.","Click the address bar, type the address below exactly, and press Enter.","Look for a tiny bit of text such as {\"nanosecond heartbeat\": 17...} with a big number — that is proof the server answered.","If the browser says the site can't be reached, check the Step 5 terminal for red error text and see Troubleshooting."],"commands":["http://localhost:8000/api/v2/heartbeat"],"check":"the browser shows a small bit of text like {\"nanosecond heartbeat\": 17...} with a big number."},{"title":"Connect a local app (AnythingLLM) to your new database, no code needed","detail":"This connects a real app to your new database with no code. Every document you upload will now be stored and searched in ChromaDB.","do":["Open AnythingLLM (if you installed it).","Click the gear/Settings icon.","Find the \"Vector Database\" section.","Change the provider from the default (usually \"LanceDB\") to \"Chroma\".","In the endpoint or host field, enter exactly  http://localhost:8000 .","Save the settings.","Optionally, pair this with a local model in Ollama at http://localhost:11434 so both the answering and the retrieval stay on your machine."],"commands":[],"check":"AnythingLLM saves without an error, and after you upload a document you see new activity appear in your Step 5 terminal log."},{"title":"Or connect from a tiny Python script (optional, for the code-curious)","detail":"This optional step talks to the database using a little Python code instead of an app. It proves your own programs can read and write the shared index.","do":["Open a SECOND terminal window, keeping the first one running the server.","Type the first command below to install the client library, and press Enter.","Create a file named  test_chroma.py  and paste in the lines shown between the install and run commands.","Save the file.","Run the last command below and press Enter.","If \"pip\" is not recognized, install Python first from python.org, then retry."],"commands":["pip install chromadb","# test_chroma.py","import chromadb","client = chromadb.HttpClient(host='localhost', port=8000)","col = client.get_or_create_collection('demo')","col.add(documents=['The library closes at 9pm on weekdays.'], ids=['1'])","print(col.query(query_texts=['When does the library close?'], n_results=1))","python test_chroma.py"],"check":"the script prints your test sentence back as the closest match."},{"title":"Stop and restart the database when you are done","detail":"This shows you how to shut the database down safely and start it again another day. Your data stays saved in the chroma-data folder either way.","do":["To stop the server, click the Step 5 terminal window and press Ctrl+C (hold Control and tap C).","To start it again another day, open Docker Desktop first and wait for the solid whale.","Then rerun the same \"docker run\" command from Step 5 inside your chroma-data folder.","Alternatively, use the play and stop buttons next to the container under the \"Containers\" tab in Docker Desktop — no terminal needed."],"commands":["# Press Ctrl+C in the server terminal to stop","docker run -v ./chroma-data:/data -p 8000:8000 chromadb/chroma    # to start again"],"check":"the container shows as \"Running\" (green) or \"Exited\" in Docker Desktop's Containers list, matching what you intended."}],"resources":[{"label":"Docker Desktop official download (choose your OS)","url":"https://www.docker.com/products/docker-desktop/"},{"label":"Install Docker Desktop on Windows (WSL 2 requirements and steps)","url":"https://docs.docker.com/desktop/setup/install/windows-install/"},{"label":"Install Docker Desktop on Mac (Apple Silicon and Intel)","url":"https://docs.docker.com/desktop/setup/install/mac-install/"},{"label":"ChromaDB official Docker deployment guide","url":"https://docs.trychroma.com/guides/deploy/docker"},{"label":"ChromaDB official Docker image on Docker Hub","url":"https://hub.docker.com/r/chromadb/chroma"},{"label":"AnythingLLM (desktop RAG app that can use Chroma as its vector store)","url":"https://anythingllm.com"},{"label":"Ollama (local model + embeddings API at localhost:11434)","url":"https://ollama.com"},{"label":"Video search phrase: 'What is a vector database explained for beginners'"},{"label":"Video search phrase: 'ChromaDB Docker setup tutorial RAG'"}],"cloudTieIn":"Frontier cloud assistants like Microsoft Copilot, Anthropic Claude, OpenAI ChatGPT, and Google Gemini all use vector search behind the scenes when they answer over files you attach or a knowledge base you connect, that \"search your documents for the relevant bit, then answer\" pattern is exactly what you just built locally with ChromaDB. The difference is where your documents live: with the cloud tools your files and their embeddings are processed on someone else's servers, while your local Chroma index never leaves your machine, which is the safer default for FERPA student records or HIPAA health data. A practical hybrid is common: keep the sensitive index local in Chroma with an open-weight model (Qwen 3.5, Gemma 4, or Llama 3.x via Ollama, typically at 4-bit/Q4 to fit consumer RAM), and still reach for Claude, ChatGPT, Gemini, or Copilot on non-sensitive or hardest questions where a frontier model is clearly stronger. Skills you learn here, chunking documents, embedding them, and querying by similarity, map directly onto how the cloud RAG features work, so this lab also demystifies what those cloud tools are doing.","troubleshooting":[{"symptom":"The 'docker run' command fails with 'Cannot connect to the Docker daemon' or 'docker: error during connect'.","fix":"Docker Desktop is not running. Open Docker Desktop from your Start menu or Applications folder and wait until the whale icon in the taskbar/menu bar stops animating and turns solid, then rerun the command."},{"symptom":"Error says 'port is already allocated' or 'bind: address already in use' for port 8000.","fix":"Another program is already using door 8000. Either stop that program, or start Chroma on a different door by changing the left number: use -p 8010:8000 in the run command, and then browse to http://localhost:8010/api/v2/heartbeat and connect your apps to port 8010 instead."},{"symptom":"Browser says 'This site can't be reached' or 'connection refused' at the heartbeat URL.","fix":"The server isn't running or isn't finished starting. Check the Step 5 terminal: if you don't see 'Application startup complete', wait a few more seconds; if you see red error text, copy the container down with Ctrl+C and rerun the command. Also confirm you typed http:// (not https://) and the exact path /api/v2/heartbeat."},{"symptom":"The first 'docker run' hangs for a long time or looks stuck downloading.","fix":"The very first run downloads the ChromaDB image (a few hundred megabytes), which is normal and can take several minutes on a slow connection. Watch for progress bars/percentages. Only worry if it errors out or shows no movement for many minutes, in which case check your internet and rerun."},{"symptom":"Your machine slows to a crawl or Docker reports it is out of memory while indexing many PDFs.","fix":"Vector indexing is memory-hungry. Close other heavy apps, and in Docker Desktop go to Settings > Resources and lower or raise the memory limit to match your RAM (leave a few GB for Windows/macOS). Index documents in smaller batches rather than dumping thousands of PDFs at once."},{"symptom":"You restarted your computer and your uploaded documents seem gone.","fix":"You almost certainly started the container without the -v folder link, or from a different folder. Always run the command from inside the same chroma-data folder (Step 4) with the -v ./chroma-data:/data flag so the data is read back from disk. Data saved with that flag persists across restarts."}],"tips":["Keep the server terminal window open and visible while you work, its live log is the fastest way to see whether your app is actually reaching the database (new lines appear on every request).","Give your embeddings a consistent model: whatever tool loads documents, use the SAME embedding model every time (for example one from Ollama), because vectors made by different models are not comparable and will silently return bad search results.","Use Docker Desktop's 'Containers' tab as a GUI: you can start, stop, view logs, and delete the Chroma container with buttons instead of memorizing commands.","Name your container so it is easy to manage: add --name chroma to the run command, then you can simply run 'docker stop chroma' and 'docker start chroma' later.","Local models are genuinely weaker on the hardest reasoning and precision tasks than frontier cloud models, always spot-check RAG answers against the source document, and remember local does not automatically make you FERPA/HIPAA compliant; it removes the third-party-sharing risk but you still control access, backups, and disk encryption."],"difficulty":"Intermediate — comfortable installing apps and copy-pasting commands","time":"About 30–45 minutes, plus a short database download"},{"id":"lab11","n":11,"cat":"A","title":"Ollama + Hermes Agent — A Local Coding Teaching Assistant","tagline":"Set up a fully local, private AI coding teaching assistant on one laptop — Ollama serves the model, Hermes Agent turns it into an autonomous agent that reads files, runs code in a sandbox, and writes feedback, all without student data ever leaving the machine.","whatItIs":"Ollama is a free program that downloads an open-weight AI model and runs it entirely on your own computer, serving it at a local web address (http://localhost:11434) that other programs can talk to. Hermes Agent, from Nous Research (open-source, MIT-licensed), is a separate program that wraps that local model in an \"agent\" — instead of just answering one question, it can read your files, run commands in your terminal, and write output, chaining many steps toward a goal you describe in plain English. Together they form a coding teaching assistant that can read student homework, run the tests, and write per-student feedback. Because both run locally, nothing is ever sent to the cloud.","whyUseIt":"For a professor, student submissions, names, and grades are protected \"education records\" under FERPA — running the whole pipeline on your own laptop keeps those records on-premises instead of handing them to a third-party cloud service. It also costs nothing per use: open-weight models have no per-token or subscription bill, unlike ChatGPT, Claude, or Copilot. An agent (rather than a plain chatbot) matters here because grading is multi-step: read a file, run its tests, compare to a rubric, write feedback, repeat — the agent loops through that on its own. Use it when your data is sensitive or identifiable, when you want zero ongoing cost, or when you want to work fully offline. The honest trade-off: a local model is weaker than frontier cloud models on the hardest reasoning, so you must review every grade — the agent is a first pass, never the final word, and running locally is not the same as being automatically compliant.","bestFor":"A non-technical instructor who grades and tutors programming homework and needs student records to stay on their own device for FERPA reasons while paying nothing per use.","platforms":["macOS (Apple Silicon, the primary target)","Windows 11","Linux"],"prerequisites":["Ollama must be installed first — it is the engine that runs the model. Install it before Hermes Agent.","Roughly 30 GB of free disk space for the model file, plus headroom for the model's working memory (the KV cache).","RAM/unified memory: the workshop targets a Mac with 48 GB. A 30B mixture-of-experts coding model at 4-bit needs about 20-24 GB free once a 64K context is loaded; 24 GB is a comfortable floor, 16 GB is tight and may force a smaller model.","Administrator rights on your computer so the installers can run.","Docker Desktop (recommended, not required) — only needed for the safe grading sandbox in the last steps. Install it if you will run untrusted student code.","Python with pytest installed, if you want the agent to auto-run unit tests against submissions."],"steps":[{"title":"Open your terminal (the text window you will type commands into)","detail":"The terminal is a plain window where you type commands instead of clicking buttons. You will copy commands exactly and press Enter after each one.","do":["On a Mac: press Command+Spacebar to open Spotlight, type the word  Terminal , and press Enter.","On Windows: click the Start button, type  PowerShell , and click \"Windows PowerShell\".","Wait for a window with a blinking cursor to appear."],"commands":[],"check":"a window with a blinking cursor is waiting for you to type."},{"title":"Install Ollama, the engine that runs the model locally","detail":"Ollama is the free program that downloads and runs the AI model directly on your computer. You install it once here.","do":["Open your web browser and go to  ollama.com/download .","Download the installer for your system, open it, and follow the prompts.","On a Mac, Ollama becomes a small icon in the top menu bar — launch it once.","Mac users who prefer the terminal can instead run the first command below (Homebrew).","Confirm it worked by typing the second command below and pressing Enter — you should see a version number like \"ollama version 0.x.x\"."],"commands":["brew install --cask ollama","ollama --version"],"check":"typing  ollama --version  prints a version number like \"ollama version 0.x.x\"."},{"title":"Download (pull) the local coding model","detail":"\"Pulling\" just means downloading the AI model to your computer once — after that it stays. This is a large file, so it can take a while.","do":["Type the first command below and press Enter to download the workshop's target model.","If that exact tag is not available yet, type the last command instead to pull the real current equivalent (qwen3-coder:30b).","Wait as it downloads roughly 20–30 GB — a progress bar fills to 100%.","Watch for the word \"success\" and your cursor returning."],"commands":["ollama pull qwen3.5:35b-a3b-coding-nvfp4","# if that tag isn't available yet, pull the real current equivalent:","ollama pull qwen3-coder:30b"],"check":"you see the word \"success\" and your cursor returns to the prompt."},{"title":"Raise the context window to 64K — the one step people skip and then fail on","detail":"The \"context window\" is how much text the model can hold in its head at once. Hermes Agent refuses to start unless it is raised to at least 64,000 tokens, so you bake that setting into a new named model.","do":["Copy all four lines of the first block below at once, paste them into the terminal, and press Enter — this creates a small recipe file called a Modelfile.","If you pulled qwen3-coder:30b instead, change the FROM line to that name.","Type the last command below and press Enter to build a new model named qwen35-coder-64k that you will use from now on.","Watch for a line reading \"success\"."],"commands":["cat > Modelfile <<'EOF'","FROM qwen3.5:35b-a3b-coding-nvfp4","PARAMETER num_ctx 64000","EOF","ollama create qwen35-coder-64k -f Modelfile"],"check":"a line reading \"success\" appears after the create command."},{"title":"Verify the model loads, shows 64000 context, and supports tools","detail":"Before an agent can work, two things must be true: the context must really read 64000, and the model must support \"tools\" (the ability to run commands and read files). These three checks confirm both.","do":["Type the first command below and press Enter — the model should reply with a friendly \"hello\".","Type the second command ( ollama ps ) and press Enter, then look at the CONTEXT column — it must read 64000, not a smaller number.","Type the third command ( ollama show qwen35-coder-64k ) and press Enter, then look for \"tools\" listed under capabilities."],"commands":["ollama run qwen35-coder-64k \"hello\"","ollama ps","ollama show qwen35-coder-64k"],"check":"you get a \"hello\" reply, CONTEXT reads 64000 in ollama ps, and \"tools\" appears in ollama show."},{"title":"Install Hermes Agent and point it at your local Ollama","detail":"Hermes Agent is the program that turns your local model into an autonomous agent. You install it and then tell it how to reach Ollama.","do":["Type the first command below and press Enter to install Hermes.","Type the second command ( source ~/.zshrc ) and press Enter to reload your shell so the new \"hermes\" command is recognized.","Type the third command ( hermes model ) and press Enter to open the interactive setup.","Choose the option for a Custom Endpoint / self-hosted / Ollama.","For Base URL, enter exactly  http://127.0.0.1:11434/v1  (the \"/v1\" at the end is required).","For API key, leave it blank and press Enter.","For Model name, enter  qwen35-coder-64k  (or your model's exact name).","For Context length, enter  64000 ."],"commands":["curl -fsSL https://hermes-agent.nousresearch.com/install.sh | bash","source ~/.zshrc","hermes model"],"check":"Hermes confirms the provider and model without an error."},{"title":"Start Hermes and confirm it can actually use a tool","detail":"Now you launch the agent and make sure it can take actions, not just chat. You give it a small task that forces it to look at your files.","do":["Type the command below and press Enter to launch the agent (or just  hermes  for the classic interface).","Look at the top for a banner naming your model and provider.","Type this instruction to it: \"List the files in this folder and tell me what the main project file is.\"","Watch to confirm Hermes actually runs a command to look at your files, rather than just guessing."],"commands":["hermes --tui"],"check":"the agent reports real file names from your folder instead of guessing."},{"title":"Lay out a teaching folder and give the agent one grading instruction","detail":"Now you give the agent a real job: grading. You set up a teaching folder with student work, your rubric, and an empty feedback folder, then start Hermes inside it so that is all it can see.","do":["Type the first command below and press Enter to create the teaching, hw3, and feedback folders.","Put one file per student submission inside the  hw3  folder.","Create a  rubric.md  file in the teaching folder with your grading criteria in plain English.","Type the second command ( cd ~/teaching ) and press Enter so the agent can only see this folder.","Type the third command ( hermes --tui ) and press Enter to start the agent.","Give it the single plain-English instruction shown in the last line below (read ./hw3, run pytest, score against rubric.md, write per-student feedback, then summarize common mistakes)."],"commands":["mkdir -p ~/teaching/hw3 ~/teaching/feedback","cd ~/teaching","hermes --tui","# then type this instruction to the agent:","# Read ./hw3, run pytest on each submission, score it against rubric.md, and write per-student feedback to ./feedback — give hints toward the fix, never the full solution. Then summarize the three most common mistakes across the whole class."],"check":"new files appear in the feedback folder, one per student."},{"title":"Harden the sandbox with Docker so untrusted student code is isolated","detail":"Running untrusted student code directly on your computer is risky. This step moves that code into an isolated Docker container so it cannot touch your real system.","do":["Install Docker Desktop from docker.com and launch it once.","Type the first command below and press Enter — a \"Hello from Docker!\" message confirms the engine works.","Type the second command below and press Enter to switch Hermes to the Docker backend.","Open  ~/.hermes/config.yaml  in a text editor and add the resource-limit block shown in the remaining lines below.","Keep  container_persistent: false  so the sandbox is wiped between sessions and no student data lingers."],"commands":["docker run --rm hello-world","hermes config set terminal.backend docker","# in ~/.hermes/config.yaml add:","# terminal:","#   backend: docker","#   docker_image: python:3.11-slim   # run 'pip install pytest' once inside","#   container_cpu: 1","#   container_memory: 5120           # MB","#   container_disk: 51200            # MB","#   container_persistent: false      # wipe workspace between sessions"],"check":"\"docker run --rm hello-world\" prints \"Hello from Docker!\" and Hermes is set to the docker backend."},{"title":"Cut the container's network so records cannot leave — then verify the lockdown","detail":"The last gap is the network — a record could still escape if the container can reach the internet. Here you cut the container off the network and verify every lock is in place.","do":["Type the first command ( docker ps ) and press Enter to find the Hermes container's name.","Type the second command below, replacing  <container>  with that name, and press Enter to disconnect it from the network.","Type the third command (again replacing  <container> ) and press Enter — confirm the network list reads empty ( {} ).","Type the fourth command and press Enter to check the lockdown.","Confirm it reads root-ro=true, caps-dropped=[ALL], pids=256, and net=none (or disconnected) — if anything else, STOP and re-check before grading real work.","On a Mac, optionally block Docker's outbound access in the macOS firewall or with a tool like Little Snitch so the rule survives restarts."],"commands":["docker ps","docker network disconnect bridge <container>","docker inspect -f '{{json .NetworkSettings.Networks}}' <container>   # expect {}","docker inspect -f 'root-ro={{.HostConfig.ReadonlyRootfs}} caps={{.HostConfig.CapDrop}} pids={{.HostConfig.PidsLimit}} net={{.HostConfig.NetworkMode}}' <container>"],"check":"the verify command reads root-ro=true, caps-dropped=[ALL], pids=256, and net=none (or disconnected), and the network list is empty ({})."}],"resources":[{"label":"Ollama — download, docs, and model library (install this first)","url":"https://ollama.com/download"},{"label":"Ollama × Hermes Agent official integration guide","url":"https://docs.ollama.com/integrations/hermes"},{"label":"Hermes Agent source code and README (Nous Research, MIT license)","url":"https://github.com/NousResearch/hermes-agent"},{"label":"Qwen3-Coder 30B model page on Ollama (the real, pullable coding model with tool-calling)","url":"https://ollama.com/library/qwen3-coder"},{"label":"Docker Desktop — download for Mac/Windows (needed only for the grading sandbox)","url":"https://www.docker.com/products/docker-desktop/"},{"label":"Docker Engine security and runtime hardening docs","url":"https://docs.docker.com/engine/security/"},{"label":"U.S. Dept. of Education — FERPA guidance for protecting education records","url":"https://studentprivacy.ed.gov"},{"label":"Video search phrase: 'Hermes Agent Ollama local setup 64K context tutorial'"},{"label":"Video search phrase: 'Ollama Qwen3-Coder local AI agent Docker sandbox walkthrough'"}],"cloudTieIn":"This local stack is the private, zero-cost sibling of the cloud coding assistants you may already use — Microsoft Copilot, Anthropic Claude, OpenAI ChatGPT, and Google Gemini. Those frontier models are stronger on the hardest reasoning and multi-file refactors, so keep reaching for them when the data is non-sensitive (public code, generic examples, your own scratch work) and you want the best possible answer. But the moment identifiable student records enter the picture — names, submissions, grades — FERPA makes local the safer default, because nothing is transmitted to a third-party processor. The workflow maps almost one-to-one: the plain-English instruction you would give Claude or Copilot ('grade these and give hints, not answers') is the same instruction you give Hermes; the difference is only where it runs. A common real-world pattern is to use the local agent for the confidential first pass over student work, then paste an anonymized, de-identified snippet into a cloud model when you want a second opinion on a tricky case. Local complements the cloud; it does not replace it.","troubleshooting":[{"symptom":"Hermes won't start and says the context is too small.","fix":"Your model is offering fewer than 64,000 tokens of context. Re-do the 64K step: rebuild the model with the Modelfile (PARAMETER num_ctx 64000) or re-run the launchctl setenv step and relaunch Ollama, then confirm with 'ollama ps' that the CONTEXT column reads 64000."},{"symptom":"Hermes replies in chat but never runs a tool (no files read, no tests run).","fix":"Either the model doesn't support function calling or the wrong model name is configured. Run 'ollama show <model>' and confirm 'tools' appears under capabilities; if not, use a tool-calling model like qwen3-coder:30b. Then re-run 'hermes model' and re-enter the exact model name."},{"symptom":"'Connection refused' or nothing listening on port 11434.","fix":"Ollama isn't running. Open the menu-bar app (Mac) or run 'ollama serve' in a terminal, then confirm the base URL in Hermes is exactly http://127.0.0.1:11434/v1 — the trailing /v1 is required. Check the engine with 'ollama ps'."},{"symptom":"Out-of-memory, the model won't load, or the whole machine crawls.","fix":"A 30B MoE model at 4-bit needs roughly 20-24 GB free once 64K context loads. Close other heavy apps; if you have under ~24 GB, pull a smaller tool-calling model (e.g. an 8B such as Llama 3.1 8B or Qwen3 8B) and set its name in Hermes. Only push the Mac GPU wired-memory limit (sudo sysctl iogpu.wired_limit_mb=40960) if you deliberately go far past 64K."},{"symptom":"The first response is very slow, then later ones are fast.","fix":"This is normal — the model is loading into memory on first use. Keep Ollama running between grading sessions so it stays warm; subsequent prompts are quick."},{"symptom":"'docker: command not found' or Docker can't connect.","fix":"Docker Desktop isn't installed or isn't running. Launch Docker Desktop and wait for its whale icon to stop animating, then confirm with 'docker run --rm hello-world' before re-running Hermes with the docker backend."},{"symptom":"The sandbox can still reach the internet (records could leak).","fix":"Disconnect the container from its network after it starts: 'docker ps' to get the name, then 'docker network disconnect bridge <container>', and verify with 'docker inspect' that the network list is empty ({}). For a durable rule, block Docker's outbound access in the macOS firewall or with Little Snitch so it survives restarts."}],"tips":["Run 'hermes doctor' whenever something feels off — it diagnoses config problems, and you should retest a plain chat before adding tools or Docker back in.","Scope the agent to Socratic HINTS, not answers, in your instruction and rubric — you want it to support learning, not do the assignment for the student.","Always keep a human in the loop: treat the agent's scores as a first pass and personally review and own every grade before it goes in the gradebook — local models are weaker on hard cases and must be verified.","Launch Hermes from inside your ~/teaching folder, never from your home directory, so the sandbox can only see this term's submissions — that data-minimization posture is exactly what FERPA expects.","Running locally protects privacy but does not make you automatically compliant: pair it with the Docker sandbox and the no-network step so you have three independent boundaries (local model, isolated execution, no exfiltration route)."],"difficulty":"Intermediate — comfortable installing apps, using the terminal, and copy-pasting commands","time":"About 45–60 minutes, plus a large one-time model download"},{"id":"lab12","n":12,"cat":"A","title":"OpenClaw — Personal AI Agents & Governance","tagline":"Stand up a private AI agent on your own computer that you can text from your phone — and lock it down like a data-governance officer so it can only do what you allow.","whatItIs":"OpenClaw (formerly Clawdbot) is a free, open-source \"personal AI agent\" that runs quietly in the background on your own computer. Unlike a chat window such as LM Studio or ChatGPT where you type and read replies, OpenClaw acts as an operator: it connects a local AI model to messaging apps you already use — WhatsApp, Telegram, Slack, Discord — so you can text it a request and it will actually do things (summarize a file, tidy a folder, draft a reply, search the web) using the computer it lives on. In this lab you point it at a model running locally through Ollama, so the \"brain\" stays on your machine at no per-message cost. It became famous in early 2026 for two reasons: it is genuinely useful, and it was at the center of a major security crisis, which makes it the perfect tool for learning how to govern an AI agent safely.","whyUseIt":"This lab teaches the single most important skill in modern AI operations: giving an AI real power and then fencing that power in. An agent that can read files and run actions is a productivity multiplier, but the same reach makes it a security liability if left open — in early 2026 more than 135,000 OpenClaw instances were exposed on the public internet and its plugin marketplace was flooded with roughly 820 malicious \"skills.\" Running it locally through Ollama gives you privacy (your messages and files never leave your machine), zero per-message cost (open-weight models are ~$0/token versus cloud subscriptions), and, for an education setting, a safer default for anything touching FERPA student records or HIPAA health data. Use this when you want hands-on practice being the data-governance officer: deciding who can message the agent, where it is allowed to read and write, and what it is forbidden to touch. Be honest with yourself — local models are weaker than frontier cloud models on the hardest reasoning, and local does NOT automatically mean compliant. You still verify its work and you still lock it down.","bestFor":"Non-technical students, executive assistants, and operations managers who want to automate everyday tasks by texting an AI, while learning first-hand how to govern and sandbox an AI agent so it cannot be abused.","platforms":["Windows","macOS","Linux"],"prerequisites":["Ollama must be installed and running FIRST — it is the local 'brain.' If you have not set it up, complete the Ollama lab before this one. Verify by opening a terminal and typing 'ollama --version'.","A computer with at least 16 GB of RAM (Windows/Linux) or 16 GB of unified memory (Apple Silicon Mac). Tool-use models like Gemma 4 12B or Qwen 3.5 9B need roughly 11-16 GB; on 8 GB you can try a smaller model but expect slower, weaker results.","About 15-20 GB of free disk space for the agent and one local model.","A free Telegram account on your phone (this lab uses Telegram because its bot setup is the simplest and safest for a first-timer).","A stable internet connection for the one-time download of the software and the model (after that, the agent runs offline).","About 45-60 minutes, and comfort typing a few commands exactly as shown — you do NOT need any prior coding experience."],"steps":[{"title":"Open your terminal (the place where you type commands)","detail":"The terminal is a window where you type instructions one line at a time and press Enter to run each one. You will leave it open for the whole lab.","do":["On Windows: click the Start menu, type the word  PowerShell , and click \"Windows PowerShell\".","On a Mac: press Command+Spacebar, type  Terminal , and press Enter.","Leave this window open for the whole lab."],"commands":[],"check":"a window with a blinking cursor is waiting for you to type."},{"title":"Confirm Ollama (the local brain) is alive before you connect anything to it","detail":"OpenClaw needs a running AI model to think with, and that comes from Ollama. These commands confirm Ollama works and that you have a model downloaded.","do":["Type the first command ( ollama --version ) and press Enter — it should print a version like \"ollama version 0.x.x\".","Type the second command ( ollama list ) and press Enter to see your downloaded models.","If the list is empty, type the third command ( ollama pull gemma4:12b ) and press Enter to download a capable model — this is several gigabytes and may take a while.","Note the address http://localhost:11434 — that is the private door on your own computer where Ollama listens."],"commands":["ollama --version","ollama list","ollama pull gemma4:12b"],"check":"the version prints and  ollama list  shows at least one model name."},{"title":"Install and launch OpenClaw the safe, managed way (through Ollama)","detail":"This installs and starts OpenClaw the safe, managed way through Ollama, which uses a known-good patched build instead of a risky script pasted from the internet.","do":["Type the command below and press Enter.","Wait while Ollama downloads OpenClaw and installs its background helper (the \"gateway\") the first time.","Read the security warnings about tool access when they appear — they are the point of this lab.","When prompted to pick a model, choose the gemma4 you downloaded."],"commands":["ollama launch openclaw"],"check":"you see a confirmation that the OpenClaw gateway is running, along with a local control address (commonly http://localhost:18789)."},{"title":"Point the agent's brain at your LOCAL model, not a cloud key","detail":"This makes sure OpenClaw's brain is your local model, not a paid cloud service. Keeping cloud keys out is what guarantees your data never leaves the machine.","do":["Type the command below and press Enter to open OpenClaw's configuration.","Find the provider/backend section and set the provider to Ollama.","Set the endpoint to exactly  http://localhost:11434 .","Set the model to your local one, for example  gemma4:12b  (or qwen3.5 if you downloaded that instead).","Do NOT paste any Anthropic or OpenAI API key here.","Save and exit when prompted."],"commands":["ollama launch openclaw --config"],"check":"the config shows provider = ollama, endpoint = http://localhost:11434, and a local model name, with no cloud key present."},{"title":"Create a private Telegram bot and give OpenClaw its token","detail":"A bot token is a long secret password that lets OpenClaw log in as your own Telegram bot. You create the bot in Telegram, then paste its token into OpenClaw.","do":["Open Telegram on your phone and search for the account named exactly  @BotFather  (it has a blue verified check).","Tap Start, then send the message  /newbot .","Give it a name (anything, e.g. \"My Ops Agent\") and a username that must end in \"bot\" (e.g. \"myops_helper_bot\").","Copy the token BotFather replies with — it looks like \"123456789:AAExxxx...\" — and keep it secret like a house key.","Back in the terminal, type the command below and press Enter to open the channels configuration.","Paste the token into the Telegram section."],"commands":["ollama launch openclaw --config"],"check":"the channels config shows Telegram enabled with your token, and OpenClaw reports it connected to Telegram."},{"title":"GOVERNANCE — lock the bot to only YOU (reject every stranger)","detail":"By default anyone who finds your bot could message it. This is the single most important control in the lab: you lock the bot so it answers only you and ignores everyone else.","do":["Open the channels configuration file  ~/.openclaw/openclaw.json  in a text editor.","Set the Telegram  dmPolicy  to \"pairing\" or \"allowlist\" (do the same for WhatsApp if you use it).","Add ONLY your own account or number to  allowFrom  — see the JSON shape below.","Set  groupPolicy  to \"disabled\" so it never acts on group chats.","Save the file."],"commands":["\"channels\": {","  \"telegram\": {","    \"dmPolicy\": \"pairing\",","    \"allowFrom\": [\"<your-telegram-username-or-id>\"],","    \"groupPolicy\": \"disabled\"","  }","}"],"check":"when you message the bot from YOUR Telegram it replies, but when a friend messages it they get nothing."},{"title":"GOVERNANCE — keep the network door shut and the files fenced in","detail":"Two more guardrails that address the 2026 security crisis: keep the control gateway reachable only from your own computer, and keep the agent boxed into its own folder.","do":["In the config, set  bindHost  to  127.0.0.1  so no other device on your Wi-Fi or the internet can reach the gateway.","Confirm the agent's working area is  ~/.openclaw/workspace  so it cannot roam your Desktop or Documents.","On Mac or Linux, type the three commands below one at a time, pressing Enter after each, to tighten the file permissions (700 = only you can open the folder; 600 = only you can read the secret files).","On Windows instead, confirm the folder lives under  C:\\Users\\<you>\\.openclaw  and is not shared."],"commands":["chmod 700 ~/.openclaw","chmod 600 ~/.openclaw/openclaw.json","chmod -R 600 ~/.openclaw/credentials/"],"check":"bindHost shows 127.0.0.1 and the workspace path is ~/.openclaw/workspace."},{"title":"Verify you are on a patched version and audit the setup","detail":"The 2026 crisis was driven by outdated builds and malicious add-ons. Here you confirm you are on a patched version and that nothing unsafe is installed.","do":["Type the first command below and press Enter to open the config, and confirm the version shown is  2026.1.29  or later (every earlier version is vulnerable to CVE-2026-25253).","Type the second command ( openclaw doctor ) and press Enter to check the gateway's health.","Type the third command ( openclaw status ) and press Enter to confirm it is running and bound to localhost.","Do NOT install any third-party skills from the ClawHub marketplace for this lab — roughly 820 of them were malicious."],"commands":["ollama launch openclaw --config","openclaw doctor","openclaw status"],"check":"the version shown is 2026.1.29 or newer, status reports the gateway running and bound to localhost, and no unknown skills are installed."},{"title":"Test it — text your agent a real task from your phone","detail":"Now you try the whole thing end to end by texting your agent a real task from your phone. Everything is generated on your own computer.","do":["Open your bot's chat in Telegram by tapping the username you created.","Send a simple, safe request such as \"What files are in your workspace folder?\" or \"Summarize this in one sentence: <paste a short paragraph>\".","Wait 20–60 seconds for the first reply while the local model wakes up — later replies are faster.","Watch the terminal to see the agent reason and act."],"commands":[],"check":"you get a sensible reply in Telegram, generated entirely by the model on your own computer with no data sent to any cloud service."}],"resources":[{"label":"Ollama OpenClaw integration guide (official docs)","url":"https://docs.ollama.com/integrations/openclaw"},{"label":"Ollama blog: OpenClaw launch announcement and setup","url":"https://ollama.com/blog/openclaw"},{"label":"OpenClaw official site","url":"https://openclaw.ai/"},{"label":"OpenClaw security news tracker (government warnings, CVEs, advisories)","url":"https://github.com/joylarkin/openclaw-security-news"},{"label":"Ollama model library (download Gemma 4, Qwen 3.5, Llama for local tool use)","url":"https://ollama.com/library"},{"label":"Video search phrase: 'How to Configure OpenClaw Safely with Ollama and Telegram 2026'"},{"label":"Video search phrase: 'Analysing the 2026 OpenClaw Security Crisis AI agent sandboxing lessons'"}],"cloudTieIn":"This local agent complements the frontier cloud tools you may already use — it does not replace them. Copilot, Claude, ChatGPT, and Gemini run on far larger models and will out-reason a local Gemma 4 or Qwen 3.5 on the hardest tasks, so keep reaching for them when you need maximum quality on NON-sensitive work. The trade is control: OpenClaw with Ollama keeps everything on your machine, which is the right default for FERPA student data, HIPAA health data, or anything you cannot send to a third party. The skills transfer directly — OpenClaw can also be pointed at an Anthropic or OpenAI API key instead of Ollama, so the exact same channel-pairing, localhost-binding, and workspace-sandbox governance you practiced here is what you would apply when wiring a cloud model into an agent. Think of it as a rehearsal: learn to fence in a local agent safely, and you will know how to govern a cloud-powered one.","troubleshooting":[{"symptom":"OpenClaw replies with an error like 'connection refused' or 'cannot reach model' and never answers.","fix":"The local brain is not running or the address is wrong. In a terminal run 'ollama list' to confirm Ollama is up, and re-check Step 4 so the provider endpoint is exactly http://localhost:11434 with a model you actually downloaded (e.g. gemma4:12b). Restart with 'ollama launch openclaw'."},{"symptom":"The very first reply takes 30-60 seconds or seems frozen.","fix":"This is normal — the local model has to load into memory the first time (a 'cold start'). Wait a minute; later replies are much faster. If it never responds, the model may be too big for your RAM (see the out-of-memory fix)."},{"symptom":"Everything is extremely slow, the reply is cut off, or the computer's fan roars and the app crashes (out of memory).","fix":"Your machine does not have enough RAM/VRAM for that model. Download a smaller one and point OpenClaw at it: run 'ollama pull llama3.1:8b' (or 'gemma4:e4b' for very small machines), then set that as the model in Step 4. Smaller models fit in 8 GB and respond faster, at some cost to answer quality."},{"symptom":"OpenClaw says a port is already in use, or the gateway won't start (default port 18789).","fix":"Another copy is probably already running. Close the extra terminal window, or run 'openclaw status' to see the running gateway. If needed, stop it and relaunch with 'ollama launch openclaw'. Only one gateway should run at a time."},{"symptom":"The bot ignores every message you send from Telegram.","fix":"Your governance allowlist is working but does not include YOU yet. In the channels config (Step 6) confirm your own Telegram username or numeric ID is listed in allowFrom, and that dmPolicy is 'pairing' or 'allowlist' (not a typo). Save and relaunch. If you are unsure of your ID, message @userinfobot on Telegram to get it."},{"symptom":"You are worried the version might be vulnerable, or a strange 'skill' appeared.","fix":"Run 'openclaw status' and confirm the version is 2026.1.29 or newer — every earlier version is exposed to the one-click takeover CVE-2026-25253. Do NOT install ClawHub marketplace skills for this lab (about 820 were malicious); remove any skill you did not add yourself, and confirm bindHost is 127.0.0.1 so nothing on the network can reach the gateway."}],"tips":["Never paste a 'curl ... | bash' install one-liner as a beginner. Use 'ollama launch openclaw' so you get a patched, managed build — casual script-piping is the exact loose habit that fueled the 2026 crisis.","Treat your Telegram bot token and the ~/.openclaw/credentials folder like house keys. Anyone who gets them controls your agent and everything it connects to. Never post a token in a chat, screenshot, or repo.","Start the agent with the narrowest powers, then widen only as needed. Keep it inside its ~/.openclaw/workspace folder and grant access to a real folder (like Documents) only for the specific task that requires it, then revoke.","Give the model a bigger context window (64k tokens or more) for local use, or it will 'forget' the start of long conversations and tool instructions mid-task.","Local does NOT equal automatically compliant. Running on your machine reduces exposure, but you are still responsible for verifying the agent's output and following your school's or employer's data rules — treat every action it takes as something you would sign your name to."],"difficulty":"Intermediate — comfortable installing apps, editing a config file, and copy-pasting commands","time":"About 30–45 minutes, plus a short model download"},{"id":"lab13","n":13,"cat":"A","title":"Multi-Agent Frameworks (CrewAI / Autogen Studio)","tagline":"Set up a local, private multi-agent AI team on your own computer, where several AI \"employees\" hand work to each other and finish a task together, with no cloud account and no data ever leaving your machine.","whatItIs":"A multi-agent framework is software that lets you run several AI \"agents\" at once and have them talk to each other and pass work down a line, like a small team. Instead of one chatbot answering you, you define roles, for example a Researcher that gathers facts, a Writer that drafts text, and a Compliance Editor that checks the draft, and the framework passes the output of one agent as the input to the next until the job is done. AutoGen Studio (from Microsoft) gives you this as a point-and-click dashboard in your web browser, so you build the team by clicking, not coding. CrewAI is a close cousin you drive with a short Python script when you want more control. In this lab both the agents and the AI model that powers them run entirely on your own computer using Ollama, so nothing is sent to any company's servers.","whyUseIt":"This is the leap from a single chatbot to autonomous teamwork: agents that plan, hand off, critique, and use tools without you babysitting every message. It is genuinely useful when a task has clear stages, for example research then draft then review, or extract then summarize then fact-check, because each agent can specialize and the handoffs are automatic. Running it locally with Ollama means the whole pipeline reads your files and produces output without any of that content touching a third party, which matters for FERPA-protected student records, HIPAA-protected health data, or any sensitive document, and it costs roughly $0 per token because open-weight models run on hardware you already own instead of a metered cloud bill. Local models are smaller and weaker than frontier cloud models, so they can be slower and make more mistakes on hard reasoning, which means a human must verify agent output before trusting it, and running it locally does not by itself make a workflow legally compliant. Use this lab to learn how agent orchestration actually works and to prototype safe, private automations; reach for the cloud when a task genuinely needs frontier-level quality.","bestFor":"A non-technical learner who has a working local model (via Ollama) and wants to see, hands-on, how a team of AI agents divides a task and hands work between them, entirely offline and private.","platforms":["Windows","macOS","Linux","Browser (the AutoGen Studio dashboard opens in your web browser)"],"prerequisites":["Ollama already installed and running, with at least one model pulled (for example `ollama pull llama3.1`). Ollama serves a local API at http://localhost:11434 that both frameworks connect to. If you have not set up Ollama yet, do that lab first.","Python 3.10, 3.11, or 3.12 installed (AutoGen Studio and CrewAI both require Python 3.10 or newer; CrewAI needs below 3.14). You will check this in Step 2 and install it if missing.","About 6-10 GB of free disk space (a few GB for the Python packages, plus room for the model Ollama already downloaded).","At least 8 GB of RAM (unified memory on Apple Silicon Macs, or system RAM plus VRAM on Windows/Linux). 8 GB comfortably runs a 3B-8B model at Q4 quantization, such as Llama 3.1 8B or Gemma; 16 GB or more lets you run 12B-32B models and gives agents more headroom.","A working internet connection for the one-time install of the software (the packages download from the internet). After setup, running the agents is fully offline.","About 45-60 minutes and a willingness to copy-paste a few commands into a terminal window (this lab tells you exactly how to open one)."],"steps":[{"title":"Confirm Ollama is running and has a model (your local \"engine\")","detail":"Both agent frameworks need a brain to think with — a model served by Ollama on your own machine. These commands confirm Ollama is on and has a model ready.","do":["Make sure Ollama is running: on Windows look for the Ollama llama icon in the system tray near the clock; on Mac look in the top menu bar.","Type the first command ( ollama list ) and press Enter to see your models.","If the list is empty, type the second command ( ollama pull llama3.1 ) and press Enter to download a small, capable model that fits 8 GB of memory.","Type the third command and press Enter to confirm the model prints a reply."],"commands":["ollama list","ollama pull llama3.1","ollama run llama3.1 \"say hello in one short sentence\""],"check":"ollama list shows at least one model (for example \"llama3.1:8b\") and  ollama run  prints a short reply."},{"title":"Open a terminal (the text window where you type commands)","detail":"A terminal is just a window where you type instructions instead of clicking. You do not need administrator rights, and you will use this window for every step below.","do":["On Windows: click the Start button, type the word  powershell , and click \"Windows PowerShell\" when it appears.","On a Mac: press Command+Spacebar to open Spotlight, type  terminal , and press Return.","On Linux: press Ctrl+Alt+T.","Leave this window open — you will use it for every step below."],"commands":[],"check":"a window with a blinking cursor is waiting for you to type."},{"title":"Create an isolated project folder and a Python \"virtual environment\"","detail":"A virtual environment is a private sandbox for this project, so anything you install here cannot break the rest of your computer. You will make a project folder and activate the sandbox inside it.","do":["Type the first command ( python --version ) and press Enter — you need it to say 3.10, 3.11, or 3.12.","If it says \"not found\" or an older number, install Python from python.org first (tick \"Add Python to PATH\" during the Windows installer).","Type the second command ( mkdir agent-lab ) and press Enter to make the project folder.","Type the third command ( cd agent-lab ) and press Enter to move into it.","Type the fourth command ( python -m venv venv ) and press Enter to create the sandbox.","Activate it: on Windows type  .\\venv\\Scripts\\Activate.ps1 ; on Mac or Linux type  source venv/bin/activate ."],"commands":["python --version","mkdir agent-lab","cd agent-lab","python -m venv venv","# Windows PowerShell:  .\\venv\\Scripts\\Activate.ps1","# Mac / Linux:         source venv/bin/activate"],"check":"\"(venv)\" appears at the start of your terminal prompt line."},{"title":"Install AutoGen Studio (the click-based agent dashboard)","detail":"AutoGen Studio is Microsoft's visual dashboard for building and running agent teams without writing code. This step downloads and installs it.","do":["Make sure  (venv)  is still showing at the start of your prompt.","Type the first command ( pip install -U autogenstudio ) and press Enter.","Wait 2–5 minutes while lines of text scroll by — this is the one step that uses the internet.","Optionally, if you want the script-based path in Step 8, type the last command ( pip install crewai ) and press Enter too."],"commands":["pip install -U autogenstudio","# optional, only if you want the script-based path in Step 8:","pip install crewai"],"check":"the scrolling stops and returns you to a normal prompt with no red \"ERROR\" text, and a final line mentions it installed \"autogenstudio\"."},{"title":"Point the agents at your LOCAL model instead of a paid cloud key","detail":"These frameworks expect a paid OpenAI key by default. You set a harmless placeholder so the software stops complaining — the value is never sent anywhere because the real thinking happens locally.","do":["On Windows, type  $env:OPENAI_API_KEY = \"local-not-used\"  and press Enter.","On Mac or Linux, type  export OPENAI_API_KEY=local-not-used  and press Enter instead.","Confirm the command finishes with no error message."],"commands":["# Windows PowerShell:","$env:OPENAI_API_KEY = \"local-not-used\"","# Mac / Linux:","export OPENAI_API_KEY=local-not-used"],"check":"the command finishes silently with no error message."},{"title":"Launch the AutoGen Studio dashboard in your browser","detail":"Now you start the dashboard and open it in your browser. It is served privately by your own machine, not from the web.","do":["Type the command below and press Enter.","Wait for a message like \"Application is running on http://localhost:8081\".","Open your web browser (Chrome, Edge, Safari, or Firefox).","Type  http://localhost:8081  into the address bar and press Enter.","Keep the terminal window open the whole time — closing it shuts the dashboard down."],"commands":["autogenstudio ui --port 8081"],"check":"the AutoGen Studio interface loads, with a left-hand menu showing sections like Team Builder, Playground, and Gallery."},{"title":"Add your local model and build a small agent team, then run it","detail":"This is where you build the actual team: add your local model, create a few agents with different jobs, and run them on a task. Watch them hand work to each other down the line.","do":["In the dashboard, go to the settings or \"Models\" area and add a new model.","Choose the Ollama provider and set the model name to exactly what  ollama list  showed (for example \"llama3.1\").","Set the base URL to  http://localhost:11434  — this is what makes the agents think locally.","Open Team Builder and create two or three agents with clear roles — for example a \"Researcher\", a \"Writer\", and a \"Compliance Editor\" — wiring each one to the Ollama model you just added.","Go to the Playground, pick your team, and type a task such as \"Summarize the attached notes into a short, policy-safe paragraph.\""],"commands":[],"check":"the chat panel shows each agent speak in turn, passing work down the line until a final answer appears."},{"title":"Optional: run the same idea as a CrewAI script for full control","detail":"This optional step does the same thing as code instead of clicks, using CrewAI. You create one Python file and run it.","do":["Open a text editor (Notepad on Windows, TextEdit in plain-text mode on Mac, or VS Code).","Create a file named  crew.py  inside your agent-lab folder.","Paste in the starter script shown below (it defines a Researcher and a Writer both pointed at your local Ollama model).","Save the file.","In the terminal, with  (venv)  still active, run it by typing  python crew.py  and pressing Enter."],"commands":["# save this as crew.py, then run:  python crew.py","from crewai import Agent, Task, Crew, LLM","local = LLM(model=\"ollama/llama3.1\", base_url=\"http://localhost:11434\")","researcher = Agent(role=\"Researcher\", goal=\"Gather key facts\", backstory=\"Careful note-taker\", llm=local)","writer = Agent(role=\"Writer\", goal=\"Write a short clear summary\", backstory=\"Plain-language editor\", llm=local)","t1 = Task(description=\"List 3 key facts about local AI privacy\", agent=researcher, expected_output=\"3 bullet points\")","t2 = Task(description=\"Turn those facts into one short paragraph\", agent=writer, expected_output=\"A short paragraph\")","Crew(agents=[researcher, writer], tasks=[t1, t2]).kickoff()"],"check":"the terminal prints each agent's step and then a final combined result."}],"resources":[{"label":"AutoGen Studio documentation (Microsoft)","url":"https://microsoft.github.io/autogen/stable/user-guide/autogenstudio-user-guide/index.html"},{"label":"AutoGen Studio package page (install command and versions)","url":"https://pypi.org/project/autogenstudio/"},{"label":"CrewAI documentation home","url":"https://docs.crewai.com/"},{"label":"CrewAI 'Connect to any LLM' guide (Ollama and local model setup)","url":"https://docs.crewai.com/en/learn/llm-connections"},{"label":"Ollama official site (download, and how the local API at localhost:11434 works)","url":"https://ollama.com/"},{"label":"Python virtual environments explained (official venv tutorial)","url":"https://docs.python.org/3/tutorial/venv.html"},{"label":"Video search phrase: 'AutoGen Studio local Ollama multi-agent tutorial for beginners'"},{"label":"Video search phrase: 'CrewAI Ollama local multi-agent crew step by step'"}],"cloudTieIn":"Think of this local agent team as a private, offline cousin of the frontier assistants you may already use. Microsoft Copilot is actually built on the same agent ideas as AutoGen (both come from Microsoft), and OpenAI's ChatGPT, Anthropic's Claude, and Google's Gemini all now offer 'agents' or tool-using assistants that plan and act in multiple steps, exactly the pattern you just built by hand. The difference is where the thinking happens: the cloud tools send your prompts and files to a company's servers and use very large, very capable models, while your local crew runs on your own machine using a smaller open-weight model, so nothing leaves the building and there is no per-token bill. A smart real-world workflow is a hybrid: use the local crew for the private stages that touch sensitive data, for example reading FERPA-protected student files or HIPAA-protected notes and doing the first summary and compliance check locally, then, only if you need frontier-level polish or reasoning on the non-sensitive parts, hand that cleaned, de-identified text to Copilot, Claude, ChatGPT, or Gemini. The skills transfer directly, defining roles, wiring handoffs, and verifying output is the same discipline whether the model runs on your laptop or in the cloud. Local complements the cloud, it does not replace it.","troubleshooting":[{"symptom":"The dashboard or script says 'Connection refused' or 'could not connect to localhost:11434' when an agent tries to think.","fix":"Ollama is not running. Start it (open the Ollama app so its tray/menu-bar icon appears), then confirm with 'ollama list' in a terminal. The agents connect to Ollama's local API at http://localhost:11434, so Ollama must be on before you run the team."},{"symptom":"Nothing happens when you type http://localhost:8081 in the browser, or you get 'This site can't be reached'.","fix":"The AutoGen Studio terminal is probably closed or the launch step errored. Go back to the terminal, make sure '(venv)' is showing, re-run 'autogenstudio ui --port 8081', and wait for the 'running on http://localhost:8081' line before opening the browser. Keep that terminal window open the whole time."},{"symptom":"'Port already in use' or 'address already in use' when launching AutoGen Studio.","fix":"Something is already using port 8081 (perhaps a previous run you forgot to close). Launch on a different port, for example 'autogenstudio ui --port 8090', then open http://localhost:8090 instead. Match the number in the command and the browser address."},{"symptom":"The computer freezes, the fan roars, or you see 'out of memory' / the model fails to load partway through.","fix":"The model is too big for your RAM. Pull a smaller one and use it, for example 'ollama pull gemma:2b' or 'ollama pull phi3:mini', then set that exact name in the model settings. As a rule, 8 GB of memory comfortably runs 3B-8B models at Q4 quantization; close other heavy apps too."},{"symptom":"'(venv)' never appears, or on Windows you get a red 'running scripts is disabled on this system' error when activating.","fix":"Windows blocks scripts by default. In the same PowerShell window run 'Set-ExecutionPolicy -Scope Process -Bypass', press Enter, then run the activate command again. This only affects the current window and is safe to undo by closing it."},{"symptom":"The first agent reply takes a very long time, or the agents give a wrong or made-up answer.","fix":"The first response is slow because Ollama loads the model into memory once; later replies are faster, so wait a minute. For wrong answers, remember local models are smaller and weaker than cloud models, tighten each agent's role and goal wording, try a larger model if your memory allows, and always have a human verify the final output, local does not mean automatically correct or compliant."}],"tips":["Give each agent a narrow, specific role and a one-sentence goal. Vague roles like 'assistant' produce mushy results; 'Compliance Editor who flags any student name or health detail' produces sharp, useful handoffs.","Start with just two agents and one handoff before building a three-agent chain. It is far easier to see what went wrong with two, and you can add the third agent once the first handoff works cleanly.","Keep the model small at first (a 3B-8B model at Q4 quantization such as Llama 3.1 8B, Gemma, or Phi-4-mini). A smaller model means faster handoffs and less chance of freezing, and you can always swap in a bigger one later by changing the model name in one place.","Because everything runs at http://localhost:11434 on your own machine, you can safely unplug from the internet after installing and watch the agents still work, a concrete way to prove to yourself that no data is leaving your computer.","Save your work: in AutoGen Studio use the Gallery/export feature to save a team you like, and for CrewAI keep your crew.py file. Reusing a saved team is much faster than rebuilding it, and it becomes a template for the next workflow."],"difficulty":"Intermediate — comfortable installing Python, using the terminal, and copy-pasting commands","time":"About 30–45 minutes, plus a short model download"},{"id":"lab14","n":14,"cat":"C","title":"Continue.dev — Your Sovereign AI Coding Assistant","tagline":"Turn VS Code into a 100% private, free AI pair programmer by wiring the Continue extension to a code model running locally in Ollama — no cloud, no subscription, and your code never leaves your machine.","whatItIs":"Continue is a free, open-source extension you add to a code editor (VS Code or JetBrains). It puts an AI coding assistant right inside your editor: a chat panel where you ask questions about your code, and \"autocomplete\" that suggests the next lines as you type — like a smarter version of the gray ghost-text you may have seen in other tools. On its own, Continue is just the interface; it needs a \"brain\" (an AI model) to think. In this lab, that brain is a code-specialized open model (such as Qwen2.5-Coder) running on your own computer through Ollama, a small free program that hosts AI models locally. Continue talks to Ollama over a private address on your machine (http://localhost:11434), so the whole thing runs offline once set up.","whyUseIt":"This is a completely free, fully private replacement for paid cloud coding assistants like GitHub Copilot — no monthly fee and no code ever sent to a company's servers. Because the model runs in your computer's own memory, your source code, comments, secrets, and proprietary logic never leave the machine, which matters enormously for student work under FERPA, for anything touching health data under HIPAA, and for any employer with a \"no third-party code sharing\" policy. It also costs about $0 per use versus per-token or subscription cloud pricing, so you can experiment as much as you want. Use it when you are learning to code, working on private or sensitive projects, coding on a plane or with no internet, or simply want to understand how AI coding tools work under the hood. Be honest about the trade-off: a local model that fits on a laptop is meaningfully weaker than frontier cloud models on the hardest problems, so always read and test what it writes — local is private and free, not automatically correct.","bestFor":"Computer science students, self-taught coders, and privacy-conscious professionals who want a free, offline AI coding assistant inside VS Code for learning and for projects where code must never leave the machine.","platforms":["Windows","macOS","Linux"],"prerequisites":["Ollama already installed and running — this is REQUIRED and is the 'brain' Continue talks to. If you have not set it up, do the Ollama starter lab first, then come back here.","Visual Studio Code (VS Code) installed — the free code editor from Microsoft (code.visualstudio.com). This lab uses VS Code; Continue also works in JetBrains IDEs with nearly identical steps.","About 8 GB of RAM for a comfortable start (fits a ~7B chat model plus a small ~1.5B autocomplete model at Q4 quantization, which is the standard memory-saving format Ollama downloads by default). 16 GB or more lets you run larger, smarter chat models.","Roughly 6-8 GB of free disk space for the two models you will download (about 4.7 GB for the 7B chat model and about 1 GB for the 1.5B autocomplete model).","An internet connection for the one-time downloads only — installing the extension and pulling the models. After that, everything runs fully offline.","About 20-30 minutes, most of which is the models downloading in the background."],"steps":[{"title":"Confirm Ollama is running (the brain must be awake)","detail":"Continue can't think without Ollama running in the background, so this quick check makes sure Ollama is awake before you go any further.","do":["Open your computer's command line. On Windows, press the Windows key, type  PowerShell , and click 'Windows PowerShell'.","On a Mac, press Cmd+Space, type  Terminal , and press Enter. On Linux, open your Terminal app.","A window with a blinking cursor appears — this is where you type commands.","Type the command below exactly and press Enter.","If you get 'connection refused' or 'command not found', open the Ollama app (or run  ollama serve  in a separate window), then run the command again."],"commands":["curl http://localhost:11434"],"check":"you see a short line like 'Ollama is running'."},{"title":"Download the two local models Continue will use","detail":"Continue needs two AI models: a tiny fast one for autocomplete and a bigger, smarter one for chat. This step downloads both onto your machine.","do":["Stay in the same command-line window from the previous step.","Type the first command and press Enter to download the 7B chat model, then wait for its progress bar to finish.","Type the second command and press Enter to download the small 1.5B autocomplete model, and wait for it to finish too.","Be patient — each model is a few gigabytes, so this can take several minutes on a normal connection.","Type the third command ( ollama list ) and press Enter, then check that both model names appear."],"commands":["ollama pull qwen2.5-coder:7b","ollama pull qwen2.5-coder:1.5b","ollama list"],"check":"you see the word 'success' after each download and both model names show up when you run  ollama list ."},{"title":"Install the Continue extension in VS Code","detail":"Continue is the assistant that lives inside your editor. This step adds it to VS Code from the built-in extensions marketplace.","do":["Open VS Code.","On the far-left strip of icons (the Activity Bar), click the Extensions icon (four small squares with one flying off), or press Ctrl+Shift+X (Cmd+Shift+X on Mac).","In the search box at the top, type  Continue .","Find the result published by 'Continue' with a large download count — its identifier is Continue.continue.","Click the blue 'Install' button on that entry.","Wait a few seconds for a new Continue icon (an infinity-like logo) to appear in the left Activity Bar.","Don't worry if you've read that Continue was acquired by Cursor in mid-2026 and its code is frozen — the published extension still installs and this local-Ollama setup works exactly as described."],"commands":[],"check":"a Continue panel opens on the side and the infinity-like Continue icon appears in the left Activity Bar."},{"title":"Open Continue's configuration file","detail":"Continue keeps its settings in a plain text file named config.yaml. This step opens that file so you can point it at your local models next.","do":["Click the Continue icon in the left Activity Bar to open its panel.","Find and click the small gear/settings icon at the top of that panel.","Choose the option to open or edit the configuration (labeled 'Open config' or 'Configure').","Ignore older guides that mention config.json — the current version uses config.yaml, which is what opens here.","If you ever need the file directly, it lives at  C:\\Users\\<your-name>\\.continue\\config.yaml  on Windows, or  ~/.continue/config.yaml  on Mac and Linux (the leading dot means it's a hidden folder)."],"commands":[],"check":"the config.yaml tab opens in the editor with some text already in it."},{"title":"Point Continue at your local Ollama models","detail":"Now you tell Continue to use the two models you downloaded instead of any cloud service, by replacing the file's contents with a small settings block.","do":["Click inside the config.yaml tab, select all the text with Ctrl+A (Cmd+A on Mac), and delete it.","Paste in the block below exactly.","Keep the spaces exactly as shown and never use Tab — indentation is what makes YAML work.","Save the file with Ctrl+S (Cmd+S on Mac); Continue reloads its settings automatically.","Optional: if you have 16 GB of RAM or more, you can change  qwen2.5-coder:7b  to a larger chat model you've pulled (for example  llama3.1:8b ), but leave the autocomplete model small."],"commands":["name: Local AI Coding Assistant","version: 0.0.1","schema: v1","models:","  - name: Local Chat","    provider: ollama","    model: qwen2.5-coder:7b","    apiBase: http://localhost:11434","    roles:","      - chat","  - name: Local Autocomplete","    provider: ollama","    model: qwen2.5-coder:1.5b","    apiBase: http://localhost:11434","    roles:","      - autocomplete"],"check":"the file saves with no indentation error and Continue reloads using your two local models."},{"title":"Test the chat panel (ask your private AI a question)","detail":"This step confirms chat works by having your local AI answer a coding question — fully offline, with no cloud involved.","do":["Open any code file, or make a new one with File > New File and save it as test.py.","Press Ctrl+L (Cmd+L on Mac) to open the Continue chat box in the sidebar.","Check that the small model selector shows 'Local Chat'.","Type a plain-English question, for example  Write a Python function that reverses a string , and press Enter.","Wait a few seconds to a minute — the very first answer is slowest because the model is loading into memory.","If it just sits there or shows an error, jump to Troubleshooting."],"commands":[],"check":"the answer streams into the chat box word by word."},{"title":"Watch autocomplete work as you type","detail":"This step shows the tiny local model suggesting your next line of code as gray 'ghost text' while you type.","do":["Click into your code file.","In a Python file, type  def add(a, b):  and press Enter to move to the next line.","Pause a moment and watch for gray 'ghost text' suggesting the rest, such as  return a + b .","Press the Tab key to accept the suggestion, or just keep typing to ignore it.","If no gray text ever appears, make sure you saved the config from Step 5 and that the autocomplete model shows up in  ollama list ."],"commands":[],"check":"gray ghost-text suggestions appear as you type and pressing Tab accepts them."},{"title":"Refactor a real block of code with a keyboard shortcut","detail":"This is the payoff: you select a block of code, ask the AI to rewrite it in plain English, then review and accept or reject the changes.","do":["Use your mouse to highlight (select) a block of code, such as a whole function.","Press Ctrl+I (Cmd+I on Mac) — a small input box appears attached to your selection.","Type an instruction in plain English, such as  add comments explaining each line  or  rewrite this to handle an empty list , and press Enter.","Read the colored diff Continue streams inline (green = added, red = removed).","Accept the changes with Ctrl+Alt+Y (Cmd+Opt+Y on Mac), or reject them with Ctrl+Alt+N (Cmd+Opt+N on Mac).","Always read the diff before accepting — treat it as a helpful draft, not a final answer, because a laptop-sized model is weaker than a frontier cloud model."],"commands":[],"check":"your selected code is replaced by the improved version after you accept."}],"resources":[{"label":"Continue official site and downloads","url":"https://continue.dev"},{"label":"Continue + Ollama setup guide (official docs)","url":"https://docs.continue.dev/guides/ollama-guide"},{"label":"Continue config.yaml reference (all settings explained)","url":"https://docs.continue.dev/reference"},{"label":"Continue extension on the VS Code Marketplace","url":"https://marketplace.visualstudio.com/items?itemName=Continue.continue"},{"label":"Ollama — download the local model engine and browse code models","url":"https://ollama.com"},{"label":"Video search phrase: 'Continue.dev Ollama VS Code local AI setup 2026 tutorial'"},{"label":"Video search phrase: 'private offline GitHub Copilot alternative Continue Ollama walkthrough'"}],"cloudTieIn":"This local stack is a direct, private stand-in for cloud coding assistants you may already know: GitHub Copilot (which is built on OpenAI models) and the coding modes of Claude, ChatGPT, and Gemini all run on someone else's servers and send your code there to get an answer. Continue keeps the same in-editor experience — chat, autocomplete, and one-shortcut refactoring — but swaps that remote brain for a model running in your own RAM via Ollama, so nothing leaves your machine. The honest trade-off is capability: for the hardest architectural questions, large multi-file reasoning, or the latest frameworks, the frontier cloud models are still clearly stronger, so many developers use both — local for everyday coding, private codebases, sensitive student or health data, and offline work, and reach for Copilot/Claude/ChatGPT/Gemini when they hit a genuinely hard problem. Usefully, Continue is not locked to local: the very same config.yaml can also add a cloud model (with an API key) alongside your Ollama models, letting you switch between 'private and free' and 'maximum power' from one dropdown. And local is not automatically compliant — running on your machine helps with FERPA/HIPAA, but you still owe the same care with the code and data you handle.","troubleshooting":[{"symptom":"Continue chat shows an error like 'connection refused', 'fetch failed', or 'could not connect to Ollama'.","fix":"Ollama is not running or not reachable. Open your command line and run 'curl http://localhost:11434' — if that also fails, start Ollama (open the Ollama app, or run 'ollama serve' in a separate window) and leave it running. Then confirm your config.yaml has 'apiBase: http://localhost:11434' spelled exactly, and save the file again."},{"symptom":"The chat replies 'model not found' or names a model that isn't installed.","fix":"The model name in config.yaml must match a model you actually pulled. Run 'ollama list' and compare the exact names and tags (for example 'qwen2.5-coder:7b'). If it is missing, run 'ollama pull qwen2.5-coder:7b'. A common slip is a typo in the tag or forgetting the ':7b' part."},{"symptom":"The computer freezes, the fan roars, or you see an 'out of memory' / model-crash error on the first big reply.","fix":"Your chat model is too large for your RAM. Switch the chat model in config.yaml to a smaller one — pull and use 'llama3.1:8b' or drop to a 3B-class model — and keep the autocomplete model at 1.5B. Also close other heavy apps. Ollama already uses the memory-saving Q4 (4-bit) format by default, so the main lever is choosing a smaller model."},{"symptom":"Autocomplete (the gray ghost text) never appears while typing.","fix":"Confirm config.yaml has a model with 'roles: [autocomplete]' and that it was saved (Ctrl+S). Check the autocomplete model is installed with 'ollama list'. If it still doesn't show, the model may be too slow to answer in time — use a small one like 'qwen2.5-coder:1.5b' rather than a 7B model for autocomplete."},{"symptom":"The very first answer takes a long time (30-60+ seconds) but later ones are fast.","fix":"This is normal, not a bug. The first request loads the model from disk into memory, which is slow; after that it stays 'warm' and responds quickly. You can pre-warm it by asking one throwaway question before you start real work. If EVERY response is slow, your model is likely too large for your hardware — see the out-of-memory fix and choose a smaller model."},{"symptom":"Editing config.yaml causes Continue to complain about invalid configuration.","fix":"YAML is picky about spacing. Make sure you used spaces (never the Tab key) for indentation and kept the exact structure from Step 5 — 'models:' at the left margin, each model starting with '  - name:', and 'roles:'/'      - chat' indented beneath it. If in doubt, delete everything and paste the Step 5 block fresh, then save."}],"tips":["Give each model the right job: keep a tiny model (1.5B-3B) for autocomplete so suggestions feel instant, and a larger one (7B+) for chat where a slightly slower, smarter answer is worth it. Mixing them in one config.yaml, as this lab does, is the setup experienced users prefer.","Pre-warm the model before a work session by asking one quick question — it loads into memory once and then every later response is fast, avoiding the slow-first-answer surprise during a demo or class.","Add context to chat with the '@' symbol: type '@' in the Continue chat box to attach a specific file, folder, or the whole codebase so the model answers about YOUR code, not generic examples. This dramatically improves answers on real projects.","Keep 'ollama ps' handy — running it in the command line shows which model is currently loaded and how much memory it is using, so you can tell at a glance whether your machine has headroom for a bigger model.","Treat every suggestion as a draft: a laptop-sized local model is weaker than frontier cloud tools, so read the inline diff before pressing accept (Ctrl+Alt+Y), and run/test the code. Private and free does not mean automatically correct."],"difficulty":"Intermediate — comfortable using a terminal, installing apps, and copy-pasting commands","time":"About 30–45 minutes (mostly waiting for the two model downloads)"},{"id":"lab15","n":15,"cat":"C","title":"LiteLLM Gateway — One Unified Local API","tagline":"Set up one local LiteLLM gateway so every AI app on your computer connects through a single address instead of you re-typing ports and model names into each one.","whatItIs":"LiteLLM is a small, free \"traffic controller\" program that runs on your own computer. It sits in front of your local AI engines (like Ollama) and any cloud keys you may have, and it presents all of them at one single web address in the industry-standard \"OpenAI API\" format. Because almost every AI app can talk to that format, you point your apps at LiteLLM once, and LiteLLM quietly forwards each request to the right model behind the scenes. Think of it as a universal power strip: many devices, one outlet you plug into.","whyUseIt":"The moment you use more than one local AI app, you feel the pain: every app (Msty, Continue, AnythingLLM, a script you wrote) wants its own copy of the server address, port number, and exact model name, and if any of those change you must edit them all. A gateway fixes that by centralizing the configuration in one file you edit once. It also unlocks real conveniences: give a model a friendly nickname like \"my-coding-model,\" swap the actual engine underneath without touching your apps, and set fallback rules so if one model is busy or missing another answers. On the privacy side, running everything locally means student records (FERPA), health data (HIPAA), and any sensitive text never leave your machine and are never retained by a third party, at roughly zero per-word cost versus a cloud subscription. Use this once you have at least one local model working and more than one app that needs to reach it. Note honestly: a gateway does not make a model smarter, and local ≠ automatically compliant, so still verify important answers.","bestFor":"Someone who already runs local models in Ollama and uses two or more AI apps, and is tired of re-entering the same server address and model names into each one.","platforms":["Windows","macOS","Linux"],"prerequisites":["Ollama already installed and working, with at least one model pulled (for example Gemma or Qwen or Llama 3.x at Q4). Ollama is what actually runs the model; LiteLLM only routes to it. Its local address is http://localhost:11434.","Python version 3.10, 3.11, 3.12, or 3.13 installed. LiteLLM is a Python program, so you need Python to run it. (We show you how to check and install it.)","About 300 MB of free disk space for LiteLLM and its supporting pieces, plus whatever space your models already use.","8 GB of RAM is enough for a 3B to 8B model like Gemma or Llama 3.x 8B at Q4 (4-bit) quantization; 16-24 GB comfortably runs 12B to 32B models. The gateway itself uses almost no memory; the model does the heavy lifting.","Ability to open a terminal (Command Prompt / PowerShell on Windows, Terminal on Mac or Linux). We walk you through opening it and typing into it, one line at a time.","No account, no API key, and no internet connection are required for the all-local setup once the pieces are installed."],"steps":[{"title":"Confirm Ollama is running and has a model","detail":"LiteLLM forwards requests to Ollama, so this step checks that Ollama is running and has at least one model before you build the gateway.","do":["Open your web browser, click the address bar at the top, type  http://localhost:11434 , and press Enter.","Check that the page shows the words 'Ollama is running'.","Open your terminal (the next step shows how if you've never done this).","Type  ollama list  and press Enter to see your installed models.","If the list is empty, run  ollama pull llama3.1:8b  and wait for it to finish downloading."],"commands":["http://localhost:11434","ollama list","ollama pull llama3.1:8b"],"check":"the browser shows 'Ollama is running' and  ollama list  shows at least one model name in the NAME column."},{"title":"Open your terminal (the black text window)","detail":"The terminal is the window where you type commands. This step just gets it open and ready.","do":["On Windows, click the Start button, type  PowerShell , and click 'Windows PowerShell' in the results.","On a Mac, press Command+Space, type  Terminal , and press Enter.","On Linux, press Ctrl+Alt+T.","Click into the window that opens so it's ready for you to type."],"commands":[],"check":"a window with a blinking cursor is open and waiting for you to type."},{"title":"Check that Python is installed (and install it if not)","detail":"LiteLLM is written in Python, so this step confirms Python is present and installs it if it's missing.","do":["In the terminal, type  python --version  and press Enter.","Check the result — 'Python 3.11.x' is good (any of 3.10, 3.11, 3.12, or 3.13 works).","On Windows, if  python  does nothing, try  py --version  instead.","If you see an error, or a version of 3.14 or higher, or a 2.x version, go to python.org and download the installer for your system.","During a Windows install, tick the box 'Add python.exe to PATH' before clicking Install.","Close and reopen the terminal after installing so it notices the new Python."],"commands":["python --version","py --version"],"check":"the terminal prints a version like 'Python 3.11.x' (anything from 3.10 through 3.13)."},{"title":"Install the LiteLLM gateway","detail":"This one command downloads LiteLLM and its extra proxy pieces from the official Python package index and installs them.","do":["In the terminal, type the command below exactly — including the quotes and the  [proxy]  part — and press Enter.","Let it run for a minute or two; it prints many lines, which is completely normal.","If you see a red 'error' about permissions, add  --user  to the end of the command and run it again.","On Mac or Linux, if  pip  is not found, use  pip3  instead (the second command)."],"commands":["pip install 'litellm[proxy]'","pip3 install 'litellm[proxy]'"],"check":"a final line reads 'Successfully installed litellm' (possibly alongside other package names)."},{"title":"Create the config.yaml routing file","detail":"This small text file lists your models once, in one place — it is the whole point of the gateway.","do":["Open a simple text editor — Notepad on Windows, or TextEdit on Mac set to Plain Text via the Format menu.","Paste in the block below.","Change the part after  ollama/  to match a model name from your  ollama list .","Save the file as exactly  config.yaml  (not config.yaml.txt) in an easy-to-find folder like Documents.","Optional: to offer more models later, repeat the block for each one."],"commands":["model_list:","  - model_name: my-local-model","    litellm_params:","      model: ollama/llama3.1:8b","      api_base: http://localhost:11434"],"check":"a file named config.yaml is saved and contains the model_list text."},{"title":"Start the gateway (the proxy server)","detail":"This step launches LiteLLM so it listens for requests on your computer at port 4000 (the address http://localhost:4000).","do":["In the terminal, move into the folder where you saved config.yaml using  cd , for example  cd Documents , and press Enter.","Type  litellm --config config.yaml  and press Enter.","Watch for a line like 'Uvicorn running on http://0.0.0.0:4000' or 'LiteLLM: Proxy initialized'.","Leave this terminal window OPEN — closing it stops the gateway."],"commands":["cd Documents","litellm --config config.yaml"],"check":"the cursor stops advancing and sits there running, showing the port 4000 line, with no red error."},{"title":"Test the gateway from a second terminal","detail":"This step sends a tiny test message through the gateway to your local model to prove the whole chain works.","do":["Leave the running gateway alone — do not close it.","Open a NEW terminal window (repeat Step 2) so you have one for the server and one for testing.","In the new window, type the command below and press Enter.","Wait for the reply — the first response can take 10–30 seconds while the model loads into memory; later replies are faster.","If you prefer, open  http://localhost:4000  in your browser instead to confirm the server responds."],"commands":["curl http://localhost:4000/v1/chat/completions -H \"Content-Type: application/json\" -d \"{\\\"model\\\":\\\"my-local-model\\\",\\\"messages\\\":[{\\\"role\\\":\\\"user\\\",\\\"content\\\":\\\"Say hello in one sentence.\\\"}]}\""],"check":"a burst of JSON appears that includes a 'content' field holding a real one- or two-sentence answer from the model."},{"title":"Point your apps at the one unified address","detail":"Now you connect your AI apps to the single gateway address instead of re-typing Ollama's details in each one.","do":["Open the app's settings and look for an 'OpenAI-compatible', 'Custom OpenAI', or 'Base URL' option.","Set the Base URL to  http://localhost:4000  (add  /v1  if the app asks for the full path:  http://localhost:4000/v1 ).","For the API key, type any placeholder like  sk-anything  — the local gateway does not require a real key.","For the model name, use the nickname from your config, here  my-local-model .","Repeat this once in each app you use (Msty, Continue, AnythingLLM, or your own scripts)."],"commands":["http://localhost:4000","http://localhost:4000/v1"],"check":"the app connects and replies through the gateway; from then on you only edit config.yaml and restart the gateway to change models."}],"resources":[{"label":"LiteLLM proxy quick-start (official docs)","url":"https://docs.litellm.ai/docs/proxy/quick_start"},{"label":"LiteLLM source code and README (official GitHub, MIT license)","url":"https://github.com/BerriAI/litellm"},{"label":"Ollama download and model library (the engine LiteLLM routes to)","url":"https://ollama.com"},{"label":"Python download (needed to run LiteLLM; get 3.10-3.13)","url":"https://www.python.org/downloads/"},{"label":"Video search phrase: 'LiteLLM proxy Ollama config.yaml local setup tutorial'"},{"label":"Video search phrase: 'connect AnythingLLM or Continue to a local OpenAI-compatible gateway'"}],"cloudTieIn":"The whole reason apps can share one gateway is the OpenAI API format — the same request shape that ChatGPT, and OpenAI-compatible endpoints for tools like it, popularized. LiteLLM speaks that format on your machine, so any app built for ChatGPT-style APIs will happily talk to your local models instead. That also means a natural on-ramp: the exact same config.yaml can hold a cloud entry alongside your local one (for example an Anthropic Claude, OpenAI ChatGPT, or Google Gemini model with your paid key), letting one app reach both and even fall back from a busy local model to a cloud one. Practically, keep anything identifiable (FERPA student data, HIPAA health data) flowing only to the local Ollama entry, and reserve Copilot, Claude, ChatGPT, or Gemini for the hardest reasoning tasks where frontier cloud models are still clearly stronger. Local complements, it does not replace, cloud — the gateway simply lets you choose per request instead of per app.","troubleshooting":[{"symptom":"The test command returns 'connection refused' or the browser cannot reach http://localhost:4000.","fix":"The gateway is not running. Return to the terminal where you ran 'litellm --config config.yaml' and confirm it is still open and showing the port 4000 line. If it exited, start it again. Remember the server terminal must stay open; use a second terminal for tests."},{"symptom":"LiteLLM starts but every request errors with something about Ollama or 'connection refused to 11434'.","fix":"Ollama itself is not running or the model name is wrong. Confirm http://localhost:11434 shows 'Ollama is running', then run 'ollama list' and make sure the text after 'ollama/' in your config.yaml exactly matches a NAME in that list (including any ':8b' tag). Save the file and restart LiteLLM."},{"symptom":"'Address already in use' or 'port 4000 is in use' when starting LiteLLM.","fix":"Another program (or a previous gateway you forgot to close) is holding port 4000. Either close that other window, or start LiteLLM on a different port by adding '--port 4001' to the command, then point your apps at http://localhost:4001 instead."},{"symptom":"'pip is not recognized' or 'command not found: pip'.","fix":"Python is missing from the terminal's path. On Windows try 'py -m pip install \"litellm[proxy]\"'; on Mac or Linux try 'pip3'. If still failing, reinstall Python from python.org and on Windows tick 'Add python.exe to PATH', then close and reopen the terminal."},{"symptom":"The model loads but the computer freezes, swaps to disk, or the reply is extremely slow, or you see an out-of-memory error.","fix":"The model is too big for your RAM. Pull a smaller or more quantized model — an 8 GB machine should use a 3B-8B model at Q4 (4-bit), such as 'ollama pull gemma:2b' or a Q4 Llama 3.x 8B. Update the 'model:' line in config.yaml to the smaller name and restart. Close other heavy apps to free memory."},{"symptom":"An app you connected says the model was not found or returns a 400/'invalid model' error.","fix":"The app is sending a model name the gateway does not know. Make sure the app's model field is set to the exact 'model_name' nickname from config.yaml (here 'my-local-model'), not Ollama's internal name, and that the Base URL is http://localhost:4000 (add '/v1' if the app requires the full path)."}],"tips":["Give models clear nicknames in config.yaml ('fast-chat', 'coding-model', 'private-grader') so your apps read like plain English and you can swap the real engine underneath without editing a single app.","Keep the gateway terminal running in the background; on Windows you can pin PowerShell to the taskbar, and start the gateway once each work session. Closing that window is the number-one reason apps suddenly 'lose' the connection.","You can list several models in one config.yaml — one local Ollama entry for private/FERPA/HIPAA work and, optionally, a cloud entry for hard tasks — and switch between them just by changing the model name your app sends.","Add fallback rules later so a busy or missing model automatically hands off to a backup; start simple with one model first, get it working end to end, then grow the file.","Because it is the standard OpenAI format, the same http://localhost:4000 address works for your own Python or JavaScript scripts too — set the base_url to it and use api_key='anything' for fully local, no-cost, no-internet automation."],"difficulty":"Intermediate — comfortable opening a terminal and copy-pasting commands","time":"About 20–30 minutes"},{"id":"lab16","n":16,"cat":"C","title":"Local Web Scraping (Crawl4AI / Firecrawl)","tagline":"Set up a private, on-your-own-computer web scraper that turns any public web page into clean, ad-free Markdown text your local AI model can actually read.","whatItIs":"A web scraper is a small program that visits a web page for you and pulls out the real content: the article words, headings, and lists, while throwing away the ads, cookie pop-ups, navigation menus, and hidden tracking scripts. This lab sets up Crawl4AI, a free open-source scraper that runs entirely on your own computer and saves each page as a clean Markdown file (Markdown is just plain text with simple marks like # for a heading and - for a bullet). Nothing is uploaded to any company's server; the page is fetched and cleaned locally. We also point you to Firecrawl, a heavier alternative that runs inside Docker, in case you outgrow the simple tool.","whyUseIt":"A local AI model can only reason about text you actually hand it, and raw web-page source code (HTML) is full of junk that confuses the model and wastes its limited context window. A local scraper strips that noise instantly so a page of industry news, a reference blog, or a research article arrives as tidy Markdown ready to paste into Ollama or drop into a RAG knowledge folder. Running it locally matters for the same three reasons the whole Lab does: privacy (the URLs you research and the text you collect never leave your machine), security (no third party keeps a log of what you scraped), and cost (open tools plus open-weight models run at roughly $0 per page instead of per-call cloud fees). For a college setting this also keeps you clear of accidentally shipping sensitive links or student-related material to an outside service. Be honest about limits, though: local scrapers only grab publicly reachable pages, cannot log in for you, and you must respect each site's terms of use and copyright; local does not automatically mean compliant.","bestFor":"A non-technical learner who wants to feed current articles, blogs, or documentation into a local Ollama model or a RAG index without sending any URLs or text to a cloud service.","platforms":["Windows","macOS","Linux"],"prerequisites":["A computer with at least 8 GB of RAM (16 GB is comfortable) and about 3 GB of free disk space for Python and a bundled Chromium browser.","Python 3.10 or newer installed. If you do not have it, download it from python.org and, on Windows, tick the 'Add Python to PATH' box during install.","A working internet connection (the scraper needs to reach the web pages you want to fetch).","Optional but recommended: Ollama already installed with one small model pulled (for example 'ollama pull llama3.1:8b') so you have a local AI at http://localhost:11434 to feed the scraped text into. Ollama is covered in the Local Model lab.","About 20 minutes and a willingness to copy-paste a few commands into a terminal window. No coding experience needed.","For the optional Firecrawl alternative only: Docker Desktop installed and at least 8 GB of RAM free."],"steps":[{"title":"Open a terminal (the text window where you type commands)","detail":"A terminal is a plain window where you type a command and press Enter instead of clicking buttons. This step opens it, and you'll keep it open for the whole lab.","do":["On Windows, click the Start menu, type  PowerShell , and click 'Windows PowerShell' when it appears.","On a Mac, press Command+Spacebar to open Spotlight, type  Terminal , and press Enter.","On Linux, press Ctrl+Alt+T.","Leave this window open for every step below."],"commands":[],"check":"a window with a blinking cursor is waiting for you to type."},{"title":"Confirm Python is installed and new enough","detail":"Crawl4AI needs Python version 3.10 or higher, so this step checks the version you have.","do":["In the terminal, type  python --version  and press Enter.","Check the result — you should see something like 'Python 3.11.6'.","If the number after 'Python' is 3.10 or higher, you're good to go.","If you see an error like 'python is not recognized' or a version below 3.10, go to python.org and download the latest version.","Install it (on Windows tick 'Add Python to PATH'), then close and reopen the terminal and try again."],"commands":["python --version"],"check":"the terminal shows 'Python' followed by a version number of 3.10 or higher."},{"title":"Install the Crawl4AI scraper","detail":"This one command downloads and installs the scraper plus all the helper libraries it needs. ('pip' is Python's app-installer and '-U' means 'give me the latest version'.)","do":["In the terminal, type  pip install -U crawl4ai  and press Enter.","Wait — many lines of text will scroll by for one to three minutes, which is normal.","If pip is not found, replace  pip  with  python -m pip  and try again."],"commands":["pip install -U crawl4ai"],"check":"the scrolling stops, your cursor returns, and a line near the end reads 'Successfully installed crawl4ai' with no red 'ERROR' text."},{"title":"Run the one-time setup so the scraper has a browser to drive","detail":"Crawl4AI reads pages by quietly steering a real browser engine (Chromium, the engine inside Chrome) so JavaScript-heavy sites load fully. This command downloads that engine and prepares a small local cache.","do":["In the terminal, type  crawl4ai-setup  and press Enter.","Wait one to two minutes while it downloads Chromium and prints progress."],"commands":["crawl4ai-setup"],"check":"the command finishes with a message that setup completed and returns your cursor with no red errors."},{"title":"Check that everything is healthy","detail":"This built-in health check confirms your Python version is compatible and that the browser engine installed correctly, before you scrape anything real.","do":["In the terminal, type  crawl4ai-doctor  and press Enter.","If it reports a missing dependency, copy the exact suggestion it prints and run that command.","On Linux it sometimes tells you to install a system library — that's a one-line copy-paste it provides for you."],"commands":["crawl4ai-doctor"],"check":"you see several green check marks or lines ending in 'OK' / 'passed'."},{"title":"Create a workspace folder to hold your clean Markdown files","detail":"This step makes a folder called 'scraped' in your home directory and moves into it, so every file you create next lands in one tidy place on your own computer.","do":["In the terminal, type  mkdir scraped  and press Enter to make the folder (mkdir means 'make directory').","Type  cd scraped  and press Enter to move into it (cd means 'change directory')."],"commands":["mkdir scraped","cd scraped"],"check":"your terminal prompt shows that you are now inside the 'scraped' folder."},{"title":"Scrape your first page into clean Markdown (the easy CLI way)","detail":"Crawl4AI includes a simple command named 'crwl' that fetches a page, strips out ads, menus, cookie banners, and scripts, and gives you back only the clean article as Markdown.","do":["Type the first command and press Enter to print the clean Markdown to your screen (the  -o markdown  part asks for Markdown output).","To also SAVE it as a file, type the second command instead — the  > article.md  writes the output into a file called article.md.","Swap the example Wikipedia URL for any public article you like.","Open the saved  article.md  in Notepad or any text editor to read it."],"commands":["crwl https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Artificial_intelligence -o markdown","crwl https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Artificial_intelligence -o markdown > article.md"],"check":"the first command fills your screen with readable text and no HTML tags, and the second creates an  article.md  file in your 'scraped' folder."},{"title":"Do the same from a tiny Python script (so you can automate and tweak it)","detail":"A short script lets you save files with clean names and later loop over many URLs, instead of running the command by hand each time.","do":["Create a file named  fetch.py  in your 'scraped' folder — on Windows, type  notepad fetch.py  and click Yes to create it.","Paste in the code block below.","Change the  url  line to the page you want to scrape.","Save the file.","Run it by typing  python fetch.py  and pressing Enter."],"commands":["import asyncio","from crawl4ai import AsyncWebCrawler","","async def main():","    async with AsyncWebCrawler() as crawler:","        result = await crawler.arun(url=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Machine_learning\")","        with open(\"page.md\", \"w\", encoding=\"utf-8\") as f:","            f.write(result.markdown)","        print(\"Saved page.md\")","","asyncio.run(main())","","# --- run it with: ---","python fetch.py"],"check":"the terminal prints 'Saved page.md' and a new  page.md  file appears in your folder containing clean Markdown."},{"title":"Feed the clean Markdown into your local AI model","detail":"This step hands the cleaned file to a local model so the AI reasons over fresh, real-world text instead of only what it memorized during training.","do":["Make sure Ollama is running (its local API lives at  http://localhost:11434 ).","On Windows PowerShell, run the first command to pipe the whole  page.md  file into a small model and ask for a summary.","On Mac or Linux, run the second command instead.","If it feels slow the first time, that's the model warming up in memory; the next question is much faster."],"commands":["Get-Content page.md | ollama run llama3.1:8b \"Summarize the key points of this article in 5 bullets:\"","cat page.md | ollama run llama3.1:8b \"Summarize the key points of this article in 5 bullets:\""],"check":"the model prints a paragraph or bullet summary drawn from your scraped page."},{"title":"Optional heavier alternative: run Firecrawl locally in Docker","detail":"If you later need an always-on scraping service with a web API, Firecrawl's self-hostable 'firecrawl-simple' build runs inside Docker and serves at http://localhost:3002. It is more powerful but much heavier.","do":["Only do this if you outgrow Crawl4AI — it needs Docker Desktop and about 8 GB of free RAM because it launches several services at once.","Type the first command and press Enter to clone the repo.","Type  cd firecrawl-simple  and press Enter to move into the folder.","Copy the example environment file (the repo's README shows the exact filename).","Type  docker compose up -d  and press Enter to start it.","Once it's up, scrape by sending a request to the  /v1/scrape  endpoint asking for the 'markdown' format."],"commands":["git clone https://github.com/devflowinc/firecrawl-simple.git","cd firecrawl-simple","docker compose up -d"],"check":"the services start and Firecrawl responds at  http://localhost:3002 ."}],"resources":[{"label":"Crawl4AI official documentation (install, CLI, Python API)","url":"https://docs.crawl4ai.com/"},{"label":"Crawl4AI on GitHub (source, issues, examples)","url":"https://github.com/unclecode/crawl4ai"},{"label":"Crawl4AI on PyPI (the package pip installs)","url":"https://pypi.org/project/Crawl4AI/"},{"label":"firecrawl-simple: stripped-down self-hostable Firecrawl (LLM-ready Markdown)","url":"https://github.com/devflowinc/firecrawl-simple"},{"label":"Firecrawl official docs and self-host guide","url":"https://docs.firecrawl.dev/"},{"label":"Ollama (run the local model you feed the scraped text into)","url":"https://ollama.com"},{"label":"Video search phrase: 'Crawl4AI beginner tutorial install python markdown scrape'","url":""},{"label":"Video search phrase: 'self-host Firecrawl docker compose localhost 3002 walkthrough'","url":""}],"cloudTieIn":"Frontier chat tools like Microsoft Copilot, Anthropic Claude, OpenAI ChatGPT, and Google Gemini already browse the live web for you, so for a quick one-off 'what does this page say' you would just paste the link into one of them. This local scraper is the do-it-yourself version of that hidden 'read the page and clean it up' step, and you use it when you specifically do not want the URLs or the collected text to travel to a cloud provider (sensitive research, competitive work, or anything touching student or health data), when you need to bulk-fetch dozens or hundreds of pages into a private RAG folder without paying per call, or when your project must run offline. A common hybrid pattern: scrape and clean pages locally with Crawl4AI, reason over routine or private ones with a local Ollama model, and only escalate the genuinely hardest analysis to Claude, ChatGPT, or Gemini, pasting in the same clean Markdown you already produced. The Markdown-in, answer-out shape is identical whether the model is local or cloud, so the workflow you learn here transfers directly.","troubleshooting":[{"symptom":"'pip is not recognized' or 'command not found: pip' when installing.","fix":"Python's installer path is not set up. Use 'python -m pip install -U crawl4ai' instead. If even 'python' is not recognized on Windows, reinstall Python from python.org and tick 'Add Python to PATH', then close and reopen the terminal."},{"symptom":"crawl4ai-doctor or a scrape fails with a browser or Playwright error.","fix":"The browser engine did not finish installing. Re-run 'crawl4ai-setup', and if it still complains run 'python -m playwright install chromium'. On Linux, run the exact 'apt-get install' line the doctor prints to add the missing system libraries."},{"symptom":"The scraped Markdown is nearly empty or missing the main article.","fix":"The site loads its content with JavaScript after a delay, or blocks bots. Try again (Crawl4AI already runs a real browser), and if it stays empty the page may require login or explicitly forbid scraping in its terms; pick a different, publicly readable source."},{"symptom":"'connection refused' or 'could not connect to localhost:11434' when feeding text to Ollama.","fix":"Ollama is not running. Open the Ollama app (or run 'ollama serve' in another terminal), confirm you have pulled a model with 'ollama pull llama3.1:8b', then retry the pipe command."},{"symptom":"The model's first response is very slow or the machine freezes briefly.","fix":"The model is loading into memory the first time and a long article uses lots of context. Use a smaller model (Gemma 4 e4B, Phi-4-mini, or Llama 3.1 8B at Q4 quantization for 8 GB machines), or summarize a shorter page. Later requests to the same loaded model are much faster."},{"symptom":"Firecrawl in Docker fails to start or reports it is out of memory.","fix":"firecrawl-simple launches several services and needs about 8 GB of free RAM. Close other heavy apps, raise Docker Desktop's memory limit in Settings > Resources, or simply use Crawl4AI, which does not need Docker at all."},{"symptom":"'port is already in use' / 'bind: address already in use' for 3002 (Firecrawl) or 11434 (Ollama).","fix":"Another program already holds that port. Stop the other copy (for Firecrawl run 'docker compose down' first), or change the PORT value in Firecrawl's .env file, then start again. For Ollama, only one server instance should run at a time."}],"tips":["Save every scraped file into one 'scraped' folder with clear names (site-topic-date.md). That folder becomes a ready-made knowledge base you can point a RAG lab at later without re-fetching anything.","Markdown keeps headings and lists, which local models parse far better than a wall of plain text. Always prefer the '-o markdown' output over raw HTML or a naive copy-paste from your browser.","Be a good web citizen: fetch a handful of pages, not thousands at once; check a site's terms of use and its /robots.txt; and never scrape pages behind a login or paywall. Local does not make it automatically legal.","For long articles, ask a small fast model (Phi-4-mini or Gemma 4 e4B) for a first summary, and only send the trickiest analysis to a bigger local model or a cloud tool. This keeps most work private and fast.","Always sanity-check what a local model tells you about scraped text. Smaller open-weight models can miss nuance or invent details, so verify important claims against the original page before you rely on them."],"difficulty":"Intermediate — comfortable using a terminal and copy-pasting commands (Docker is only needed for the optional last step)","time":"About 20–30 minutes"},{"id":"lab17","n":17,"cat":"M","title":"ComfyUI — Node-Based Image & Video Generation","tagline":"Install ComfyUI on your own computer and generate your first AI image by visually wiring together the nodes that make a Stable Diffusion or Flux model work — no cloud, no subscription, nothing leaves your machine.","whatItIs":"ComfyUI is a free program you run on your own computer that turns image-and-video AI models (like Stable Diffusion and Flux) into a visual flowchart. Instead of typing into one box like ChatGPT, you see a canvas of connected boxes called \"nodes\" — one node loads the AI model, one holds your text prompt, one does the actual image-making, one saves the picture. You drag wires between the nodes so that data flows from left to right, and when you press a button the image appears. It is the most popular tool that serious local AI artists and developers use, precisely because you can see and rearrange every step.","whyUseIt":"The nodes are a real, hands-on lesson: you can literally watch how a text prompt becomes numbers, becomes a blurry \"latent\" image, and finally becomes a finished picture — something a single text box hides from you. Running it locally means every image is generated on your hardware, so your prompts and pictures never leave the computer (privacy), nothing is retained by a company (security), and after the one-time download the models cost about $0 to run instead of a per-image cloud fee (cost). For a school setting where images might include student faces or other identifiable material, keeping generation local avoids handing that data to a third party. The honest trade-off: local image models are slower on modest hardware and usually a step behind the very best paid cloud image tools, so treat this as a learning-and-experimentation station, not a guaranteed replacement for professional cloud generators.","bestFor":"A curious beginner or art/design student who wants to see how latent-diffusion image models actually work, generate images privately on their own machine, and experiment for free rather than paying per image in the cloud.","platforms":["Windows","macOS (Apple Silicon)","Linux","Runs in your web browser after you start it locally"],"prerequisites":["A computer with a dedicated graphics card (GPU) is strongly recommended: an NVIDIA card with at least 6 GB of VRAM, or an Apple Silicon Mac (M1/M2/M3/M4) with 16 GB+ unified memory. It will also run CPU-only, just very slowly.","About 15 GB of free disk space before you download any models, and more as you collect models (a single model file is often 2-7 GB).","A stable internet connection for the one-time download of ComfyUI (~1.5 GB) and at least one model file (2-7 GB).","This is a standalone install — it does NOT require Ollama or LM Studio (those run text chat models; ComfyUI runs image/video models).","On Windows only, the free 7-Zip app (from 7-zip.org) if you choose the Portable version, because the download is a .7z archive Windows cannot open by itself.","Patience for the first render: the very first image is always the slowest because the model has to load into memory."],"steps":[{"title":"Understand the two install choices, then pick one","detail":"There are two beginner-friendly ways to get ComfyUI, and this step helps you choose one — you do NOT need both.","do":["Choose the Desktop app if you have never used a terminal — it's a normal installer that bundles everything, including the ComfyUI-Manager helper.","Choose the Portable version if you'd rather unzip a self-contained folder that installs nothing into Windows.","For this lab, follow the Desktop app as the main path; the Portable path is shown as an alternative at the end.","Pick just one — you do not need both."],"commands":[],"check":"you've decided which single path to follow (the Desktop app suits most beginners)."},{"title":"Download and install the Desktop app","detail":"This step downloads the official ComfyUI installer and runs it so the app lands on your computer.","do":["Open your web browser and go to  https://comfy.org/download .","The site auto-detects your operating system — click the Download button for your system.","Save the file, then double-click it.","On Windows, a setup wizard (an NSIS installer) opens — click Next/Install through the prompts, and pick where to store models when asked (the default is fine).","On a Mac, drag the ComfyUI icon into your Applications folder."],"commands":["Open https://comfy.org/download and click the Download button for your system"],"check":"a new ComfyUI icon appears in your Start Menu (Windows) or Applications folder (Mac)."},{"title":"Launch ComfyUI and confirm it opened in your browser","detail":"This step starts ComfyUI, which opens its visual canvas as a tab in your web browser.","do":["Double-click the ComfyUI icon.","Wait 30–60 seconds the first time while a small window and/or a black command window starts it up.","Let it automatically open a browser tab showing a dark canvas with some connected boxes.","Check that the address bar reads  http://127.0.0.1:8188  (127.0.0.1, also written 'localhost', just means 'this very computer', and 8188 is the port ComfyUI listens on).","IMPORTANT: leave the little black command window OPEN — closing it shuts ComfyUI down."],"commands":["In your browser address bar, this should appear automatically: http://127.0.0.1:8188"],"check":"a browser tab titled ComfyUI shows a graph of nodes."},{"title":"Load the built-in starter workflow (the default node graph)","detail":"This step loads the standard text-to-image node layout so you have a working example to learn on.","do":["In the ComfyUI window, open the Workflow menu (top-left).","Choose Browse Workflow Templates, then pick the basic 'Image Generation' / text-to-image template.","If the canvas is already showing a graph, you can instead click the Load Default option.","Read the boxes left to right, because this is the lesson in how a diffusion model works: Load Checkpoint (loads the AI model) -> two CLIP Text Encode boxes (your positive prompt of what you want, and your negative prompt of what to avoid) -> Empty Latent Image (a blank canvas of the right size) -> KSampler (removes noise step by step to form the image) -> VAE Decode (turns the model's internal math into a real picture) -> Save Image."],"commands":[],"check":"those boxes appear on screen, joined by colored wires."},{"title":"Get a model file (the 'checkpoint') if the template asks for one","detail":"The Load Checkpoint node needs an actual model file to work — the multi-gigabyte 'brain' that generates images. This step gets that file onto your computer.","do":["If ComfyUI pops up a prompt offering to download the missing file, click to accept and wait for the progress bar.","If it does NOT auto-offer, open the Manager (the Manager button in the top menu, included with the Desktop app).","Click Install Models.","Download a beginner-friendly checkpoint — an SD 1.5 or SDXL model is small and forgiving; Flux is higher quality but larger and needs more VRAM."],"commands":["Manager -> Install Models -> pick an SD 1.5 or SDXL checkpoint -> Install"],"check":"a .safetensors file finishes downloading with no errors."},{"title":"(Only if you downloaded a model file manually) put it in the checkpoints folder","detail":"If you got a model file yourself from a site like Hugging Face instead of using the Manager, this step places it where ComfyUI looks for it.","do":["Move the  .safetensors  file into the  models/checkpoints  folder inside your ComfyUI installation.","In the Desktop app, find this folder via Settings, which shows your models path; in the Portable version it's the  ComfyUI/models/checkpoints  subfolder.","Click the small circular refresh arrow on the Load Checkpoint node (or reload the browser tab) so the new file appears in the dropdown."],"commands":["Windows Portable path: <extracted folder>\\ComfyUI\\models\\checkpoints\\","Put your .safetensors file there, then click the refresh arrow on the Load Checkpoint node"],"check":"your model's name shows up in the Load Checkpoint dropdown."},{"title":"Select the model and write your prompts","detail":"This step picks your model and fills in the two prompt boxes that tell the AI what to make and what to avoid.","do":["Click the dropdown inside the Load Checkpoint node and choose your downloaded model.","Click into the positive prompt box (the CLIP Text Encode node wired toward the 'positive' input of KSampler) and type what you want to see, for example:  a photo of a red bicycle leaning on a stone wall, morning light, sharp focus .","Click into the negative prompt box (the other CLIP Text Encode node) and type what to avoid, for example:  blurry, text, watermark, extra limbs ."],"commands":[],"check":"your model is selected and both text boxes are filled with your words."},{"title":"Run your first render and find the saved image","detail":"This step runs the workflow to generate your first image and shows you where it is saved.","do":["Press the Queue (Run) button — the large button in the toolbar, sometimes labeled Queue Prompt or shown as a play/queue icon.","Watch the green highlight move through the nodes one at a time, and the progress bar count the KSampler steps.","Be patient — the FIRST render is slowest because the model is loading into memory (a minute or several on a weak machine, a few seconds on a strong GPU).","Find the finished picture inside the Save Image node on the canvas, and as a new  .png  file in the ComfyUI/output folder.","Change a word in your prompt and press Queue again to iterate — you're now experimenting."],"commands":["Click Queue (Run). Find results in: <your ComfyUI folder>\\output\\"],"check":"a finished image appears on screen and a new .png file lands in the output folder."},{"title":"(Alternative install) The Portable version, step by step","detail":"If you preferred the Portable route, this step installs and launches it instead of the Desktop app; from there you rejoin the same steps above.","do":["Download the Windows portable  .7z  from the official GitHub releases page:  https://github.com/comfy-org/ComfyUI/releases .","Right-click the  .7z  file and use 7-Zip -> Extract Here (regular Windows unzip will fail on .7z).","Open the extracted folder and double-click  run_nvidia_gpu.bat  if you have an NVIDIA card, or  run_cpu.bat  if you have no dedicated GPU.","Wait for the black window's startup text to end with a line like 'To see the GUI go to: http://127.0.0.1:8188', and let your browser open there.","From this point, follow the same steps above for loading the workflow, adding a checkpoint, prompting, and queuing."],"commands":["Download the portable build from https://github.com/comfy-org/ComfyUI/releases","Right-click the .7z file -> 7-Zip -> Extract Here","Double-click run_nvidia_gpu.bat  (or run_cpu.bat if you have no GPU)"],"check":"the same ComfyUI canvas opens in your browser at  127.0.0.1:8188 ."}],"resources":[{"label":"ComfyUI official download (Desktop app, auto-detects your OS)","url":"https://comfy.org/download"},{"label":"ComfyUI official documentation (install guides, node reference, templates)","url":"https://docs.comfy.org"},{"label":"ComfyUI Portable for Windows — step-by-step official guide","url":"https://docs.comfy.org/installation/comfyui_portable_windows"},{"label":"ComfyUI source, releases, and portable builds on GitHub","url":"https://github.com/comfy-org/ComfyUI"},{"label":"Hugging Face — where open-weight Stable Diffusion and Flux model files (.safetensors) are hosted","url":"https://huggingface.co"},{"label":"Video search phrase: 'ComfyUI beginner tutorial 2026 first image install desktop'"},{"label":"Video search phrase: 'ComfyUI explained node graph load checkpoint KSampler VAE decode'"}],"cloudTieIn":"You have probably made AI images by typing a sentence into a cloud tool — Microsoft Copilot, ChatGPT (DALL-E), or Google Gemini all generate pictures from a single text box, and Anthropic's Claude helps you write and refine the prompts. ComfyUI is the opposite philosophy: instead of hiding the machinery behind one box, it exposes every stage (model -> prompt -> latent -> sample -> decode -> image), which makes it the best tool for actually understanding what those cloud services do internally. Use the cloud when you want the highest-quality result with zero setup, when you are on a weak laptop, or when you need the newest flagship image model; use ComfyUI locally when privacy matters (nothing leaves your computer), when you want unlimited free iterations, or when you need fine control the cloud tools do not expose. A great habit: ask Claude, Copilot, ChatGPT, or Gemini to help you craft and improve your positive and negative prompts, then paste those prompts into ComfyUI to generate the actual images privately on your own hardware.","troubleshooting":[{"symptom":"Generation fails with an 'out of memory', 'CUDA out of memory', or 'allocation' error.","fix":"Your GPU ran out of VRAM. Lower the image size in the Empty Latent Image node (try 512x512 for SD 1.5), use a smaller model (SD 1.5 instead of SDXL or Flux), and close other GPU-heavy apps like games or video editors. On a laptop, plug it into power. As a last resort, restart ComfyUI to clear stuck memory."},{"symptom":"The browser says the page cannot be reached, or 'connection refused' at 127.0.0.1:8188.","fix":"ComfyUI is not actually running. Make sure the little black command window is still open (closing it stops the program). Relaunch the Desktop app or re-run the .bat file, wait for the 'To see the GUI go to' line, then reload the browser tab. If it still fails, restart your computer and try once more."},{"symptom":"It says port 8188 is already in use, or a second copy will not start.","fix":"ComfyUI is probably already running in another window or browser tab. Close the extra command windows, then open just one browser tab to http://127.0.0.1:8188. If you truly need two copies, that is an advanced setup — for now run only one."},{"symptom":"The Load Checkpoint node dropdown is empty or says 'null' / 'undefined'.","fix":"No model file is in the checkpoints folder yet. Use Manager -> Install Models to download one, or place a .safetensors file into ComfyUI/models/checkpoints, then click the refresh arrow on the node or reload the browser tab so it appears."},{"symptom":"The first image takes a very long time or seems frozen.","fix":"The first render is always the slowest because the multi-gigabyte model is loading into memory — this is normal, especially CPU-only. Watch the black command window: if text is still moving, it is working, not frozen. Later renders with the same model are much faster. If you have no dedicated GPU, expect minutes per image and use small (512x512) sizes."},{"symptom":"7-Zip errors or Windows cannot open the downloaded .7z portable file.","fix":"Windows cannot open .7z archives on its own. Install the free 7-Zip from 7-zip.org, then right-click the file and choose 7-Zip -> Extract Here. Do not try to run the .bat files from inside the compressed archive — you must extract to a real folder first."}],"tips":["Start with a small, forgiving model (Stable Diffusion 1.5 or SDXL) before trying Flux — Flux gives better results but needs much more VRAM and downloads several gigabytes more.","Everything you generate is saved automatically as a .png in the ComfyUI/output folder, and each image file secretly contains the exact workflow that made it — drag that .png back onto the ComfyUI canvas to instantly reload the whole node setup.","Change only one thing at a time (one prompt word, or one setting like 'steps' in the KSampler) and re-queue, so you learn what each control actually does instead of guessing.","Use the ComfyUI-Manager (bundled with the Desktop app) as your safe front door for installing models and community add-on nodes — it puts files in the right folders for you so you avoid manual mistakes.","Because generation is fully local, it is genuinely private and free to iterate — but 'local' does not automatically mean 'compliant': you are still responsible for not creating or storing images you are not allowed to, and for any real people's likenesses you feed in."],"difficulty":"Intermediate — comfortable installing apps and downloading large (multi-gigabyte) model files","time":"About 30–45 minutes (mostly waiting for the model download)"},{"id":"lab18","n":18,"cat":"M","title":"Whisper — Local, Offline Speech-to-Text","tagline":"Set up a completely offline speech-to-text engine on your own computer so private audio (meetings, interviews, lectures) is transcribed to text with zero data leaving your machine.","whatItIs":"Whisper is a free, open-source speech-to-text model made by OpenAI that turns spoken audio into written text. Normally you'd send audio to a cloud service, but Whisper can run entirely on your own laptop or desktop, offline. This lab sets up Buzz, a free point-and-click app that runs Whisper locally with drag-and-drop simplicity, and then shows the optional \"power user\" route using Whisper.cpp, a hyper-optimized version that runs from a terminal. In both cases the audio file and the transcript never touch the internet.","whyUseIt":"Audio from private company meetings, medical visits, or research interviews is a privacy minefield: uploading it to a cloud transcription service means a third party now holds a recording of identifiable people saying private things. Running Whisper locally eliminates that exposure entirely, which matters directly for FERPA (student records) and HIPAA (health data) where identifiable audio should stay on a controlled machine. It's also effectively free, no per-minute fees or subscriptions, so you can transcribe hundreds of hours at $0 in usage cost. Use it whenever the audio is sensitive, when you have a lot to transcribe, or when you simply have no internet. Be honest with yourself, though: local transcription is not automatically compliant (you still control where the files live), and the model can mishear names, jargon, and crosstalk, so always proofread the transcript before trusting it.","bestFor":"Anyone who needs to transcribe private or sensitive audio (student interviews, faculty meetings, medical or legal recordings, research fieldwork) where the recording legally or ethically must not be uploaded to a cloud service.","platforms":["Windows","macOS","Linux"],"prerequisites":["A computer with at least 8 GB of RAM (16 GB is more comfortable for longer files). No graphics card is required; a GPU just makes it faster.","About 3-5 GB of free disk space: the app itself plus one or more downloaded Whisper model files (the 'base' model is ~150 MB, the 'large' model is ~3 GB).","An audio or video file you want to transcribe (MP3, WAV, M4A, or MP4 all work). If you don't have one, any voice memo from your phone works for practice.","An internet connection ONCE, only to download the app and the model file. After that, transcription runs fully offline.","No prior terminal experience is needed for the main path (Buzz). The optional advanced path (Whisper.cpp) does use the terminal, and this lab walks you through it click by click.","Optional but recommended: Ollama installed (from ollama.com) if you also want to summarize the transcript with a local AI afterward, as described in the last step."],"steps":[{"title":"Understand the plan (read this first, nothing to click yet)","detail":"This lab installs one free app called Buzz that runs the Whisper speech-to-text model on your own computer, offline. Here you are just getting the lay of the land before you click anything.","do":["Know the goal: install a free app called Buzz that turns spoken audio into written text, entirely on your own computer.","Understand you will pick a 'model size' (a speed-versus-accuracy trade-off), drag in an audio file, and export a text transcript.","Remember that everything runs offline, so no audio ever leaves your machine.","If you would rather use the fast command-line engine instead, skip ahead to Step 8 for the Whisper.cpp route."],"commands":[],"check":"you understand the end goal: a .txt or .srt file full of the words that were spoken, created entirely offline."},{"title":"Download and install Buzz (the no-terminal app)","detail":"Buzz is the free app that runs Whisper with buttons instead of commands. This step downloads and installs it for your operating system.","do":["Open your web browser and go to the official Buzz releases page.","On Windows: download the three Windows files (one ending in .exe and two ending in .bin) and put all three in the same folder.","On Windows: double-click the .exe file to start it.","On Windows: if a blue 'Windows protected your PC' warning appears, click 'More info', then click 'Run anyway'.","On macOS: download the .dmg file, double-click it, and drag the Buzz icon into your Applications folder.","On macOS: the first time, right-click the Buzz icon and choose 'Open' to get past the 'unidentified developer' prompt.","On Linux: open a terminal and run the snap command shown below."],"commands":["sudo snap install buzz"],"check":"the Buzz window opens with an empty list and a '+' or 'New Transcription' button."},{"title":"Start a new transcription and load your audio file","detail":"Now you tell Buzz which audio file to transcribe. This only loads the file; it does not start the work yet.","do":["In Buzz, click the '+' button (or click 'File', then 'New Transcription').","When the dialog appears asking for the source, choose 'Import File'.","Browse to and select your audio or video file (MP3, WAV, M4A, or MP4).","Check that the file's name now appears in the dialog."],"commands":[],"check":"your file's name is shown in the transcription setup window."},{"title":"Choose your model size (the accuracy vs. speed dial)","detail":"The model size sets the trade-off between speed and accuracy: bigger is more accurate but slower and heavier. For your first run you will pick a small, fast one so you can see the whole process quickly.","do":["In the same dialog, find the 'Model' or 'Model Size' dropdown.","For your first run, choose 'base' so it finishes quickly (tiny/base = very fast; small = balanced; medium = better on accents but slower; large = best accuracy but needs ~16 GB RAM).","Set the 'Language' to the spoken language, or choose 'Detect'.","Leave 'Task' set to 'Transcribe' (not 'Translate')."],"commands":[],"check":"the dropdown shows your chosen model."},{"title":"Let Buzz download the model once, then run it offline","detail":"The very first time you use a given model size, Buzz downloads it once — the only network step in the whole lab. After that it runs entirely offline.","do":["Click 'Run' (or 'Start').","Wait while Buzz downloads the model the first time, shown as 'Downloading model...' (about 150 MB for 'base', up to ~3 GB for 'large').","Watch the status change to 'In Progress' as it transcribes.","Wait for it to finish — a 10-minute clip on 'base' usually takes well under a minute on a modern laptop."],"commands":[],"check":"the status changes to 'Completed' and the transcript text appears on screen."},{"title":"Review the transcript and export it as text with timestamps","detail":"Now you open the finished transcript, fix any obvious mistakes, and save it to your computer as a file.","do":["Double-click the completed item to open the transcript.","Read a few lines and fix any obvious mistakes (Whisper often mishears proper names, technical jargon, and crosstalk).","Click 'Export'.","Choose a format: pick TXT for plain text, or SRT / VTT to stamp each line with the time it was spoken.","Pick a folder you control and save the file."],"commands":[],"check":"a transcript file is saved on your disk, created without a single byte of your audio leaving the computer."},{"title":"Confirm it was truly offline (the privacy check)","detail":"This optional check proves the transcription really is private by running it again with the internet switched off.","do":["Turn off your Wi-Fi or disconnect your network.","Start another transcription using the same model you already downloaded in Step 5.","Confirm Buzz still transcribes normally with no internet connection.","Remember that 'offline' protects the data in transit, but you are still responsible for where the files are stored and who can access that computer."],"commands":[],"check":"Buzz still transcribes normally even with the network disconnected."},{"title":"OPTIONAL power-user route: run Whisper.cpp from the terminal","detail":"This optional route swaps the Buzz app for Whisper.cpp, a leaner, faster engine you drive from the terminal. You will download it, build it, and transcribe a built-in sample to confirm it works.","do":["Open a terminal: on Windows press the Start key, type 'PowerShell', and press Enter; on macOS press Cmd+Space, type 'Terminal', and press Enter.","Type each command below one line at a time, pressing Enter after each.","Run the 'git clone' command to download the project.","Run 'cd whisper.cpp' to move into the project folder.","Run the download-ggml-model.sh command to fetch the 'base' English model.","Run the two 'cmake' commands to build the program.","Run the final whisper-cli command to transcribe the built-in JFK sample.","For your own audio, first convert it to 16 kHz WAV with ffmpeg (ffmpeg -i input.mp3 -ar 16000 output.wav)."],"commands":["git clone https://github.com/ggml-org/whisper.cpp.git","cd whisper.cpp","sh ./models/download-ggml-model.sh base.en","cmake -B build","cmake --build build -j --config Release","./build/bin/whisper-cli -m models/ggml-base.en.bin -f samples/jfk.wav"],"check":"transcribed text with [timestamps] prints in the terminal, and a matching .txt/.srt is written next to your audio file."},{"title":"OPTIONAL: summarize the transcript with a local AI (keep it all offline)","detail":"Because your transcript is just text, you can hand it to a local language model for a summary or action items without anything leaving your machine.","do":["Make sure you have Ollama installed (from ollama.com); it exposes a local API at http://localhost:11434.","Run the 'ollama pull gemma' command to download a small model that fits your RAM.","Run the 'ollama run' command below, pasting your transcript where it says <paste transcript here>.","Read the summary and action items it produces."],"commands":["ollama pull gemma","ollama run gemma \"Summarize this meeting transcript into 5 bullet points and a list of action items: <paste transcript here>\""],"check":"a written summary appears, generated entirely on your own computer."}],"resources":[{"label":"Buzz — official GitHub repo (free, open-source Whisper GUI for Windows/macOS/Linux)","url":"https://github.com/chidiwilliams/buzz"},{"label":"Buzz — official installation guide","url":"https://chidiwilliams.github.io/buzz/docs/installation"},{"label":"Whisper.cpp — official GitHub repo (the optimized C/C++ engine and download-ggml-model.sh script)","url":"https://github.com/ggml-org/whisper.cpp"},{"label":"Whisper.cpp model files (ggml-base.bin and other quantized weights) on Hugging Face","url":"https://huggingface.co/ggerganov/whisper.cpp"},{"label":"Ollama — official site, for locally summarizing your transcript after transcription","url":"https://ollama.com"},{"label":"Video search phrase: 'Buzz Whisper offline transcription tutorial for beginners'"},{"label":"Video search phrase: 'whisper.cpp install and build ggml-base.bin step by step'"}],"cloudTieIn":"This local Whisper setup complements the cloud AI assistants you may already use rather than replacing them. Tools like Microsoft Copilot, ChatGPT, Google Gemini, and (via its apps) Anthropic Claude can transcribe or summarize audio, but doing so sends your recording to their servers, which is exactly what you want to avoid for FERPA/HIPAA-sensitive meetings and interviews. The practical pattern is to transcribe locally with Whisper so the sensitive audio never leaves your machine, then, if you choose, paste only the de-identified text into a cloud assistant for polishing, translation, or drafting, keeping the raw recording private. When accuracy on a hard file really matters (heavy accents, terrible audio, rare languages), the frontier cloud models may still transcribe better, so use local as the private default and reach for cloud deliberately when the audio isn't sensitive and quality is critical.","troubleshooting":[{"symptom":"Windows shows 'Windows protected your PC' and won't let the Buzz installer run.","fix":"This is because the free app isn't code-signed, not because it's unsafe. Click the small 'More info' link on the warning, then click the 'Run anyway' button that appears. On macOS the equivalent is right-clicking the app and choosing 'Open' the first time."},{"symptom":"Transcription is extremely slow or the app freezes on a long file.","fix":"You likely picked too large a model for your hardware. Switch to a smaller model ('base' or 'small' instead of 'medium'/'large'), and close other heavy apps to free RAM. A GPU speeds this up a lot, but a smaller model is the quickest fix on a CPU-only machine."},{"symptom":"The app crashes or reports 'out of memory' when loading the 'large' model.","fix":"The 'large' model needs roughly 16 GB of RAM. On an 8 GB machine, use 'base' or 'small', which are designed for lighter hardware. This mirrors the general local-AI rule that model size must fit your available memory."},{"symptom":"The model download never finishes or fails partway.","fix":"The one-time model download needs internet; check your connection and try again, since a partial file can also cause 'model won't load' errors. In Buzz you can re-download from Help then Preferences then Models. For Whisper.cpp, re-run the download-ggml-model.sh script."},{"symptom":"In Whisper.cpp you get an error about the audio format or garbled output.","fix":"Whisper.cpp only accepts 16 kHz WAV files. Convert your audio first with ffmpeg: run 'ffmpeg -i yourfile.mp3 -ar 16000 -ac 1 converted.wav', then point whisper-cli at converted.wav."},{"symptom":"The transcript has wrong names, made-up words, or jumbled crosstalk.","fix":"This is expected: Whisper mishears proper nouns, jargon, and overlapping speakers, and can occasionally 'hallucinate' text during silence. Use a larger model for better accuracy and always proofread. Local transcription is fast and private, but it is not automatically correct and must be verified before you rely on it."},{"symptom":"The optional Ollama summary step says 'connection refused' at localhost:11434.","fix":"Ollama isn't running. Start it (open the Ollama app, or run 'ollama serve' in a terminal), confirm it's installed from ollama.com, then re-run your 'ollama run' command. The local API only answers when the Ollama service is up."}],"tips":["Pick the smallest model that's 'good enough': test 'base' first, and only move up to 'small'/'medium' if the accuracy on your specific audio isn't acceptable. You'll save huge amounts of time.","Record and feed in the cleanest audio you can, a single speaker, close mic, minimal background noise dramatically improves accuracy far more than a bigger model does.","Export as SRT or VTT (timestamped) rather than plain TXT when you'll need to jump back to specific moments in the recording; you can always strip the timestamps later.","Keep your transcripts and audio in an encrypted, access-controlled folder. 'Offline' stops third-party exposure, but on-disk security and who can log into the computer are still your responsibility for FERPA/HIPAA data.","Chain it: transcribe locally with Whisper, then summarize locally with an Ollama model (Gemma or Llama 3.x 8B on 8 GB) for a start-to-finish private meeting-notes workflow that never touches the cloud."],"difficulty":"Intermediate — the main app is point-and-click; the two optional power-user steps use the terminal","time":"About 30 minutes, plus one-time model-download time"},{"id":"lab19","n":19,"cat":"O","title":"Open Hermes & Choosing the Right Model","tagline":"Learn to pick the right open-weight AI model for your task and hardware, then pull a specialized community favorite like OpenHermes into Ollama and feel the difference a model choice makes.","whatItIs":"An open-weight model is an AI \"brain\" you download and run entirely on your own computer, for free, with no internet needed after the download. Ollama is a small, free program that fetches these models from an online catalog and lets you chat with them in a text window. This lab teaches you that not all models are the same: a plain \"base\" model just predicts text, while an \"instruct\" or \"fine-tuned\" model like OpenHermes has been specially trained to follow your instructions, hold a conversation, and behave the way you'd expect a helpful assistant to behave. Choosing the right model is like choosing the right tool from a toolbox, and this lab shows you how to read the labels and pick well.","whyUseIt":"Model choice is the single biggest lever a beginner controls, and this lab makes that lever visible. A generic base model merely continues text, while an instruction-tuned model like OpenHermes has been fine-tuned to follow directions, hold a conversation, and stay coherent; a coding-tuned or reasoning-tuned variant behaves differently again. Use this whenever you want to understand hands-on why professionals obsess over 'which model,' or when you need a safe, cheap, repeatable way to try specialized community models. Running locally means your prompts never leave your computer, which is the privacy-safe default for identifiable data under FERPA or HIPAA, avoids third-party retention for security, and costs roughly nothing per use versus cloud per-token or subscription pricing. Remember the honest caveats: local models are weaker on the hardest tasks and must be verified, and local is not automatically compliant.","bestFor":"A non-technical learner who has installed Ollama (or is willing to) and wants to understand, hands-on, why picking a specialized instruction-tuned model like OpenHermes changes how the AI behaves.","platforms":["Windows","macOS","Linux"],"prerequisites":["Ollama installed and running (this lab uses it as the local framework). If you have not installed it, Step 1 tells you exactly how, so you can start from zero.","A computer with at least 8 GB of memory (RAM). OpenHermes is a 7-billion-parameter model that needs roughly 5 to 6 GB free while running; 8 GB total is the realistic floor, 16 GB is comfortable.","About 6 GB of free disk space for the OpenHermes download, plus room for any other models you try.","An internet connection for the one-time downloads only. After a model is downloaded, chatting with it works fully offline.","About 30 to 45 minutes, most of which is waiting for the model to download the first time.","No coding experience required. You will type a few short commands exactly as written; the lab explains what each one does."],"steps":[{"title":"Open your terminal (the text window where you type commands)","detail":"A terminal is a plain window where you type a command and press Enter to run it. This step just opens one — you will use it for the rest of the lab.","do":["On Windows: click the Start button (bottom-left of the screen), type the word powershell, and click 'Windows PowerShell' when it appears.","On macOS: press Command and the Spacebar together, type the word terminal, and press Enter.","On Linux: press Ctrl+Alt+T.","Wait for the window with a blinking cursor to open."],"commands":[],"check":"a window with a blinking cursor is open, waiting for you to type."},{"title":"Confirm Ollama is installed and running","detail":"Ollama is the free program that fetches these models and lets you chat with them. This step proves it is installed by asking for its version number.","do":["In the terminal window, type the command below exactly and press Enter.","Look for a short line such as 'ollama version is 0.x.x'.","If you instead see 'command not found' or 'not recognized as the name of a cmdlet', go to ollama.com/download and install it (Windows: double-click OllamaSetup.exe and click through; macOS: open the .dmg and drag Ollama to Applications).","After installing, re-open the terminal and run the command again."],"commands":["ollama --version"],"check":"a short line such as 'ollama version is 0.x.x' prints back."},{"title":"See what a model registry looks like (read the labels before you buy)","detail":"Before downloading anything, you will look at Ollama's online catalog and read a model's 'card' — its description and size — the way you would read a label before buying.","do":["Open a web browser and go to Ollama's model registry, the catalog of every model you can pull.","Then visit ollama.com/library/openhermes specifically.","Read the model card: the short description, the Tags dropdown, and the file sizes.","Notice the description says OpenHermes 2.5 is a 7B model fine-tuned from Mistral on hundreds of thousands of instructions, and that it is instruction-tuned for chat."],"commands":[],"check":"you can point at the page and say 'this is a 7-billion-parameter, instruction-tuned chat model, about 4 GB to download.'"},{"title":"Learn to read a model tag (the secret code after the colon)","detail":"A model 'tag' is the recipe written after the colon in a name like openhermes:7b-mistral-v2.5-q4_K_M. This step teaches you to read it so you know exactly what you are downloading.","do":["Still on the OpenHermes page, click the Tags dropdown.","Look at names like openhermes:latest and openhermes:7b-mistral-v2.5-q4_K_M.","Read the tag as name:size-type-quantization: '7b' means 7 billion parameters, 'mistral-v2.5' is the base model it was fine-tuned from, and 'q4_K_M' means it was compressed to 4 bits per number.","Remember that typing a model name with no tag makes Ollama pick a sensible default (usually the Q4 version)."],"commands":[],"check":"you understand that 'q4' in a tag is what makes a 7B model run on a normal laptop."},{"title":"Pull OpenHermes into your local framework","detail":"'Pulling' downloads the OpenHermes model from the registry to your machine, but does not start it yet. It is roughly 4 GB, so give it a few minutes.","do":["Back in the terminal, type the command below and press Enter.","Watch the one or more progress bars fill up — the download is roughly 4 GB.","Leave the window open and do not close it while it works.","If the download stalls or errors out partway, run the exact same command again — Ollama resumes where it left off."],"commands":["ollama pull openhermes"],"check":"the progress bars reach 100 percent and a final line says 'success'."},{"title":"Confirm the model is now on your machine","detail":"This lists every model you have downloaded, proving OpenHermes now lives on your computer and needs no internet to use.","do":["Type the command below and press Enter.","Read the table it prints — each row shows a model's name, a short ID, its size on disk, and when you got it.","Find the row for 'openhermes:latest' with a size around 4 GB.","If the list is empty, the pull in the previous step did not finish, so repeat Step 5."],"commands":["ollama list"],"check":"the table shows a row for 'openhermes:latest' at a size around 4 GB."},{"title":"Chat with OpenHermes and feel the instruction-tuning","detail":"Now you load OpenHermes into memory and chat with it live, giving it real instructions to feel how closely it follows the format you ask for.","do":["Type the command below and press Enter to drop into a live chat prompt (you will see a '>>>' symbol).","Wait 10 to 60 seconds for the first response as the model loads into memory.","Type the instruction: Explain what a firewall is to a 10-year-old, in exactly three sentences. — then press Enter.","Read the answer and notice it follows the exact format you asked for.","Try a second, harder ask like: Now rewrite that as a short rhyming poem.","Type /bye and press Enter to leave the chat."],"commands":["ollama run openhermes","Explain what a firewall is to a 10-year-old, in exactly three sentences.","/bye"],"check":"coherent, on-instruction answers appear in your terminal, generated entirely offline on your own hardware."},{"title":"Compare against a different model so 'model choice matters' becomes real","detail":"Now you pull a second, different-flavored model and ask it the same questions, so the contrast between models becomes something you can feel.","do":["Run the first command below to pull Google's compact Gemma model.","Run the second command to start chatting with it.","Give it the exact same firewall instruction you used in Step 7.","Compare the tone, length, and how closely each model obeyed the 'exactly three sentences' rule.","Try one more comparison of your own — for example, ask each model to write a two-line Python function.","Type /bye and press Enter when finished."],"commands":["ollama pull gemma3","ollama run gemma3","/bye"],"check":"you can say, in your own words, why you would choose one model over another for a given job."},{"title":"Match the model to your hardware (so you never pick one too big to run)","detail":"Before pulling any new model, you do a quick sanity check against your computer's memory so you never download one too big to run. This step also shows what Ollama is currently holding in memory.","do":["Note your computer's memory (RAM, called 'unified memory' on Apple Silicon Macs or 'VRAM' on an NVIDIA graphics card).","Use the rough Q4 rule: 8 GB comfortably runs 3B–8B models; 16–24 GB handles 12B–32B; 40 GB or more is needed for ~70B; 128 GB (or multi-GPU) runs frontier-class models like Qwen 3.5 122B.","Run the command below to see which models Ollama is currently holding in memory and how much they are using."],"commands":["ollama ps"],"check":"you can size up a model's parameter count against your own RAM before you pull it, so you never download something that will not run."}],"resources":[{"label":"Ollama official download page (installers for Windows, macOS, Linux)","url":"https://ollama.com/download"},{"label":"Ollama model registry / library (browse all pullable models and read model cards)","url":"https://ollama.com/library"},{"label":"OpenHermes model card and tags on Ollama","url":"https://ollama.com/library/openhermes"},{"label":"Hugging Face Open LLM Leaderboard and model hub (compare and evaluate open models)","url":"https://huggingface.co/models"},{"label":"Ollama GitHub repository (official docs, CLI reference, and issue tracker)","url":"https://github.com/ollama/ollama"},{"label":"Video search phrase: 'Ollama beginner tutorial install and run first model'","url":""},{"label":"Video search phrase: 'what is model fine-tuning instruct vs base model explained'","url":""}],"cloudTieIn":"The frontier cloud assistants you may already use, Microsoft Copilot, Anthropic Claude, OpenAI ChatGPT, and Google Gemini, are themselves very large fine-tuned models running on someone else's servers; what you did in this lab is the same idea shrunk down to run on your own machine. Think of it as a two-track workflow: use a cloud assistant when you need maximum reasoning power on your hardest or most creative tasks, and reach for a local model like OpenHermes when the data is sensitive (student records, health information), when you want zero per-use cost, or when you want to work offline. A practical pattern is to draft or brainstorm privately on a local model, then, only if needed and only with non-identifiable data, move to a cloud tool for the final polish. The model-selection skill is identical in both worlds: on the cloud you pick between Copilot, Claude, ChatGPT, or Gemini for a job; locally you pick between OpenHermes, Gemma, Qwen, or Llama. Learning to read model cards here makes you a sharper chooser everywhere.","troubleshooting":[{"symptom":"'ollama' is not recognized (Windows) or 'command not found' (macOS/Linux) when you type a command.","fix":"Ollama is not installed or the terminal was open before you installed it. Install it from ollama.com/download, then fully close the terminal window and open a brand-new one so it picks up the newly installed command, and try again."},{"symptom":"The download stalls, freezes, or ends with a network/connection error partway through the pull.","fix":"Run the exact same 'ollama pull' command again. Ollama resumes the partial download rather than restarting it. If it keeps failing, check your internet connection and confirm no firewall or VPN is blocking ollama.com."},{"symptom":"An error mentioning 'out of memory', 'not enough memory', or the model fails to load / your computer freezes when you run it.","fix":"The model is too large for your RAM. Close other heavy apps (browsers with many tabs, video editors) and try again. If it still fails, pick a smaller model: for 8 GB machines choose a 3B to 8B model such as phi4-mini or a small Gemma variant instead of anything 12B or larger."},{"symptom":"'Error: could not connect to ollama app' or 'connection refused' on localhost:11434.","fix":"The Ollama background service is not running. On Windows and macOS, open the Ollama app from your Start menu or Applications folder to start it, then return to the terminal. On Linux, run 'ollama serve' in a separate terminal window and leave it open, then try your command again."},{"symptom":"The first response takes a long time (10 to 60 seconds) or feels slow.","fix":"This is normal. The first reply includes loading the whole model into memory. Later replies in the same session are faster. If every reply is slow, your model is likely too big for your hardware, so switch to a smaller one; a model that fits comfortably in memory responds much quicker."},{"symptom":"The port is already in use, or you see 'address already in use' / '11434 in use'.","fix":"Ollama is already running in the background, so you do not need to start it again. Just run your 'ollama run' or 'ollama list' command directly. If a stuck process is the problem, restart your computer to clear it, then try once more."},{"symptom":"The model gives a confident but wrong or made-up answer.","fix":"This is expected. Local models, especially smaller ones, are weaker on the hardest tasks and can hallucinate, so always verify important facts yourself. Running locally keeps data private but local is not automatically compliant or automatically correct; treat every answer as a draft to check."}],"tips":["Pull with no tag (for example 'ollama run openhermes') to get Ollama's sensible Q4 default; only add a specific tag like ':7b-mistral-v2.5-q4_K_M' once you know exactly why you want that variant.","When comparing models, use the identical prompt for each one and change nothing else. Same input, different model, is the cleanest way to see what fine-tuning actually changed.","Match parameter count to memory before you download: with Q4, keep to 3B-8B on 8 GB, 12B-32B on 16-24 GB, and don't attempt ~70B unless you have 40 GB or more. This saves you failed downloads.","Delete models you're done with using 'ollama rm <model-name>' to reclaim disk space; each 7B model is roughly 4 GB.","'Open weight' does not mean 'open training data' and does not mean 'free for any use'. Always check the license on the model card (for example Qwen and gpt-oss are Apache-2.0, Llama has its own community license) before using a model for real work."],"difficulty":"Intermediate — comfortable opening a terminal and copy-pasting commands","time":"About 30–45 minutes, mostly waiting on model downloads"},{"id":"lab20","n":20,"cat":"O","title":"VRAM & Quantization — Will This Model Fit?","tagline":"Learn to calculate whether an AI model will fit in your computer's memory before you download it, so it runs smoothly instead of freezing or crashing your machine.","whatItIs":"Every AI model is a big file made of billions of numbers called \"parameters.\" To answer your questions, the model has to be loaded into fast memory: on a Mac with Apple Silicon that is \"unified memory\" (shared between the processor and graphics); on a Windows PC with an NVIDIA graphics card that is \"VRAM\" (memory that lives on the graphics card itself). \"Quantization\" is a compression trick that shrinks each of those numbers so the model takes up much less memory, at a small cost to quality. This lab teaches you a simple pencil-and-paper way to check, in advance, whether a given model will fit in your machine's memory, and how to pick the right compressed version so it fits and runs fast.","whyUseIt":"Downloading a model that is too big for your memory does not give an error at download time, it fails later when you try to use it: the machine freezes, the fan roars, the answer crawls out one word every few seconds, or the app crashes entirely. Knowing the quick math up front saves you a multi-gigabyte download and a frustrating crash. It also lets you shop for models on purpose: instead of guessing, you can look at a model labeled \"8B\" and immediately know whether your laptop can run it and which compressed file to grab. For a college program handling student records (FERPA) or health data (HIPAA), running the model locally keeps that data on your own machine instead of sending it to a cloud company, and open-weight models cost about $0 per use instead of a per-message cloud bill, so being able to fit one on your own hardware is what makes the private, free path possible.","bestFor":"A complete beginner who wants to run a local AI model on their own laptop and needs to know, before downloading, whether it will actually fit and run without crashing.","platforms":["Windows (NVIDIA GPU or CPU-only)","macOS (Apple Silicon: M1/M2/M3/M4)","Linux (NVIDIA GPU or CPU-only)"],"prerequisites":["A laptop or desktop running Windows 10/11, macOS (Apple Silicon), or Linux. Older Intel Macs work but are much slower.","About 10-20 GB of free disk space for one or two models (each model file is several GB).","Knowing how much memory your machine has: on a Mac, the number after \"Memory\" in About This Mac (e.g., 16 GB); on a Windows NVIDIA laptop, your graphics-card VRAM (this lab shows you how to find it).","Ollama installed (free, from ollama.com). It runs models locally and exposes a local address at http://localhost:11434. This lab shows the install.","An internet connection for the one-time downloads of Ollama and the model. After that, the model runs fully offline.","No prior terminal experience required. The lab tells you exactly how to open the terminal and what to type."],"steps":[{"title":"Understand the one formula you will use all lab","detail":"This whole lab rests on one simple formula for estimating how much memory a model needs. Here you just learn the rule — you do not type anything.","do":["Learn the rule: a model's memory need is roughly (parameters in billions) times (bytes per parameter), plus a little overhead.","Remember that a 4-bit 'Q4' model (the most common) uses about 0.55–0.6 GB of memory for every 1 billion parameters.","Use the beginner shortcut: billions-of-parameters times 0.6, then add about 1–2 GB of overhead for the software and your conversation.","Practice on an 8B model: 8 times 0.6 = about 5 GB, plus overhead, so about 6–7 GB total."],"commands":[],"check":"you can say the rule out loud — an 8B model at Q4 needs about 6–7 GB total."},{"title":"Find out how much memory your machine has","detail":"Now you find your computer's memory budget — the one number every later step compares against. Where you look depends on your machine.","do":["On a Mac: click the Apple logo in the top-left corner, choose 'About This Mac', and read the 'Memory' line (for example 16 GB).","On a Mac (Apple Silicon): budget only about 60–70% of that number for a model (the rest runs the operating system), so 16 GB means about 10–11 GB.","On a Windows PC with an NVIDIA graphics card: press the Windows key, type 'Task Manager', and press Enter.","In Task Manager: click the 'Performance' tab, click 'GPU', and read 'Dedicated GPU Memory' (for example 8.0 GB) — that VRAM number, not your system RAM, is your budget.","Write down one number: your memory budget in GB."],"commands":[],"check":"you have written down one number: your memory budget in GB."},{"title":"Match your memory budget to a model size","detail":"Now you compare the budget you just found against tested tiers to pick a model size that will fit, all assuming Q4 quantization.","do":["Compare your Step 2 budget against these tiers: about 8 GB fits 3B–8B models (for example Gemma 4 4B, Llama 3.x 8B, or Phi-4-mini).","About 16–24 GB fits 12B–32B models (for example Gemma 4 12B or a Qwen 3.5 9B).","About 40 GB or more can run a ~70B model at Q4; a 128 GB Mac or multi-GPU rig can run frontier-class models like Qwen 3.5 122B.","Pick one model name and size that fits under your budget with a couple GB to spare (at exactly 8 GB start with an 8B model; if it feels tight, drop to a 3B–4B model)."],"commands":[],"check":"you have picked one model name and size that comfortably fits under your budget with a couple GB to spare."},{"title":"Install Ollama, the free program that runs the model","detail":"Ollama is the free program that downloads and runs the model you chose. This step installs it.","do":["Open your web browser and go to ollama.com.","Click the big 'Download' button (it auto-detects Windows or macOS).","On macOS: double-click the .zip, drag the Ollama app into Applications, and open it once (approve any security prompt).","On Windows: double-click the .exe installer and click through Next/Install.","Look for a small llama icon in your menu bar or system tray, showing it is now running."],"commands":[],"check":"nothing dramatic happens on screen, but the program is running in the background and listening at http://localhost:11434."},{"title":"Open a terminal and confirm Ollama is alive","detail":"Now you open a terminal — a place to type commands — and confirm Ollama is installed by asking for its version.","do":["On Windows: press the Windows key, type 'PowerShell', and press Enter — a dark blue window opens.","On macOS: press Command+Space, type 'Terminal', and press Enter — a small window opens.","In that window, type the command below exactly and press Enter.","If you instead see 'command not found' or 'not recognized', redo Step 4 and, on Windows, close and reopen PowerShell so it notices the new program."],"commands":["ollama --version"],"check":"a line such as 'ollama version is 0.x.x' prints back."},{"title":"Do the fit-check math for YOUR chosen model, on paper","detail":"Before downloading, you plug your chosen model into the Step 1 rule to get a clear yes-or-no on whether it fits.","do":["Take your model's size in billions and multiply by 0.6 to estimate the weights (for example 8 times 0.6 = 4.8 GB).","Add about 1.5 GB of overhead (for example 4.8 + 1.5 = roughly 6.3 GB needed).","Compare that to your Step 2 budget — 6.3 GB needed under an 8 GB budget fits with about 1.7 GB to spare.","Check the counter-example: a 14B model needs 14 times 0.6 = 8.4 GB plus overhead (over 9 GB), which is bigger than an 8 GB budget, so skip it or choose a smaller / more-compressed version."],"commands":[],"check":"you have a clear yes/no — the needed memory sits comfortably under your budget."},{"title":"Download and run the model — and confirm it loaded","detail":"Now you download and start your model. The first run pulls the multi-GB file, then drops you into a chat so you can confirm it works.","do":["In the same terminal, type the command below (swap in the model you decided on; the example uses Llama 3.1 8B) and press Enter.","Wait for the download bar to finish — this is the multi-GB part (Ollama pulls a memory-efficient Q4 version by default).","At the '>>>' prompt, type a simple question like 'Say hello in one sentence.' and press Enter.","Type /bye and press Enter to leave the chat."],"commands":["ollama run llama3.1:8b"],"check":"the model replies in a second or two and stays responsive (a slow first answer is just the one-time cost of loading it into memory)."},{"title":"Watch memory while it runs to prove your math was right","detail":"While the model answers, you watch your memory usage to confirm it landed near your estimate — proof your math was right.","do":["Ask the model a question so it is actively working.","On Windows (NVIDIA): reopen Task Manager, go to the Performance tab, click GPU, and watch 'Dedicated GPU Memory' climb toward your Step 6 estimate.","On a Mac: open Activity Monitor (Command+Space, type 'Activity Monitor'), click the 'Memory' tab, and watch that memory pressure stays green, not red.","If memory pins to the top and the answer crawls one word at a time, stop it with /bye and pull a smaller size or a more-compressed tag."],"commands":[],"check":"usage lands near your estimate and the machine stays smooth."},{"title":"If it was tight, pick a smaller or more-compressed version","detail":"If the model felt tight, this step shows the two easy levers — fewer parameters or heavier compression — with a smaller model to try.","do":["Understand the quantization levels: Q8 (biggest, closest to full quality), Q5, Q4 (the balanced default), and Q3/Q2 (smallest, noticeably lower quality).","Lever 1: drop to fewer parameters (for example an 8B down to a 3B–4B model).","Lever 2: ask Ollama for a smaller quantization tag, or search ollama.com/library for the exact tags a model offers.","Run the first command below to pull a smaller model, then the second command to chat with it."],"commands":["ollama pull gemma2:2b","ollama run gemma2:2b"],"check":"the smaller pull fits under your budget from Step 8 and answers without freezing."}],"resources":[{"label":"Ollama - download and install (auto-detects your OS)","url":"https://ollama.com/download"},{"label":"Ollama model library - browse models, sizes, and quantization tags","url":"https://ollama.com/library"},{"label":"LM Studio - a friendly graphical app that shows a green \"will fit\" / red \"too big\" badge next to each model for your hardware (local API at http://localhost:1234)","url":"https://lmstudio.ai"},{"label":"Hugging Face - model cards, licenses, and GGUF quantized files (check the license before use)","url":"https://huggingface.co"},{"label":"YouTube search phrase: \"Ollama quantization VRAM which model fits my GPU beginner\"","url":""},{"label":"YouTube search phrase: \"LM Studio choose model for your hardware GGUF Q4 explained\"","url":""}],"cloudTieIn":"If you already use Microsoft Copilot, Anthropic Claude, OpenAI ChatGPT, or Google Gemini, those run on massive datacenter GPUs, so you never think about VRAM - the trade is that your text leaves your machine and you pay per message or per subscription. This local setup is the opposite: you own the hardware limit (which is exactly why this fit-check math matters), but your data never leaves the laptop and each use costs about $0. A practical rule for a college program: keep identifiable student records (FERPA) or health data (HIPAA) on a local model you fit with these steps, and reach for the frontier cloud tools for the hardest reasoning, the biggest documents, or when quality matters more than privacy. The workflow is portable too - a prompt you test locally in Ollama can be pasted straight into Claude or ChatGPT to compare, since local complements the cloud rather than replacing it. Be honest about the ceiling: a model small enough to fit an 8 GB laptop is genuinely weaker on the hardest tasks than a frontier cloud model, so always verify its answers, and remember that running locally does not by itself make you compliant - it removes the third-party sharing risk, but you still handle the data responsibly.","troubleshooting":[{"symptom":"The machine freezes, the fan roars, and answers come out one word every few seconds.","fix":"The model is too big for your memory budget and is \"spilling\" out of fast memory. Type /bye to stop it, then run a smaller model (e.g., ollama run gemma2:2b) or a lighter quantization tag. Re-do the Step 6 math with a smaller size until needed memory sits well under your budget."},{"symptom":"The model crashes or you see an \"out of memory\" / \"failed to allocate\" error the moment it starts.","fix":"Your GPU VRAM (Windows) or unified memory (Mac) cannot hold the model at all. Close other heavy apps (browsers with many tabs, video editors) to free memory, then choose a model at least one tier smaller. On an 8 GB machine, stay at 3B-8B; do not attempt 14B or larger."},{"symptom":"The terminal says \"ollama: command not found\" or \"'ollama' is not recognized.\"","fix":"Ollama is not installed or the terminal opened before it was installed. Reinstall from ollama.com, then fully close the terminal/PowerShell window and open a new one so it picks up the newly installed program, and try ollama --version again."},{"symptom":"An app can't reach the model and says \"connection refused\" at http://localhost:11434.","fix":"The Ollama background service isn't running. On Windows/Mac, open the Ollama app once from your Start menu or Applications folder so its tray/menu-bar icon appears, then retry. localhost:11434 only works while Ollama is actually running."},{"symptom":"Starting a model says the port or address is already in use.","fix":"Another copy of Ollama (or another tool on 11434) is already running - that's usually fine, just use it. If you truly need a clean start, quit Ollama from its tray/menu-bar icon and reopen it once, then run your model again."},{"symptom":"The very first answer takes 20-60 seconds, then later ones are fast.","fix":"This is normal: the first request loads the multi-GB model from disk into memory. It's a one-time cost per session. If EVERY answer stays that slow, the model is too big and is being re-loaded each turn - drop to a smaller size."},{"symptom":"The answers are noticeably dumber or more error-prone than you expected.","fix":"You may have pulled a very aggressive quantization (Q2/Q3) or too small a model. Step up one level: try a Q4 or Q5 tag, or move from a 3B to an 8B model if your budget allows. There is a real trade-off - smaller and more-compressed means weaker, so verify anything important."}],"tips":["Memorize the beginner shortcut: model billions x 0.6 (GB) at Q4, then add ~1-2 GB overhead. It gets you the right answer 90% of the time without a calculator.","Never plan to use 100% of your memory. Leave 20-30% headroom for the operating system, your browser, and the growing conversation - a model that just barely fits will choke as the chat gets longer.","If you prefer clicking over typing, install LM Studio (lmstudio.ai): it shows a green badge when a model fits your exact hardware and a red one when it doesn't, doing this lab's math for you automatically.","Q4 (specifically the Q4_K_M variant) is the sweet spot for most people - near-full quality at roughly half the memory. Only go to Q5/Q8 if you have memory to spare, and only drop to Q3/Q2 as a last resort to squeeze a model in.","On Apple Silicon, unified memory means the same pool serves the whole model, so a 16 GB Mac punches above a 16 GB Windows machine whose model must fit in a smaller separate VRAM pool - factor that in when comparing to a friend's setup."],"difficulty":"Intermediate — comfortable installing an app and copy-pasting terminal commands","time":"About 20–30 minutes"},{"id":"lab21","n":21,"cat":"O","title":"Local AI Troubleshooting & Error-Recovery Matrix","tagline":"Turn any \"it froze / it errored / it won't respond\" moment with your local AI into a calm, fix-it-yourself checklist so you never have to give up and delete everything.","whatItIs":"This lab is a diagnostic center for the four things that most often go wrong when you run an AI model on your own computer instead of in the cloud: the machine slows to a crawl, the model runs out of memory, the \"port\" it talks through is blocked by other software, or the conversation grows so long it crashes. You learn to recognize each symptom in plain language, then run a few exact commands to recover, all without reinstalling anything. Think of it as the \"have you tried turning it off and on again\" guide, but specific to local AI. It is meant to be kept open in a second window so you can look up whatever just happened.","whyUseIt":"Running AI locally (with a free tool like Ollama) keeps your data on your machine, which matters when you are handling student records under FERPA or health data under HIPAA, and it costs roughly $0 per use instead of a cloud subscription. But local tools talk to you through a terminal, and when a terminal hangs or spits out red text, non-technical people usually assume they broke something permanently and quit. Almost none of these problems are permanent: they are memory, ports, and settings, and each has a two-minute fix. Learning to recover on your own means you stay independent, keep your sensitive data local, and do not have to email IT (or paste private data into a cloud chatbot) every time something hiccups. Use this the moment anything feels stuck.","bestFor":"A complete beginner running a local model (via Ollama or LM Studio) on a normal laptop who hit an error, saw a wall of text, and wants a safe, step-by-step way to get unstuck without reinstalling or asking for help.","platforms":["Windows","macOS","Linux"],"prerequisites":["Ollama already installed and at least one model pulled (for example gemma or llama3.1) — if you have never done this, do the 'Install Ollama and run your first model' lab first.","Around 15 minutes and the willingness to type a few commands exactly as shown (copy/paste is fine and encouraged).","8 GB of RAM is the realistic floor; 16 GB+ is much more comfortable. RAM is the resource that runs out and causes most crashes in this lab.","No coding knowledge needed — you will only copy and paste commands, never write any.","Optional: LM Studio installed if you prefer a clickable app; its local address is http://localhost:1234 (Ollama's is http://localhost:11434), and this lab notes both.","A second browser tab or window kept open on this page so you can look up a symptom while the terminal is in front of you."],"steps":[{"title":"Open the terminal — the text window everything runs in","detail":"Local AI tools are driven from the terminal, a plain window where you type commands instead of clicking buttons. First you open one — this is where every fix in this lab gets typed.","do":["On Windows: click the Start button (bottom-left corner), type the word powershell, and click 'Windows PowerShell' in the results.","On a Mac: press Command+Spacebar to open Spotlight, type terminal, and press Enter.","On Linux: press Ctrl+Alt+T.","Wait for a window with a blinking cursor to open — you do not need to understand what is on screen, just keep this window open."],"commands":[],"check":"a window with a cursor is open, waiting for you to type."},{"title":"Confirm the AI service is even running (this rules out half your problems)","detail":"Ollama runs a small background service that models talk through; if it stopped, nothing responds and it can look like a crash. These commands ask it 'are you alive?'","do":["Type the first command below and press Enter to ask the service for its version.","Type the second command and press Enter to list your models.","If you see an error like 'command not found', Ollama is not installed on this computer — go do the install lab first.","If it hangs with no response for more than 20 seconds, the service is stuck, and the next steps fix that."],"commands":["ollama --version","ollama list"],"check":"a short line of text mentioning a version number (for example 'ollama version is 0.x.x') prints back."},{"title":"Spot an out-of-memory (OOM) error and understand what it means","detail":"Out-of-memory means the model you asked for is bigger than the free RAM your computer has right now — the single most common local-AI failure, and not a sign your computer is broken.","do":["Look for clue words in red or error text: 'out of memory', 'OOM', 'failed to allocate', 'not enough memory', or a model simply refusing to load.","Run the command below to see which models you have and their sizes.","Identify which models are large — a 7B or 8B needs roughly 5–6 GB free, a 12B needs more, and a 3B (like phi or a small gemma) needs far less."],"commands":["ollama list"],"check":"you can see the size next to each model name and identify which ones are large."},{"title":"Fix out-of-memory by switching to a smaller, lighter model","detail":"The fastest fix for out-of-memory is simply running a smaller model. This step downloads a lightweight one and chats with it.","do":["Choose a smaller model — on 8 GB of RAM, stay around 3B–8B (for example gemma:2b, phi, or llama3.2:3b).","Prefer a 'Q4' (4-bit) version if offered — quantization roughly halves the memory a model needs with only a small quality trade-off.","Run the first command below to download a small model (this takes a few minutes the first time; a progress bar fills to 100%).","Run the second command to chat with it.","Type /bye and press Enter to exit the chat when done."],"commands":["ollama pull gemma:2b","ollama run gemma:2b"],"check":"the model replies to 'hello' in the terminal."},{"title":"Free up memory the safe way: unload the model instead of rebooting","detail":"If your whole computer is lagging (fan roaring, mouse stuttering) because a model is still loaded, you can release that memory instantly and safely — no restart needed.","do":["Close any big programs you are not using (many browser tabs, Zoom, Photoshop) — each one competes for the same RAM.","Run the first command below to tell Ollama to unload the model from memory (replace gemma:2b with whatever you were running).","Run the second command to confirm nothing is still loaded in memory."],"commands":["ollama stop gemma:2b","ollama ps"],"check":"within a few seconds the fan quiets down and the machine feels responsive again."},{"title":"Restart the local backend service cleanly when it is truly stuck","detail":"If the service is frozen — commands hang, nothing responds — you restart just the AI service, not your whole computer. It loses nothing but the current in-memory chat.","do":["Find the Ollama icon in the system tray (Windows: bottom-right, near the clock; Mac: top-right menu bar).","Right-click or click it and choose 'Quit'.","Wait five seconds, then reopen Ollama from your Start menu or Applications folder.","Prefer the terminal? Run the first command to check status, then the second ('ollama serve') to restart the service in the foreground — leave that window open."],"commands":["ollama ps","ollama serve"],"check":"after restarting, 'ollama list' responds instantly again."},{"title":"Diagnose 'connection refused' — a port conflict with other software","detail":"A 'port' is a numbered door programs use to talk to each other; Ollama listens on door 11434. 'Connection refused' usually means another program grabbed that door, or the service is not running.","do":["First re-check the service is up (Step 2).","On Windows: run the netstat command below to see what is using port 11434.","On macOS/Linux: run the lsof command below instead.","If a different program shows up on 11434, that is your conflict.","Move Ollama to a free door: run the OLLAMA_HOST command for your system to set the address to 11500, then restart Ollama (Step 6).","Point any app that talks to Ollama at the new address, for example http://localhost:11500."],"commands":["# Windows PowerShell — see what is using Ollama's port:","netstat -ano | findstr 11434","# macOS / Linux — same idea:","lsof -i :11434","# Windows — move Ollama to a free port, then restart it (Step 6):","$env:OLLAMA_HOST=\"127.0.0.1:11500\"; ollama serve","# macOS / Linux equivalent:","OLLAMA_HOST=127.0.0.1:11500 ollama serve"],"check":"after setting a new port and restarting, your chat tool connects at the new address, http://localhost:11500."},{"title":"Prevent context-window crashes by scaling down how much the model remembers","detail":"The 'context window' is how much of your conversation the model holds at once; a very long chat or huge paste can overflow it and cause a slowdown or crash. Two fixes keep it stable.","do":["Instant fix: inside an Ollama chat, type /clear and press Enter to wipe the current conversation and start fresh (or close and reopen the chat for a long paste).","Preventive fix: run the /set command below to cap the context at a modest 2048 tokens — plenty for normal Q&A and much lighter on memory."],"commands":["/clear","/set parameter num_ctx 2048"],"check":"after /set parameter num_ctx 2048, long sessions stay stable and the model responds without lagging."},{"title":"Build your personal recovery habit so nothing feels scary next time","detail":"Finally, you turn all of this into a reflex you can run in under a minute whenever something breaks, checking the four buckets in order.","do":["Check 1 — is the service alive? Run 'ollama --version' and 'ollama ps'.","Check 2 — is it memory? Switch to a smaller/Q4 model and 'ollama stop' the big one.","Check 3 — is it a port? Check 11434, move to 11500, restart.","Check 4 — is it context? /clear and cap num_ctx.","Note down which model runs smoothly on YOUR machine — that becomes your safe default."],"commands":["ollama --version","ollama ps","ollama list"],"check":"you can look at any error, name which of the four buckets it falls into, and know the one command that fixes it, without reinstalling anything."}],"resources":[{"label":"Ollama — official site, downloads, and model library","url":"https://ollama.com"},{"label":"Ollama — GitHub repo, README, and troubleshooting/FAQ docs","url":"https://github.com/ollama/ollama"},{"label":"LM Studio — official site (the clickable alternative to Ollama; local API on port 1234)","url":"https://lmstudio.ai"},{"label":"Hugging Face — model cards and licenses for Gemma, Qwen, Llama, Phi (check what fits your RAM)","url":"https://huggingface.co"},{"label":"YouTube search phrase: 'Ollama out of memory fix beginner' — short walkthroughs of the exact OOM and restart steps","url":""},{"label":"YouTube search phrase: 'change Ollama port OLLAMA_HOST' — visual demo of resolving a port conflict","url":""}],"cloudTieIn":"The whole reason to fight through a local error instead of just opening Microsoft Copilot, Anthropic's Claude, ChatGPT, or Google Gemini is that those cloud tools send your text to someone else's servers — fine for brainstorming, risky for identifiable student or health data under FERPA/HIPAA. Local keeps that data on your machine at ~$0 per use, which is exactly why it is worth learning to recover from a hang rather than falling back to the cloud with sensitive material. The practical playbook: use frontier cloud tools for your hardest, non-sensitive reasoning where the biggest models genuinely win, and use your local model for anything private or high-volume — and when the local model stumbles on a truly hard task, that is a signal to move that one non-sensitive task to Claude or Copilot, not to abandon local entirely. Local complements the cloud; it does not replace it. One more honesty check: local running successfully is not the same as being compliant — local reduces exposure, but you still verify outputs and follow your institution's data rules.","troubleshooting":[{"symptom":"Red text says 'out of memory', 'OOM', or 'failed to allocate', or the model just won't load.","fix":"You asked for a model bigger than your free RAM. Close other big apps, run 'ollama stop <model>' to unload anything loaded, then switch to a smaller or Q4 model (for example 'ollama run gemma:2b' or a 3B model). On 8 GB stay at 3B–8B."},{"symptom":"'Error: connection refused' or a chat app can't reach the model.","fix":"The service is down or a port is blocked. Run 'ollama --version' to confirm it's installed, restart the service (quit Ollama from the tray and reopen, or run 'ollama serve'). If the port is taken, check with 'netstat -ano | findstr 11434' (Windows) or 'lsof -i :11434' (Mac/Linux) and move Ollama to a free port like 11500."},{"symptom":"'address already in use' when starting Ollama, or another AI tool is running.","fix":"Something else grabbed port 11434 (often a second copy of Ollama, or LM Studio on 1234). Set a new port with OLLAMA_HOST=127.0.0.1:11500 and restart, then point your apps at http://localhost:11500. Do not force-kill the other program unless you know what it is."},{"symptom":"Whole computer lags, fan roars, mouse stutters while a model is loaded.","fix":"A model is still occupying RAM. Run 'ollama stop <model>' to unload it instantly, close spare browser tabs and heavy apps, and next time cap the context with '/set parameter num_ctx 2048'. You do NOT need to reboot the computer."},{"symptom":"The model crashes or slows down during a very long chat or after pasting a huge document.","fix":"You overflowed the context window. Type '/clear' to reset the conversation, or close and reopen the chat. Prevent it by capping context: '/set parameter num_ctx 2048'. A smaller context uses less memory and is more stable."},{"symptom":"First response after starting a model takes a very long time, then later replies are fast.","fix":"This is normal, not an error — the model is loading from disk into memory the first time (the 'cold start'). Wait it out once; subsequent replies come from memory and are much faster. If cold starts are always painfully slow, your model is too big for your RAM, so drop to a smaller/Q4 model."},{"symptom":"'command not found' or 'ollama is not recognized' when you type a command.","fix":"Ollama isn't installed or isn't on this machine's path. Reinstall from ollama.com, then fully close and reopen the terminal window so it picks up the new program. Do the install lab first if you've never set it up."}],"tips":["Keep a sticky note (physical or digital) with the one model name that runs smoothly on YOUR laptop — that becomes your safe default, so recovery is just 'switch back to the one I know works'.","Q4 (4-bit quantization) is almost always the right download choice on a laptop: it roughly halves memory use for a small, usually unnoticeable quality drop. Prefer the Q4 tag when a model offers one.","Run 'ollama ps' anytime to see what is currently loaded in memory and eating RAM — it's the local-AI equivalent of Task Manager and instantly tells you what to 'ollama stop'.","Unloading a model ('ollama stop') and restarting the service ('ollama serve') never delete your models or files — the worst you lose is the current in-memory chat. Restarting is safe, so try it early.","Smaller context (num_ctx) is a two-for-one win: it prevents context-window crashes AND lowers memory pressure, so setting num_ctx 2048 quietly fixes a lot of 'random' slowdowns."],"difficulty":"Intermediate — comfortable typing commands in a terminal; used when your local AI misbehaves","time":"About 15 minutes to work through, or keep it open and dip in as needed"},{"id":"lab22","n":22,"cat":"S","title":"Google Colab: Run Real AI in Your Browser with a Free GPU","tagline":"Open a free, no-install coding notebook in the cloud, switch on a free cloud GPU (typically an Nvidia T4), install an AI library, and run a real machine-learning model in a few lines — then save it to your Google Drive, all without ever leaving your browser.","whatItIs":"Google Colab (short for \"Colaboratory\") is a free website from Google that gives you a Jupyter notebook — an interactive page where you write and run small blocks of Python code called \"cells\" and see the results right underneath each one. The twist is that none of it runs on your own computer: Google lends you one of its cloud machines, and on the free tier you can switch on a GPU — a graphics chip that makes AI models run far faster. As of 2026 the free GPU is typically an Nvidia T4, though Google notes the available hardware can vary over time and is not guaranteed. There is nothing to download and nothing to configure; if you have a Google account, you can open a blank notebook, type or paste code, press a button, and watch a genuine AI model run. This lab walks you, click by click, from a blank screen to running an actual model and saving your work.","whyUseIt":"Setting up AI on your own laptop can mean wrestling with Python versions, drivers, and gigabytes of downloads before you ever see a result — and many laptops do not have the powerful graphics card that modern models want. Colab erases all of that: it is the single fastest way for a non-technical person to go from curious to actually running AI, because Google has pre-installed the hard parts and lends you capable hardware for free. It is the friendliest possible sandbox to experiment, follow a tutorial, or try a model you read about, without spending a cent, installing anything, or risking your own machine. When something breaks, you just close the tab and start fresh.","bestFor":"A complete beginner who wants to try real AI code without installing anything, has a Google account, and would rather borrow Google's free cloud GPU than fight with setup on their own laptop. Perfect for following along with an AI tutorial or running a model you read about.","platforms":["Any modern web browser — Google Chrome or Microsoft Edge recommended","Works on Windows, macOS, Chromebook, or Linux, because all the computing happens on Google's servers rather than your device"],"prerequisites":["A free Google account — the same login you use for Gmail or Google Drive. If you have Gmail, you already have one; if not, creating a Google account is free.","A reliable internet connection. Because the actual work runs in Google's cloud, your own computer can be modest — even a basic Chromebook is fine.","No Python or coding experience needed. You will only copy and paste the code shown, never write any from scratch.","About 20-30 minutes and, ideally, Google Chrome or Microsoft Edge, where Colab runs most smoothly.","No payment method and no credit card — the free tier of Colab requires neither."],"steps":[{"title":"Open Google Colab and sign in","detail":"First you go to the Colab website and sign in with your Google account. This is the whole 'installation' — there isn't one.","do":["In your browser's address bar, type colab.research.google.com and press Enter (the shorter address colab.google redirects to the same place).","If you are not already signed in, click the blue 'Sign in' button in the top-right corner.","Enter your Google email and password (the same one you use for Gmail), just as you would to check your email.","A window titled 'Open notebook' may pop up listing example and recent notebooks. If it does, click 'Cancel' or the X to close it for now."],"commands":[],"check":"you'll know it worked when you see the Colab page with your Google account picture in the top-right corner instead of a 'Sign in' button."},{"title":"Create a new, blank notebook and give it a name","detail":"A 'notebook' is your working document — one page that holds your code, its results, and your notes. You make a fresh empty one now.","do":["Click the 'File' menu in the top-left of the screen.","Choose 'New notebook' from the menu that drops down. A blank notebook opens in a new tab, with one empty grey box (a 'cell') in the middle.","Look at the top-left, where it says 'Untitled0.ipynb' — that is the file's name. Click directly on that text.","Type a friendlier name, for example 'My First AI Notebook', and press Enter. (The '.ipynb' ending is just the file type for notebooks; you can leave it or ignore it.)"],"commands":[],"check":"you'll know it worked when the tab shows your chosen name at the top-left and a single empty grey cell sits in the middle of the page, waiting for input."},{"title":"Run your very first cell","detail":"A 'cell' is a box you type code into; pressing its play button runs that code on Google's cloud machine and prints the answer right below. Let's prove it works with simple math.","do":["Click inside the empty grey cell so a cursor appears.","Type the line shown in the commands below (or copy and paste it).","Press the round 'Play' button that appears at the left edge of the cell (a triangle inside a circle). You can also just press Shift and Enter together, which runs the cell and is the fastest way.","The first run takes a few seconds while Google quietly assigns you a cloud machine — this one-time wait is called 'connecting to a runtime' and is normal.","Watch for the answer to appear in small text directly beneath the cell."],"commands":["print(2 + 2)"],"check":"you'll know it worked when the number 4 appears just below the cell, and a green checkmark shows to the left of it."},{"title":"Add more cells and mix code with plain-English notes","detail":"Real notebooks are built from many cells. Colab has two kinds: 'Code' cells that run Python, and 'Text' cells for human notes (headings, explanations). You add both here.","do":["Hover your mouse just below your first cell, or look at the top toolbar, to find two buttons: '+ Code' and '+ Text'.","Click '+ Code' to add a new code cell. Type the first command below into it and press Shift+Enter to run it.","Click '+ Text' to add a note cell. Type a sentence like 'This is my AI experiment' — it appears as normal formatted writing, not code, and does not need to be 'run'.","Tip: to run everything on the page top to bottom in order, use the 'Runtime' menu at the top and choose 'Run all'."],"commands":["print('Hello from the cloud!')"],"check":"you'll know it worked when your greeting prints under the code cell, and your typed note shows up as ordinary text (not grey code) in the text cell."},{"title":"Turn on the free GPU","detail":"A GPU (Graphics Processing Unit) is a chip built to do the heavy math AI models need, many times faster than a normal processor. Colab lends you a free GPU — as of 2026 this is typically an Nvidia T4 — but you have to switch it on. (Google notes the exact hardware can vary over time and is not guaranteed, so on a busy day you may be offered a different chip or asked to wait.)","do":["Click the 'Runtime' menu at the top of the page ('runtime' is Colab's word for the cloud machine currently running your code).","Choose 'Change runtime type' from the menu.","A small window opens with a section titled 'Hardware accelerator'. Click the circle next to 'T4 GPU'.","Click the blue 'Save' button.","Colab will connect you to a machine that has the GPU — you may briefly see 'Connecting' in the top-right near the 'Connect' button. Wait until it settles."],"commands":[],"check":"you'll know it worked when the window closes and, back in the notebook, the top-right shows a green checkmark next to a resource meter (RAM/Disk) instead of the plain 'Connect' button."},{"title":"Confirm the GPU is really switched on","detail":"Before relying on the GPU, it's reassuring to see it for yourself. This one command asks the cloud machine to describe its graphics card.","do":["Add a new code cell with the '+ Code' button.","Type or paste the command below. The exclamation mark '!' at the front is important — it tells the notebook 'run this as a system command, not as Python.'","Press Shift+Enter to run it.","Read the table that prints out — you are looking for the name of your GPU, usually 'Tesla T4' (the official name of the T4 chip). If you were assigned a different GPU, you'll simply see its name instead."],"commands":["!nvidia-smi"],"check":"you'll know it worked when a table prints showing a GPU name (usually 'Tesla T4', with a memory figure around 15360 MiB). If you instead see an error about no GPU, revisit Step 5 and make sure 'T4 GPU' was selected and saved."},{"title":"Install a Python library with pip","detail":"A 'library' is a ready-made bundle of code someone else wrote so you don't have to. 'pip' is the tool that fetches and installs them. Colab pre-installs many AI libraries, but you'll often want to add or upgrade one.","do":["Add a new code cell.","Paste the command below. Again the '!' means 'run as a system command', 'pip install' means 'go get this library', '-q' just means 'quietly, with less clutter', and '--upgrade' means 'give me the newest version'.","Press Shift+Enter and wait — you'll see progress text scroll by for a few seconds to a minute as Google downloads it onto your cloud machine.","Note: 'transformers' (used in the next step) usually comes pre-installed on Colab; this step both proves how installing works and makes sure you have the latest version."],"commands":["!pip install -q --upgrade transformers"],"check":"you'll know it worked when the scrolling stops and you see a green checkmark by the cell with no red error text (a line about 'Successfully installed' or simply a clean finish is what you want)."},{"title":"Run a real AI model in just a few lines","detail":"Now the payoff: you run a genuine, pre-trained machine-learning model that reads a sentence and judges whether its tone is positive or negative. The 'pipeline' tool downloads a default model and runs it for you.","do":["Add a new code cell.","Paste all three lines below into that one cell.","Press Shift+Enter. The first time, it will download a small model file (a progress bar fills up — this is normal and takes a moment). You may also see an informational note that no model was specified and a default was chosen; that is expected, not an error.","Read the result printed below: it will show a label of 'POSITIVE' or 'NEGATIVE' and a confidence score between 0 and 1.","Experiment: change the sentence inside the quotation marks to your own words and run the cell again to see the model re-judge it.","(Optional variation: instead of running a model, you could call a web service's API here using Python's 'requests' library — the same notebook works for that too.)"],"commands":["from transformers import pipeline","classifier = pipeline('sentiment-analysis')","print(classifier('I am really enjoying my first day with Google Colab!'))"],"check":"you'll know it worked when a result like [{'label': 'POSITIVE', 'score': 0.99...}] prints beneath the cell. You just ran a real AI model on a free cloud GPU."},{"title":"Save your notebook to Google Drive","detail":"Colab saves your notebook into a 'Colab Notebooks' folder in your Google Drive, but it's worth saving on purpose and knowing where it lives so you can find it again.","do":["Open the 'File' menu and click 'Save' (or just press Ctrl+S on Windows, or Command+S on a Mac). A brief 'Saving...' then 'All changes saved' message appears near the top.","Your notebook now lives in Google Drive under a folder named 'Colab Notebooks' — open drive.google.com anytime to find it there.","Optional — save a data FILE (not just the notebook) to Drive: add a code cell, paste the two lines below, and run them. A pop-up will ask permission to connect your Drive; click through it and choose the SAME Google account you signed in with, then approve the requested access.","After it connects, your Drive is reachable inside the notebook at the folder path /content/drive/MyDrive/, so any file you write there is saved to your real Drive."],"commands":["from google.colab import drive","drive.mount('/content/drive')"],"check":"you'll know it worked when you see 'All changes saved' for the notebook, and (if you mounted Drive) the message 'Mounted at /content/drive' prints in the cell."},{"title":"Finish cleanly and stay inside the free limits","detail":"The free tier is generous but not unlimited: on the free version of Colab a notebook can run for at most about 12 hours (depending on availability and usage), and free GPUs are shared, so it's polite (and practical) to release the machine when you're done.","do":["When you've finished experimenting, open the 'Runtime' menu and choose 'Disconnect and delete runtime', then confirm. This hands the cloud machine (and its GPU) back to Google.","Your notebook and its saved results stay safe in Google Drive — disconnecting only frees the temporary machine, it does not delete your work.","Turn the GPU back on (Step 5) and reconnect whenever you return; any files you saved to your own Drive will still be there, but files left only in the temporary /content area are wiped when the machine is released.","To keep your own editable copy of any shared or example notebook, use File > 'Save a copy in Drive'."],"commands":[],"check":"you'll know it worked when the top-right resource meter returns to a plain 'Connect' button, meaning the cloud machine has been released and you're no longer using GPU time."}],"resources":[{"label":"Google Colab — open it here (official site)","url":"https://colab.research.google.com/"},{"label":"Colab official FAQ — free-tier limits, GPUs, and where notebooks are saved","url":"https://research.google.com/colaboratory/faq.html"},{"label":"Welcome to Colab — the official interactive intro notebook","url":"https://colab.research.google.com/notebooks/intro.ipynb"},{"label":"Using GPUs in Colab — official notebook (Runtime > Change runtime type, nvidia-smi)","url":"https://colab.research.google.com/notebooks/gpu.ipynb"},{"label":"External data: Drive, Sheets & Cloud Storage — official notebook for mounting Google Drive","url":"https://colab.research.google.com/notebooks/io.ipynb"},{"label":"Hugging Face Transformers — official docs for the pipeline() tool used in this lab","url":"https://huggingface.co/docs/transformers/index"}],"cloudTieIn":"Colab is the cloud on-ramp to everything else on this site: it is the quickest way to run real AI code with zero setup, which makes it perfect for learning and for tutorials where you just want to see a model work. The trade-off is exactly the one the local labs (like installing Ollama on your own machine) are built around — in Colab your code and any data you paste run on Google's servers, not privately on your computer, so it is great for public or practice data but not the right home for identifiable student or health records. A sensible path is to learn and prototype in Colab's free cloud, then, once you want privacy or to run things offline at roughly $0 per use, graduate to the local-model labs. Cloud and local are partners: Colab lowers the barrier to trying AI, and local keeps sensitive work on your own machine.","troubleshooting":[{"symptom":"A message says 'Cannot connect to GPU backend' or 'You cannot currently connect to a GPU due to usage limits'.","fix":"Free GPUs are shared and resources aren't guaranteed, so they're sometimes fully booked, or you've used a lot of GPU time recently. Either wait a while and try again, or keep working without the GPU for now: go to Runtime > Change runtime type, pick 'CPU', and Save — your code still runs, just slower. Limits reset over time."},{"symptom":"The notebook shows 'Runtime disconnected' or your variables suddenly seem 'forgotten'.","fix":"Colab disconnects idle sessions and caps a free session at about 12 hours. Click 'Reconnect' in the top-right, then re-run your cells from the top (Runtime > 'Run all' is the easy way). Nothing is lost permanently — the notebook itself is saved in Drive."},{"symptom":"Running a cell gives a red 'NameError: name ... is not defined'.","fix":"You ran cells out of order, so the code that defines something hadn't run yet. Cells depend on the ones above them. Fix it by running everything top to bottom: Runtime menu > 'Run all'."},{"symptom":"You installed a library with !pip but importing it still fails with 'ModuleNotFoundError'.","fix":"Occasionally a freshly installed library needs the session restarted to be picked up. Go to Runtime > 'Restart session', then run your install cell and your import cell again from the top."},{"symptom":"The Drive-mount pop-up won't finish, or you can't see your files at /content/drive.","fix":"Make sure you click through the permission pop-up and choose the SAME Google account you signed into Colab with, then approve access. If it's stuck, re-run the drive.mount cell. Files you want kept must be written under /content/drive/MyDrive/, not just /content (which is temporary)."}],"tips":["The single most useful shortcut is Shift+Enter: it runs the current cell and jumps to the next one, so you can walk down a notebook quickly without touching the mouse.","Turn the GPU on only when you actually need it (running models). For plain text or simple code, a CPU runtime is fine and helps you stay within the free GPU limits for when you need them.","Colab auto-saves, but pressing Ctrl+S (Windows) or Command+S (Mac) every so often guarantees your latest work is safely in Google Drive.","Explore the built-in examples: File > 'Open notebook' has an 'Examples' tab full of ready-to-run official notebooks — a great, safe way to see what's possible.","When you're done for the day, use Runtime > 'Disconnect and delete runtime' to hand the machine back. It frees resources and is good etiquette on a shared free service.","If a notebook gets into a weird state, the nuclear-but-safe reset is Runtime > 'Restart session' — it gives you a clean machine while keeping your code cells intact."],"difficulty":"Beginner — no coding experience needed; you only copy and paste, and everything runs in your browser with nothing to install","time":"About 20-30 minutes for a first run-through, less once you know the buttons"},{"id":"lab23","n":23,"cat":"S","title":"Model Garden on Google Cloud — Explore and Deploy AI Models","tagline":"Open Google Cloud's model catalog in your browser, chat with Gemini for free, then one-click-deploy an open model like Gemma to your own private endpoint — and safely shut it down so it never surprises you with a bill.","whatItIs":"Model Garden is a catalog inside Google Cloud where you can discover, test, tune, and deploy hundreds of AI models from one page — Google's own Gemini and Gemma, Meta's Llama, and many partner and open-source models (over 200 in total). Think of it as an app store for AI models that live on Google's computers instead of your own: you browse cards, click a model to read about it, try it in a built-in prompt box, and — for open models — press one button to spin up a private copy that only you can use. (Naming heads-up: in spring 2026 Google renamed the wider \"Vertex AI\" platform to \"Gemini Enterprise Agent Platform,\" and renamed its prompt studio from \"Vertex AI Studio\" to \"Agent Studio.\" Model Garden kept its name and now lives under the \"Models\" area of that platform. The name \"Vertex AI\" still appears in the underlying API — aiplatform.googleapis.com — and in older links and docs, which all still work, so don't be thrown when you see both.)","whyUseIt":"It is the fastest way to compare and try many top models side by side without installing anything, and to see how a \"real\" cloud AI platform works — the same skills transfer to your local labs and to any team that runs AI in production. Testing Gemini in the built-in panel costs only pennies (covered by your free trial credit) because you are just borrowing Google's shared model. Be honest with yourself about the trade-off, though: the moment you *deploy* an open model to an endpoint, Google reserves a powerful graphics chip (GPU) for you and bills you by the hour for as long as it is running — even when you are not using it — so this lab treats \"shut it down when done\" as a required step, not an afterthought.","bestFor":"A non-technical beginner who wants to see the cloud counterpart to the local labs: browse a huge model catalog, chat with Gemini in a browser, and experience a one-click model deployment once — cheaply and safely — using free trial credits.","platforms":["Any modern web browser (Chrome or Edge recommended)"],"prerequisites":["A Google account (a personal Gmail address is fine, or a Google Workspace account from your school/employer).","A credit or debit card. Google's free trial requires one to confirm you are a real person — Google places a small temporary authorization hold (usually $0–$1, no funds withdrawn), does NOT charge you when the trial ends, and the account will not convert to paid billing unless you explicitly choose to upgrade.","The free trial itself: $300 in credit valid for 90 days, available only to people who have never been a paying user of Google Cloud, Firebase, or Google Maps Platform and have never signed up for the trial before. If you have used it already, you can still follow along on a paid account, but watch costs carefully.","About 30–45 minutes and a willingness to read one or two on-screen confirmation dialogs before clicking.","No coding experience required. A few optional copy-and-paste commands are provided for the curious, but every task can be done by clicking."],"steps":[{"title":"Create or sign in to a Google Cloud project","detail":"Everything in Google Cloud lives inside a 'project' — a labeled container for your work and its bill. You need one before you can open Model Garden. New here? Start the free trial, which creates your first project for you.","do":["Open a new browser tab and go to https://console.cloud.google.com — this is the Google Cloud console, the control panel for everything Google Cloud.","Sign in with your Google account if asked.","If this is your first time, a banner or button offers the free trial (often labeled 'Activate' or 'Start free'). Click it, choose your country, agree to the Terms of Service by ticking the box, and click 'Continue'.","Enter your details and a credit/debit card when prompted. This is for identity verification only — Google places a small temporary hold (about $0–$1) but does not charge you when the trial ends unless you deliberately upgrade to a paid account. Finish the sign-up.","Look at the very top of the page for a project picker (it shows the current project name next to 'Google Cloud'). If no project exists, click it, then 'New Project', give it a friendly name like 'model-garden-lab', and click 'Create'. Wait a few seconds, then click the picker again and select your new project so it is the active one."],"commands":[],"check":"the bar at the top of the console shows your project name (e.g. 'model-garden-lab'), and you can see the main console dashboard rather than a sign-in or billing prompt."},{"title":"Turn on the Vertex AI / Agent Platform service (enable the API)","detail":"An 'API' is just the doorway that lets you use a Google Cloud service. Model Garden runs on the service still named 'aiplatform' under the hood (branded 'Vertex AI', now part of Gemini Enterprise Agent Platform), so you flip that service on once. The console usually offers to do it for you the first time you open Model Garden, but turning it on deliberately avoids surprises.","do":["In the search bar at the very top of the console, type: Vertex AI API","In the drop-down results, under 'Products & pages' or 'Marketplace', click the entry for the Vertex AI API (depending on your account it may be labeled 'Vertex AI API' or 'Gemini Enterprise Agent Platform API' — both point to the same aiplatform.googleapis.com service).","On the page that opens, click the blue 'Enable' button. If it already says 'Manage' or 'API Enabled', it is on already — nothing to do.","Wait a few seconds while it turns on. If a box titled 'Enable all recommended APIs' appears when you later open Model Garden, click 'Enable' there too — it switches on the small set of related services Model Garden needs."],"commands":["gcloud services enable aiplatform.googleapis.com"],"check":"the API page shows 'API Enabled' with a green check (or a 'Manage' button), instead of a blue 'Enable' button."},{"title":"Open Model Garden","detail":"Now open the catalog itself. Model Garden is the front door to every model on the platform.","do":["Go straight to https://console.cloud.google.com/vertex-ai/model-garden in your browser — this opens Model Garden for your active project (the link still works and now displays under the 'Agent Platform' branding).","Alternatively, click the three-line menu (the 'hamburger' icon, ☰) in the top-left corner, find 'Gemini Enterprise Agent Platform' (older or cached menus may still read 'Vertex AI'), and click 'Model Garden' under its 'Models' section. If you cannot spot it, type 'Model Garden' into the top search bar and click the result — the most reliable route.","Give the page a moment to load. You will see a grid of model 'cards', each a small tile with a model's name, its provider's logo, and a short description.","If a pop-up asks you to enable APIs or confirm a region, accept it — this is the same step 2 confirmation, now in context."],"commands":[],"check":"you see a page titled 'Model Garden' with a grid of model cards — including familiar names like Gemini, Gemma, and Llama."},{"title":"Browse and filter the catalog","detail":"Hundreds of models is a lot. The filters on the left let you narrow the grid to exactly what you want, so you can find, say, the open models you are allowed to deploy yourself.","do":["Look at the filter panel down the left side of the Model Garden page. It groups models by category.","Click a checkbox under 'Tasks' to filter by what a model does — for example 'Generation' (writing text) or 'Chat'.","Click under 'Model collections' to pick who manages the model — Google's own models, or partner/open models.","Click under 'Providers' to filter by maker (Google, Meta, Anthropic, and others).","Look under 'Features' and tick the option for open models you can self-host and, if shown, a 'one-click deployment' filter — this narrows the grid to models you can deploy yourself in one step, which is what you will do later.","Use the search box at the top of the grid to jump straight to a model: type gemma and press Enter to see the Gemma family."],"commands":[],"check":"the grid of cards shrinks as you tick filters, and typing 'gemma' shows only Gemma model cards."},{"title":"Test Gemini in the built-in prompt box (cheap, no deployment)","detail":"Before deploying anything, get a feel for chatting with a model right on its card. Gemini is Google's flagship 'managed' model — you use Google's shared copy and pay a tiny per-use fee (fractions of a cent, covered by your trial credit). There is nothing to deploy and no per-hour GPU charge here, which makes this the safest way to experiment.","do":["In the Model Garden search box, type Gemini and press Enter, then click a Gemini model card — pick a 'Flash' model (for example 'Gemini 2.5 Flash', or a newer Flash if one is listed), since 'Flash' models are the fast, low-cost ones.","On the model card, find the 'Try it' / prompt panel. Click into the text box and type a prompt, for example: Explain what a GPU is to a complete beginner in 3 sentences.","Optionally adjust the sliders — 'Temperature' controls creativity (lower = more focused, higher = more varied), and the output-token setting caps how long the answer can be. A 'token' is a chunk of text, roughly three-quarters of a word.","Click 'Submit' (or the send arrow) and read the model's reply appear in the panel.","For a fuller workspace, click 'Open in Agent Studio' (this was called 'Vertex AI Studio' before the 2026 rename; a cached account may still show the old label). This opens a larger prompt designer where you can save prompts and compare settings — the same underlying Gemini model."],"commands":[],"check":"you typed a prompt and Gemini wrote back an answer inside the prompt panel — no deployment, no waiting, just an instant reply."},{"title":"Choose an open model (Gemma) and accept its license","detail":"Now the main event: deploying your own private copy of an open model. 'Open' models like Gemma can be run on hardware you control — here, a slice of Google's cloud. First you open the card and agree to the model's license, exactly like accepting terms before a download.","do":["Back in Model Garden, search for gemma and click a small, deploy-friendly Gemma card — for a first, low-cost test pick the smallest size available (for example 'Gemma 3 1B' — the '1B' means one billion parameters, the smallest and cheapest to run).","Read the model card: it describes what the model is good at, its size, and its license terms.","If a license or terms-of-use box appears (Gemma requires you to accept one — you may need to click 'Enable' or 'Agree and continue' first), read it, tick the agreement box, and confirm. This is a normal, free step — you are agreeing to the model's usage terms, not paying anything yet.","Locate the 'Deploy' button near the top of the card. Do not click it yet — the next step walks through the settings pane it opens."],"commands":[],"check":"you are on a specific Gemma model card, any license box has been accepted, and you can see an active 'Deploy' button."},{"title":"Deploy Gemma to an endpoint","detail":"An 'endpoint' is a private web address that hosts your model so programs (and you) can send it prompts. Deploying attaches a real GPU to your model. This is the one step that starts costing real money per hour, so pick the smallest options and remember step 9.","do":["Click the 'Deploy' button on the Gemma card. A 'Deploy model' pane slides in from the right.","Leave the auto-filled model / resource name as-is, or give it a friendly name. Do the same for the endpoint name — a simple label like gemma-test-endpoint is fine.","Choose a 'Region' (also called 'Location') — this is which Google data center hosts your model. Pick one close to you that is offered in the list, such as 'us-central1'. Some regions have more GPUs available than others.","Under 'Machine type' / 'Machine spec', accept the recommended default. For a small model this is the smallest GPU option — the cheapest choice. Do not upgrade to a bigger machine for this test.","Review any cost note shown in the pane, then click the blue 'Deploy' button at the bottom.","Now wait. Deployment typically takes 10–20 minutes while Google reserves the GPU and loads the model. You can watch progress under the 'Online prediction' → 'Endpoints' area of the left menu (type 'Endpoints' in the top search bar if you can't find it); a spinner means it is still coming up."],"commands":[],"check":"after 10–20 minutes, your endpoint appears in the Endpoints list with a green check and status 'Deployed' (no longer 'Deploying' or a spinner)."},{"title":"Send a test prompt to your deployed endpoint","detail":"Your private Gemma is now live. Unlike managed Gemini, a self-deployed open model is usually called through its API rather than a chat box, but the console hands you a ready-made 'Sample request' you can copy — so you do not have to write anything from scratch.","do":["Open your endpoint: use the top search bar for 'Endpoints' (or the left menu → 'Online prediction' → 'Endpoints'), then click your gemma-test-endpoint.","Look for a 'Sample request' section or a test/prediction panel on the endpoint page. It shows copy-and-paste code (curl or Python) already filled in with your project and endpoint IDs.","The simplest path: click the copy icon on the provided sample, so you have the exact, correct request for your model.","If you want to run it yourself, open Cloud Shell (the '>_' terminal icon in the top-right of the console, which needs no setup), paste the copied command, and press Enter. The command below is only a representative shape — use the console's version, because the exact JSON differs per model (a Gemma served this way often uses a chat-style body rather than a plain 'prompt' field).","Read the JSON response that comes back: buried in it is the model's generated text answering your prompt."],"commands":["# Representative shape only — copy the EXACT 'Sample request' the console shows you.\nPROJECT_ID=\"your-project-id\"\nENDPOINT_ID=\"your-endpoint-id\"\nREGION=\"us-central1\"\n\ncurl -X POST \\\n  -H \"Authorization: Bearer $(gcloud auth print-access-token)\" \\\n  -H \"Content-Type: application/json\" \\\n  \"https://${REGION}-aiplatform.googleapis.com/v1/projects/${PROJECT_ID}/locations/${REGION}/endpoints/${ENDPOINT_ID}:predict\" \\\n  -d '{\"instances\":[{\"prompt\":\"Write one encouraging sentence for a new AI student.\",\"max_tokens\":128,\"temperature\":0.7}]}'"],"check":"the terminal (or the console's test panel) returns a JSON block containing the model's generated sentence — proof your own private Gemma answered you."},{"title":"Shut it down: undeploy the model and delete the endpoint","detail":"This is the most important step in the whole lab. A deployed endpoint keeps billing you by the hour for its reserved GPU until you take it down — even overnight, even when idle. Do this the moment you finish experimenting.","do":["Open the Endpoints list (top search bar → 'Endpoints', or left menu → 'Online prediction' → 'Endpoints') and click your gemma-test-endpoint.","In the list of deployed models on that endpoint, click the three-dot menu (⋮) next to your model and choose 'Undeploy model' (or 'Remove'). Confirm. This releases the GPU and stops the hourly charge.","Once nothing is deployed on the endpoint, delete the empty endpoint itself: from the Endpoints list, click the three-dot menu (⋮) for the endpoint and choose 'Delete endpoint'. Confirm.","Optional tidy-up: under 'Model registry' you can also delete the uploaded model copy if one was created — it does not cost money to keep, but removing it keeps things clean.","Double-check nothing is left running: the Endpoints page should show no endpoint in a 'Deployed' state. Peace of mind is the goal."],"commands":["# Optional command-line equivalent (the console does the same thing by clicking):\ngcloud ai endpoints undeploy-model ENDPOINT_ID \\\n  --project=PROJECT_ID --region=us-central1 \\\n  --deployed-model-id=DEPLOYED_MODEL_ID\n\ngcloud ai endpoints delete ENDPOINT_ID \\\n  --project=PROJECT_ID --region=us-central1"],"check":"your Endpoints list shows nothing in a 'Deployed' state (the endpoint is gone or empty), which means the GPU is released and the hourly billing has stopped."}],"resources":[{"label":"Model Garden (open it in the console)","url":"https://console.cloud.google.com/vertex-ai/model-garden"},{"label":"Overview of Model Garden — official docs","url":"https://docs.cloud.google.com/gemini-enterprise-agent-platform/models/model-garden/explore-models"},{"label":"Use models in Model Garden — official docs","url":"https://docs.cloud.google.com/gemini-enterprise-agent-platform/models/model-garden/use-models"},{"label":"Tutorial: Deploy and inference Gemma from Model Garden — official docs","url":"https://docs.cloud.google.com/gemini-enterprise-agent-platform/models/model-garden/deploy-and-inference-tutorial"},{"label":"Vertex AI → Gemini Enterprise Agent Platform name changes — official docs","url":"https://docs.cloud.google.com/gemini-enterprise-agent-platform/vertex-ai-name-changes"},{"label":"Google Cloud Free Trial ($300 / 90 days) — details and eligibility","url":"https://cloud.google.com/free"}],"cloudTieIn":"This is the cloud mirror of your local Engines labs: the very same open models you run privately with Ollama or LM Studio — Gemma, Llama, and friends — are here in Model Garden, except they run on Google's GPUs instead of your laptop. The difference is who pays and who holds the data: locally, models are free-per-use and your text never leaves your machine; in Model Garden, Google supplies far bigger hardware but bills you by the hour for a deployed endpoint and processes your prompts on their servers. Use this lab to understand what a production cloud platform offers, then decide per task whether the privacy and zero-per-use cost of local (your other labs) or the raw scale of the cloud is the right call.","troubleshooting":[{"symptom":"The 'Enable' button is greyed out, or you get a 'permission denied' / 'you do not have access' message.","fix":"Two common causes. First, billing may not be linked to your project — go to the ☰ menu → 'Billing' and make sure your free-trial billing account is attached. Second, on a school or work Google account you might not have the 'Owner' or 'Editor' role; use a personal Gmail account for this lab, or ask your Google Workspace admin to grant access."},{"symptom":"Deployment fails with an error about 'quota', 'resources exhausted', or 'no GPUs available in this region'.","fix":"New accounts start with little or no GPU quota, and popular regions run out of chips. Try a different region (for example switch from 'us-central1' to 'us-east1' or 'europe-west4') in the Deploy pane, or pick the smallest machine type. If it still fails, open ☰ menu → 'IAM & Admin' → 'Quotas', search for the GPU type, and request a small increase — approval can take minutes to a day."},{"symptom":"The endpoint sits on 'Deploying' with a spinner for a long time.","fix":"This is normal — first-time deployment of an open model commonly takes 10–20 minutes while Google reserves hardware and loads the model. Leave the page and check back on the Endpoints list. If it fails after ~30 minutes, it usually points to the quota/region issue above; undeploy anything half-created and try another region or a smaller model."},{"symptom":"You are worried you will be charged, or a bill/credit-drop appears unexpectedly.","fix":"A managed model like Gemini in the 'Try it' panel costs only pennies per prompt (covered by trial credit). The real cost is a DEPLOYED endpoint, which bills per hour until you undeploy it (step 9). If you deployed and walked away, go undeploy the model and delete the endpoint now. To sleep easy, set a budget alert: ☰ menu → 'Billing' → 'Budgets & alerts' → 'Create budget', set a small amount like $5, and Google will email you if you approach it."},{"symptom":"You cannot find the free trial, or the console asks you to pay / says you are on a paid account.","fix":"The $300 / 90-day trial is one-per-person and only for people who have never been a paying user of Google Cloud, Firebase, or Google Maps Platform. If you have used it before, you will not see the offer. You can still do the lab on a normal paid account — just be extra diligent about step 9 and set a budget alert, since there is no credit cushion."},{"symptom":"The menu says 'Gemini Enterprise Agent Platform' but this lab (or a link) says 'Vertex AI', and you're not sure they match.","fix":"They are the same product. Google renamed Vertex AI to Gemini Enterprise Agent Platform in spring 2026, and Vertex AI Studio to Agent Studio. Model Garden kept its name and sits under the 'Models' area. The old name still appears in the API (aiplatform.googleapis.com) and in older /vertex-ai/ links, which all still work. Follow the icons and the 'Model Garden' label, and use the top search bar if a menu item has moved."}],"tips":["The single rule that saves you money: undeploy your endpoint the moment you finish (step 9). A forgotten GPU endpoint is the most common way beginners run up an unexpected cloud bill. If in doubt, delete it — redeploying later takes one click.","Explore for free before you spend. Testing Gemini in the 'Try it' panel and browsing every model card costs essentially nothing, so play there as long as you like; only deploying an open model turns on the hourly meter.","Set a budget alert on day one: Billing → 'Budgets & alerts' → create a $5 budget. It will not stop charges, but it emails you early so nothing sneaks up on you.","Deploy small first. Pick the smallest model size (like Gemma 3 1B) and the default/smallest machine for your first deployment — it is cheaper, faster to start, and enough to prove the whole flow works.","Names changed in 2026: 'Vertex AI' is now 'Gemini Enterprise Agent Platform' and 'Vertex AI Studio' is now 'Agent Studio', but Model Garden kept its name. If a link or the API still says 'Vertex AI', it is the same thing — follow the icons and buttons, and use the top search bar to find anything that moved.","Region matters for both cost and availability. GPUs are scarcer and sometimes pricier in some regions; if a deployment will not start, changing the region is the fastest fix."],"difficulty":"Beginner — no coding needed; runs entirely in your browser. A few optional copy-paste commands are included for the curious.","time":"About 30–45 minutes (deploying the open model takes 10–20 minutes on Google's side, during which you can step away)."},{"id":"lab24","n":24,"cat":"S","title":"Build Your First AI Agent with Microsoft Copilot Studio","tagline":"Describe an AI assistant in plain English, ground it in your own website or documents, test it live, and publish it to a demo site or Microsoft Teams — all without writing code.","whatItIs":"Microsoft Copilot Studio is a low-code, browser-based studio for building custom AI \"agents\" (chat assistants) without programming. You describe what you want in plain language, point it at trusted information, and Copilot Studio generates a working agent's name, description, and instructions that you can test and share.","whyUseIt":"It lets a non-technical person stand up a genuinely useful, grounded AI assistant — for a class, a help desk, or an FAQ — in minutes, and share it on a website or in Microsoft Teams. It is one of the fastest ways to feel how modern \"agent\" tools turn a description plus a knowledge source into a working product.","bestFor":"Beginners who want a hands-on first taste of building and shipping an AI agent, and educators or teams who want a shareable question-and-answer assistant grounded in their own website or documents.","platforms":["Any modern web browser: Chrome 91+ (recommended), Microsoft Edge (Chromium-based)","Firefox 89+ and Safari 16.4+ are also officially supported","No install required — Copilot Studio runs entirely in the cloud"],"prerequisites":["A Microsoft 365 work or school account, or a free Copilot Studio trial. Personal email addresses (Gmail, Outlook.com) are typically rejected during trial sign-up — a work or school account is required.","To publish and share: a standalone Copilot Studio subscription, or the Copilot Studio for Teams plan included in select Microsoft 365 subscriptions. The free trial lets you build and test but NOT publish.","A trusted public website URL (not login-protected), or a document (PDF, Word, PowerPoint, or text) to use as your agent's knowledge.","About 25-35 minutes and a stable internet connection."],"steps":[{"title":"Open Copilot Studio and sign in (or start a free trial)","detail":"Copilot Studio is a website — nothing to install. You sign in with a Microsoft work or school account, or start a free trial. Note: personal Gmail or Outlook.com addresses are usually rejected during trial sign-up, so a work or school Microsoft 365 account works best. The trial can be extended by 30 days when it nears expiry, and your agent keeps working for up to 90 days after the trial expires.","do":["In Chrome or Edge, go to copilotstudio.microsoft.com and sign in with your Microsoft 365 work or school account.","If you don't have an account, open the sign-up page (link below), enter your email address, select Next, and follow the instructions to start your free trial.","Wait for the Home page to finish loading."],"commands":["https://copilotstudio.microsoft.com","https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkId=2107702"],"check":"You land on the Copilot Studio Home page and see a box inviting you to describe what your agent should do."},{"title":"Describe your agent in plain English","detail":"Instead of building screen by screen, you tell Copilot Studio what you want in a sentence or two. Its built-in AI generates a working agent — writing the name, description, and instructions (the agent's standing rules) for you.","do":["Click inside the 'Describe your agent' box on the Home page.","Type one or two plain sentences describing the agent's job AND its tone. The description can be up to 1,024 characters (about a paragraph).","Press Enter, or select the send/submit arrow.","Wait up to a minute or so while Copilot Studio provisions (sets up) your agent. It may suggest a name, triggers, knowledge, and tools — you can ignore, accept, or dismiss these suggestions; they don't persist beyond this session unless you accept them."],"commands":["Help users learn how to create agents with Copilot Studio. Answer like a kind, patient teacher and keep replies short."],"check":"A new page for your agent appears showing an auto-generated Name, Description, and Instructions."},{"title":"Review and rename your agent","detail":"You now land on your agent's main page. In the classic experience this is the Overview page. In the new experience it is the Build tab (the top tabs read Build, Preview, Evaluate, Monitor). Everything here is editable — nothing is locked in.","do":["Find the Name field near the top and change it to something clear, for example 'Copilot Studio Guide.'","Read the Instructions box. These are the agent's standing rules (its 'system prompt'). Adjust the wording if you want a different tone or focus.","Your edits save automatically, or select Save if a Save button is shown."],"commands":[],"check":"Your chosen name shows at the top of the page and your edited instructions stay in the Instructions box."},{"title":"Add a public website as a knowledge source","detail":"A 'knowledge source' is the material your agent is allowed to read when answering — this is called grounding. Public-website knowledge uses Bing search, so the site must be publicly viewable and indexed (login-protected sites like SharePoint or wikis aren't supported), and the URL can be at most two levels deep.","do":["Find the Knowledge section (on the Overview or Knowledge page in the classic experience; on the Build tab in the new experience).","Select Add knowledge.","Select Public websites.","Enter a website address, for example learn.microsoft.com/copilot-studio. Optionally add a name and a description.","Select Add to agent. The source now appears in the Knowledge list."],"commands":["https://learn.microsoft.com/copilot-studio"],"check":"The website appears as an item in your agent's Knowledge list."},{"title":"(Optional) Upload your own documents","detail":"You can also feed the agent your own files — like a PDF handbook or a Word FAQ. This is great for information that isn't on a public website.","do":["In the same Knowledge section, select Add knowledge again.","Choose the Files option.","Pick a document from your computer (PDF, Word, PowerPoint, or plain text) and confirm the upload.","Wait for the file's status to finish preparing/indexing before asking questions about it."],"commands":[],"check":"Your file appears in the Knowledge list and its status changes from preparing to ready/available."},{"title":"Test your agent in the test pane","detail":"The test chat is a live conversation where you talk to your agent exactly as a real user would — before anyone else sees it. In the classic experience it is the 'Test your agent' panel on the right; in the new experience it is the Preview tab.","do":["Open the 'Test your agent' panel (classic) or the Preview tab (new experience).","Type a real question your agent should be able to answer and press Enter.","Read the reply. Check that it answers from your knowledge source and matches the tone you intended.","If replies seem stale after you change something, select the 'Start new test session' (refresh) icon at the top of the panel to begin a fresh chat."],"commands":["How do I add a knowledge source to my agent?"],"check":"The agent replies with an on-topic answer that reflects your knowledge source and tone."},{"title":"Refine the instructions and greeting, then re-test","detail":"The fastest way to improve an agent is: change something, test, repeat. Two easy wins are the instructions (overall behavior) and, in the classic experience, the greeting (the agent's first message).","do":["To change behavior: go back to the Instructions box, adjust it (for example add 'Always answer in three short bullet points.'), and save.","To change the first message (classic experience): in the 'Test your agent' chat, select the agent's introductory message. The Conversation Start topic opens with its Message node in focus.","Select the message text, replace it with your own welcome message, and select Save.","Select the 'Start new test session' (refresh) icon, then ask another question to see the difference."],"commands":["Hello, I'm here to help you learn how to use Microsoft Copilot Studio. You can ask me things like: \"What is an agent?\" or \"How do I add knowledge?\""],"check":"A fresh test session opens with your new greeting and the agent's answers reflect your updated instructions."},{"title":"Publish your agent","detail":"Publishing takes your latest changes live so they can appear in a 'channel' (a place people actually use the agent). Important: the free trial lets you create and test but NOT publish — publishing needs a standalone Copilot Studio subscription or a qualifying Microsoft 365 (Copilot Studio for Teams) plan.","do":["At the top of the page, select Publish.","In the 'Publish this agent' confirmation message, select Publish again.","Wait a few seconds for a green success banner to appear at the top of the page.","If Publish is unavailable, your account is likely a trial — see Troubleshooting to move to a licensed account or the Teams plan."],"commands":[],"check":"A green banner confirms the agent published successfully."},{"title":"Share it: a demo website or Microsoft Teams","detail":"A 'channel' is where your published agent lives for other people. The quickest way to share is a demo website (a ready-made test page with a link). To reach coworkers, add it to Microsoft Teams.","do":["Demo website (classic experience): at the top of the page select the three dots (…), then Go to demo website. Copy the page URL and send it to someone to try. (Depending on who you want to reach, you may need to adjust the demo website's authentication settings.)","Microsoft Teams: on the top menu bar select Channels, then select the 'Teams and Microsoft 365 Copilot' tile.","Optionally keep 'Make agent available in Microsoft 365 Copilot' selected, then select Add channel.","Select See agent in Teams, then Add to install it for yourself. To let others install it, select Availability options, then Copy link, and share that link with coworkers who have access to the agent."],"commands":[],"check":"You can open your agent from the demo website link (or from within Teams) and chat with it as a real user."}],"resources":[{"label":"Quickstart: Create and deploy an agent in the classic experience (Microsoft Learn)","url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/microsoft-copilot-studio/fundamentals-get-started"},{"label":"Get access to Copilot Studio — trial & licensing (Microsoft Learn)","url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/microsoft-copilot-studio/requirements-licensing-subscriptions"},{"label":"Add a public website as a knowledge source (Microsoft Learn)","url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/microsoft-copilot-studio/knowledge-add-public-website"},{"label":"Connect and configure an agent for Teams and Microsoft 365 Copilot","url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/microsoft-copilot-studio/publication-add-bot-to-microsoft-teams"},{"label":"What is Microsoft Copilot Studio? (Overview)","url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/microsoft-copilot-studio/fundamentals-what-is-copilot-studio"},{"label":"Sign in to Copilot Studio","url":"https://copilotstudio.microsoft.com"}],"cloudTieIn":"This is the cloud counterpart to the local, in-browser labs on this site: instead of running a small model on your own machine, you use Microsoft's hosted AI to build and \"ground\" an agent in your own sources. It's the same retrieval-and-instruction ideas from the local RAG and prompt-engineering labs, now on a managed enterprise platform you can share with real users.","troubleshooting":[{"symptom":"Sign-up rejects my email address.","fix":"Copilot Studio trials usually reject personal addresses (Gmail, Outlook.com). Use a work or school Microsoft 365 account instead. If you get a message that sign-up couldn't be completed, your organization's IT admin likely disabled self-service sign-up — ask them to enable it."},{"symptom":"The Home page has no box asking me to describe my agent.","fix":"Your environment doesn't support agent creation using natural language. Switch to a supported environment using the environment picker, or use the manual Create path described in the Microsoft Learn 'Create an agent' documentation."},{"symptom":"The Publish button won't let me publish.","fix":"A free trial can create and test but not publish. Ask your admin for a standalone Copilot Studio subscription, or use the Copilot Studio for Teams plan included in select Microsoft 365 subscriptions to publish to Teams."},{"symptom":"My agent ignores the website or documents I added.","fix":"Confirm the knowledge source finished indexing, then select the 'Start new test session' (refresh) icon so the chat picks up the change. Public-website knowledge uses Bing, so login-protected sites (SharePoint, wikis), un-indexed pages, URLs deeper than two levels, or sites that redirect to a different top-level domain won't be read."},{"symptom":"Changes I made don't show up in the test chat.","fix":"Save your edits, then select the 'Start new test session' icon at the top of the test panel. Ongoing conversations keep using the previous version until you restart them (in Teams, enter 'Start over')."}],"tips":["Write instructions like you'd brief a new employee: state the agent's job, its tone, what to do when it doesn't know an answer, and any topics to avoid.","Add one trusted knowledge source first and test it before adding more — that makes it easy to see where each answer is coming from.","Public-website URLs can be at most two levels deep (for example www.contoso.com/docs/guide) and must be publicly indexed by Bing, so pick a specific, public section of a site.","Use Chrome or Edge, and keep only one Copilot Studio tab open at a time to avoid editing conflicts.","Your trial agent keeps working for up to 90 days after the trial ends, and you can extend the trial by 30 days, so you have time to explore before committing to a paid license.","Test with the exact messy, vague questions real users would ask — that's how you find and fix weak spots.","Give the agent a clear name and a warm greeting; it's the first thing users see and it sets their expectations."],"difficulty":"Beginner — no coding needed; runs entirely in your browser","time":"About 25-35 minutes"},{"id":"lab25","n":25,"cat":"A","title":"Build a Telegram Bot Agent Powered by Your Local AI","tagline":"Text a chatbot on your phone and have it answered by the AI model running on your own computer — no cloud, no monthly bill, no data leaving your machine.","whatItIs":"A focused, self-contained build. You will create a Telegram bot (a chat account run by a program instead of a person), then write a short, fully copy-paste Python script that wires that bot to the Ollama model already running on your computer. You text the bot from Telegram; the script hands your message to your local model at http://localhost:11434 and texts the answer back. It is a single, dedicated bot built the most direct beginner-friendly way, so you can see exactly how each piece connects.","whyUseIt":"It turns the AI running privately on your computer into something you can reach from your phone anywhere you have internet — a genuinely useful personal assistant that costs nothing to run and keeps your conversations on your own hardware. Along the way you learn the core loop that every AI agent is built from: receive an input, send it to a model, return the model's output. That receive to model to reply pattern is the same whether you are building a toy bot or a production agent.","bestFor":"Motivated beginners who already have Ollama working (from lab1) and want their first real, useful, always-private AI project — one they can actually text from their phone — without needing to know how to code beyond copying a short script and running one command.","platforms":["Windows 10/11","macOS","Linux","Any desktop/laptop that can run Ollama + Python 3.9 or newer","Plus the free Telegram app on your phone or desktop"],"prerequisites":["Ollama already installed and running, with at least one model pulled (for example llama3.2). If you have not done this, complete lab1 (Local AI Setup) first.","Python 3.9 or newer installed on the same computer that runs Ollama.","A free Telegram account (the phone or desktop app), which you will use to create the bot and to chat with it.","Comfort copying a short script into a text file and running one command in a terminal (Command Prompt / PowerShell on Windows, Terminal on macOS/Linux). No prior coding required."],"steps":[{"title":"Meet your bot: the plan","detail":"You are going to build a tiny messenger between two things you may already have: Telegram (the free chat app) and Ollama (the AI model running on your own computer). A 'bot' is simply a Telegram account controlled by a program instead of a human. Your program will do three jobs, over and over: (1) receive whatever you text the bot, (2) hand that text to your local model, and (3) text the model's answer back to you. Nothing leaves your computer except the words you choose to send to Telegram. This is deliberately different from lab12 (OpenClaw), which is a no-code, multi-channel agent with built-in governance and guardrails. Here you hand-build one dedicated Telegram bot from scratch so the moving parts are fully visible.","do":["Read the three jobs your script will do until you can say them from memory.","Note the one key difference from lab12: this is a single, hand-coded, Telegram-only bot, not a no-code multi-channel platform.","Decide roughly which local model you want to use (you will confirm the exact name in the next step)."],"commands":[],"check":"You can state, in your own words, the three jobs of your script: receive a message, ask the local model, send the reply back."},{"title":"Make sure your local AI is awake","detail":"The bot is useless if the model is not running, so confirm that first. Ollama runs a small web server on your computer at http://localhost:11434. ('localhost' just means 'this very computer', and 11434 is the door number, called a port.) On the Mac/Windows app, Ollama usually starts automatically; on Linux or if it is not running, `ollama serve` starts it. You also need at least one model downloaded ('pulled'). If any of this fails, pause and do lab1 first.","do":["Start Ollama: open the Ollama app, or run `ollama serve` in a terminal and leave it open.","List the models you have already pulled.","Send the model a quick test message from the terminal to prove it responds.","Write down the exact model name shown by `ollama list` (for example llama3.2) — you will paste it into the script later."],"commands":["ollama list","ollama run llama3.2 \"Say hello in one short sentence.\"","# Optional raw API test (macOS/Linux). On Windows PowerShell, just trust the 'ollama run' test above:\ncurl http://localhost:11434/api/chat -d '{\"model\":\"llama3.2\",\"messages\":[{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":\"hello\"}],\"stream\":false}'"],"check":"`ollama list` shows at least one model, and `ollama run` prints a sentence back. You have the model's exact name written down."},{"title":"Create your bot and copy its token (@BotFather)","detail":"Telegram hands out new bots through an official bot named @BotFather. You chat with it exactly like a person, and it walks you through naming your bot. At the end it gives you a token: a long secret string (something like 123456789:AAE-xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx) that is essentially your bot's password. Anyone who has it can control your bot, so treat it like a password from this moment on.","do":["Open Telegram and search for @BotFather. Pick the one with the blue verified checkmark — that is the only official one.","Open the chat and send the command /newbot.","When asked, type a friendly display name (what people see), e.g. 'My Local AI'.","When asked for a username, type something unique that MUST end in the word 'bot', e.g. 'my_local_ai_bot'.","Copy the token BotFather sends back and keep it somewhere private (not a group chat, not a screenshot you share)."],"commands":["/newbot","/mybots   # later, to manage or find your bot again","/revoke   # only if your token ever leaks: this cancels it and issues a new one"],"check":"You have a token in the form 123456789:AA... and tapping the t.me link BotFather gave you opens a chat with your new (currently silent) bot."},{"title":"Install Python and the two libraries","detail":"Python is the language of our script. You most likely already have it (it is a prerequisite). The script needs two small add-on libraries: 'python-telegram-bot' (the current, well-maintained library for talking to Telegram — v22 as of 2026) and 'requests' (a simple way to talk to Ollama's web server). 'pip' is Python's built-in installer. Note: the command might be `python`, `python3`, or `py` on your system, and `pip` might be `pip3` — use whichever your computer recognizes.","do":["Confirm your Python version is 3.9 or newer.","Install both libraries with pip.","Confirm they imported correctly."],"commands":["python --version   # need 3.9+  (try 'python3 --version' or 'py --version' if 'python' isn't found)","pip install \"python-telegram-bot\" requests   # or: python -m pip install \"python-telegram-bot\" requests","python -c \"import telegram, requests; print('libraries OK')\""],"check":"pip finishes without red error text, and the last command prints 'libraries OK'."},{"title":"Save the bot script","detail":"This is the whole program — about 30 lines, and every line is explained by a comment. Create a new plain-text file named telegram_local_ai.py and paste in the code below. Then change just three things at the top: paste your BotFather token into TELEGRAM_TOKEN, set OLLAMA_MODEL to the exact model name from Step 2, and leave ALLOWED_CHAT_ID as 0 for now (you will lock it down in Step 7). The function ask_local_ai sends your text to Ollama's /api/chat endpoint and reads the reply out of message.content; the function handle_message runs every time you text the bot, prints the sender's chat id to your terminal, and replies with the model's answer.","do":["Create a new file called telegram_local_ai.py in a folder you can find (for example your Desktop).","Paste in the full script below.","Replace PASTE-YOUR-BOTFATHER-TOKEN-HERE with your real token, keeping the quotes.","Set OLLAMA_MODEL to the exact name from `ollama list` (e.g. \"llama3.2\").","Leave ALLOWED_CHAT_ID = 0 for now, and save the file."],"commands":["# telegram_local_ai.py — a private Telegram bot powered by your local Ollama model.\nimport requests\nfrom telegram import Update\nfrom telegram.ext import Application, MessageHandler, ContextTypes, filters\n\n# ---- Settings you edit ----\nTELEGRAM_TOKEN = \"PASTE-YOUR-BOTFATHER-TOKEN-HERE\"   # from @BotFather (keep it secret!)\nALLOWED_CHAT_ID = 0        # 0 for now; you'll paste YOUR numeric id here in Step 7\nOLLAMA_MODEL = \"llama3.2\"  # must match a name from `ollama list`\nOLLAMA_URL = \"http://localhost:11434/api/chat\"   # your local AI, on this computer\n\n\ndef ask_local_ai(user_text: str) -> str:\n    \"\"\"Send the user's text to the local model and return its reply.\"\"\"\n    payload = {\n        \"model\": OLLAMA_MODEL,\n        \"messages\": [{\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": user_text}],\n        \"stream\": False,   # get one complete answer instead of a live stream\n    }\n    response = requests.post(OLLAMA_URL, json=payload, timeout=120)\n    response.raise_for_status()\n    return response.json()[\"message\"][\"content\"]\n\n\nasync def handle_message(update: Update, context: ContextTypes.DEFAULT_TYPE) -> None:\n    \"\"\"Runs every time someone texts the bot.\"\"\"\n    chat_id = update.effective_chat.id\n    print(f\"Message from chat id: {chat_id}\")   # <-- read this to learn YOUR id\n\n    # Safety gate: once ALLOWED_CHAT_ID is set, ignore everyone but you.\n    if ALLOWED_CHAT_ID and chat_id != ALLOWED_CHAT_ID:\n        return\n\n    reply = ask_local_ai(update.message.text)\n    await update.message.reply_text(reply)\n\n\ndef main() -> None:\n    app = Application.builder().token(TELEGRAM_TOKEN).build()\n    app.add_handler(MessageHandler(filters.TEXT & ~filters.COMMAND, handle_message))\n    print(\"Bot is running. Press Ctrl+C to stop.\")\n    app.run_polling()\n\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    main()"],"check":"The file is saved as telegram_local_ai.py, your real token sits between the quotes on the TELEGRAM_TOKEN line, and OLLAMA_MODEL exactly matches a name from `ollama list`."},{"title":"Start the bot and say hi from your phone","detail":"Now run the script. It will 'poll' Telegram, meaning it repeatedly asks Telegram 'any new messages for me?' and reacts when one arrives. Keep this terminal window open — the bot only lives while the script is running. Then open Telegram and message your bot. The very first reply can take several seconds while Ollama loads the model into memory; after that, replies are quicker.","do":["In a terminal, move to the folder with your file and run the script.","Wait for the line 'Bot is running.'","In Telegram, open your bot's chat and send it a message like 'Hello, who are you?'","Wait for the reply, then look at your terminal — it printed a line like 'Message from chat id: 123456789'."],"commands":["python telegram_local_ai.py","# (leave this running; open Telegram and text your bot)"],"check":"Your bot replies in Telegram with text your local model generated, and the terminal shows a 'Message from chat id: <number>' line. Copy that number — you need it next."},{"title":"Lock the door: only you can use the bot","detail":"Right now, anyone who discovers your bot's @username could chat with it — and that means using your computer's AI and your electricity. The fix is one line: paste your own numeric chat id (the number the terminal printed in Step 6) into ALLOWED_CHAT_ID. After that, the bot silently ignores every message whose chat id is not yours. This is the single most important safety step in the whole lab.","do":["Stop the bot with Ctrl+C in the terminal.","Open telegram_local_ai.py and set ALLOWED_CHAT_ID to your own numeric id from Step 6 (a plain number, no quotes).","Save the file, then start the bot again.","Send it a message to confirm you still get replies. (Optional: ask a friend to message the bot — they should get no answer at all.)"],"commands":["ALLOWED_CHAT_ID = 123456789   # <-- replace with YOUR numeric id from the terminal","python telegram_local_ai.py"],"check":"You still receive replies, but any other person messaging the bot gets nothing, because their chat id does not match ALLOWED_CHAT_ID."},{"title":"Make it truly yours","detail":"Two easy upgrades. First, give your bot a personality by adding a 'system' message — a standing instruction the model follows on every reply. Second, swap models any time by changing one line (OLLAMA_MODEL) to another name from `ollama list`. And here is the privacy point worth internalizing: the thinking happens 100% on your computer. There is no OpenAI, Anthropic, or any cloud AI key anywhere in this file — the only internet used is Telegram's own delivery of your text messages. The model itself never phones home.","do":["To add a personality, replace the messages list inside ask_local_ai with the version below (note the added 'system' line).","To try a different brain, change OLLAMA_MODEL to another model you have pulled and restart.","Confirm for yourself that the file contains no cloud AI API key — proof the reasoning is fully local."],"commands":["# Give your bot a persona: swap the \"messages\" list in ask_local_ai for this:\n    \"messages\": [\n        {\"role\": \"system\", \"content\": \"You are a concise, friendly assistant. Keep answers short.\"},\n        {\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": user_text},\n    ],"],"check":"After editing and restarting, the bot's tone or the model's answers change as expected, and you can confirm there is no cloud AI key in the file — only your local Ollama URL."},{"title":"Run it anytime, and where to go next","detail":"You now own a working, private AI bot. To use it: start the script, keep the terminal open, and text away; press Ctrl+C to stop. It answers only while your computer is on and the script is running. When you outgrow a single hand-coded Telegram bot — say you want the same assistant on WhatsApp, Slack, and Discord at once, with logging, guardrails, and approval rules, and without writing code — that is exactly what lab12 (OpenClaw) is for. This lab showed you the machinery by hand; OpenClaw is the governed, multi-channel version of the same idea.","do":["Practice stopping (Ctrl+C) and restarting (run the command again) the bot.","Remember the bot is live only while the script runs — close the terminal and it goes quiet.","When you want multi-channel reach plus governance without code, move on to lab12 (OpenClaw).","Explore the site's other Agents & Automation labs to keep building."],"commands":["python telegram_local_ai.py   # start whenever you want to use the bot","# Ctrl+C in the terminal to stop it"],"check":"You can confidently stop and restart your bot, and you understand it only responds while your computer and the script are running."}],"resources":[{"label":"Telegram — From BotFather to 'Hello World' (official bot tutorial)","url":"https://core.telegram.org/bots/tutorial"},{"label":"Telegram — Bots: an introduction for developers (official)","url":"https://core.telegram.org/bots"},{"label":"python-telegram-bot — official project site","url":"https://python-telegram-bot.org/"},{"label":"python-telegram-bot — Echo Bot example (current v22)","url":"https://docs.python-telegram-bot.org/en/stable/examples.echobot.html"},{"label":"Ollama — API reference (the /api/chat endpoint)","url":"https://github.com/ollama/ollama/blob/main/docs/api.md"},{"label":"Ollama — Streaming and chat API docs","url":"https://docs.ollama.com/api/streaming"}],"cloudTieIn":"Think of this lab and lab12 (OpenClaw) as two ends of the same idea. Here you hand-built one dedicated Telegram bot with a short Python script, so every step of the receive-to-model-to-reply loop is visible. OpenClaw is the no-code, multi-channel alternative: it connects the same kind of local (or cloud) model to Telegram, WhatsApp, Slack, Discord and more at once, and adds the governance layer a hand-coded bot lacks — logging, guardrails, rate limits, and approval rules. Do this lab to understand the machinery; graduate to OpenClaw when you want that machinery managed for you across many channels. Everything here also builds directly on lab1 (Local AI Setup), which got Ollama and your first model running, and it reinforces the same local-first, privacy-preserving philosophy behind the rest of the site's Agents & Automation track — your model, your computer, your data.","troubleshooting":[{"symptom":"The bot stays completely silent — no reply in Telegram, no error in the terminal.","fix":"Make sure the script is actually running (you should see 'Bot is running.'). Then confirm you are messaging the exact bot username you created. If ALLOWED_CHAT_ID is set, verify it matches the number the terminal prints for your messages — a mismatch makes the bot ignore you on purpose."},{"symptom":"On startup you get an error like 'InvalidToken' or 'Unauthorized'.","fix":"The TELEGRAM_TOKEN is wrong. Re-copy it from BotFather with no extra spaces or line breaks, keep it inside the quotes, and make sure you did not accidentally delete a character. If it may have leaked, send /revoke to BotFather and paste the fresh token."},{"symptom":"The terminal shows a connection error such as 'Connection refused' to localhost:11434.","fix":"Ollama is not running. Open the Ollama app, or run `ollama serve` in a separate terminal and leave it open, then restart the bot. Confirm with `ollama list` that the server responds."},{"symptom":"You get a reply, but it errors with a model / 404 'model not found' message, or the reply is nonsense.","fix":"OLLAMA_MODEL does not match a model you have pulled. Run `ollama list` and copy an exact name into OLLAMA_MODEL (for example \"llama3.2\"). If you have not pulled any model, run `ollama pull llama3.2` first."},{"symptom":"The bot ignores you even after you set ALLOWED_CHAT_ID.","fix":"Use the numeric id (a plain number like 123456789), not the @username, and enter it with no quotes. Re-read the 'Message from chat id:' line the terminal printed for YOUR own message and paste that exact integer, then restart the bot."},{"symptom":"Running the script fails with 'ModuleNotFoundError: No module named telegram' (or 'requests').","fix":"The libraries were installed into a different Python than the one running the script. Reinstall using the matching interpreter: `python -m pip install \"python-telegram-bot\" requests`, and start the bot with that same `python` command."}],"tips":["Guard the token like a password: never paste it in a group chat, put it in a screenshot you share, or commit it to a public GitHub repo. If it ever leaks, send /revoke to BotFather to cancel it and get a new one. For anything beyond a personal toy, load it from an environment variable instead of hard-coding it.","Always keep ALLOWED_CHAT_ID set to your own numeric id. Without it, anyone who stumbles onto your bot's username can use your computer's AI and your electricity — the one-line filter is your whole security model.","The first reply after a quiet period is slow because Ollama has to load the model into memory; later replies are fast. Ollama keeps the model 'warm' for about 5 minutes by default (the keep_alive setting), so rapid follow-up questions feel snappy.","The AI reasoning is 100% local — there is no cloud AI key in your script. The only thing that uses the internet is Telegram delivering your text, so this will not work fully offline, but your prompts and the model's answers are computed entirely on your machine.","Smaller models reply faster and use less memory; larger models are smarter but slower. Swap between any models you have pulled by changing the single OLLAMA_MODEL line and restarting.","When you want the same assistant across many channels (WhatsApp, Slack, Discord) with logging, guardrails, and approval rules — and without writing code — move up to lab12 (OpenClaw), the governed multi-channel version of what you just built by hand."],"difficulty":"Intermediate — comfortable copying a short script and running one terminal command; no prior coding needed.","time":"About 30–45 minutes"}];
